GBIF description: Africa
Wikipedia summary: Pelargonium capitatum is one of several species known as rose geranium or rose-scented pelargonium in English. The popular names refer to the scent of the essential oils extracted from glandular tissue, not the flowers, which have hardly any scent to speak of. Some of the species are known as kusmalva in Afrikaans.
Distribution: Bogotá (INTRODUCED); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Bermuda (INTRODUCED); California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Cape Provinces; KwaZulu-Natal; Tasmania (INTRODUCED); Tristan da Cunha (INTRODUCED); Spain [c]; Madeira [I]; Canary Isl. [I] (Lanzarote [I]); South Africa (KwaZulu-Natal, W-Cape Prov., E-Cape Prov.); Taiwan [I]; India [c]; Australia [I] (Western Australia [I], New South Wales [I]); USA [I] (California [I]); Colombia [I]; AU (PRESENT); Belgium (PRESENT); Flemish Region (PRESENT); BR (MANAGED); Cundinamarca (MANAGED); IN (PRESENT); Santa Maria Island (PRESENT); PT (PRESENT); Hawaii (PRESENT)
