9,Mercurialis annua L.,Mercurialis annua,Mercurialis,Euphorbiaceae,annua,L.,,Not assessed,3062975,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Mercurialis annua,https://www.gbif.org/species/3062975,Annual Dog's Mercury; Annual Mercury; French mercury; herb mercury; mockery; stinkweed,"Lectotype (Radcliffe-Smith in Meikle, Fl. Cyprus 2: 1451. 1985): Herb. Linn. No. 1188.3 (LINN).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part M),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania; Algeria; Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Argentina South (INTRODUCED); Ascension (INTRODUCED); Austria; Azores; Bahamas (INTRODUCED); Baleares; Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Belarus; Belgium; Bermuda (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is.; Cape Provinces (INTRODUCED),habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Mercurialis annua,"Mercurialis annua, annual mercury, is a species of flowering plant in the spurge family Euphorbiaceae. It is native to the Middle East and the Mediterranean region, where it grows on bare, sandy soils. Its seeds are dispersed by harvester ants, which remove an oily coating that delays germination. In recent centuries, annual mercury has spread to northern Europe and many other parts of the world as an agricultural and urban weed. It has been studied for its complex genetics and breeding system. The name is from the Roman god Mercury, due to its association with fertility.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercurialis_annua,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Mercurialis+annua,"Lectotype (Radcliffe-Smith in Meikle, Fl. Cyprus 2: 1451. 1985): Herb. Linn. No. 1188.3 (LINN).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 9
