13,Ibicella lutea (Lindl.) Van Eselt.,Ibicella lutea,Ibicella,Martyniaceae,lutea,(Lindl.) Van Eselt.,,Not assessed,3172647,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Ibicella lutea,https://www.gbif.org/species/3172647,double-claw; pumpkinvine; unicorn-plant; Yellow Devil's Claw; Yellow Martynia; Yellow Unicorn-plant; Yellow-flower Devil's-claw,Southern America (WGSRPD:8),Manual of the Alien Plants of Belgium,eng,North America (PRESENT); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast; Argentina Northwest; Arizona (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Brazil Northeast; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; California (INTRODUCED); Cape Provinces (INTRODUCED); East Aegean Is. (INTRODUCED); Florida (INTRODUCED); France (INTRODUCED); Germany (INTRODUCED); KwaZulu-Natal (INTRODUCED); Mississippi (INTRODUCED); Northern Provinces (INTRODUCED); Paraguay,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Campo de Altitude""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Ibicella lutea,"Ibicella lutea is a species of flowering plant known by the common name yellow unicorn-plant. It grows in dry conditions, such as those in desert regions. It is native to South America, but has become established as a non-native species in various semi-arid regions around the world, including Southern Africa and the Central Valley of California. The plant is aromatic, with an unpleasant scent. It produces short, glandular hairs over most of its aerial surfaces and is coated in sticky resin. Insects often become stuck in the slimy exudate and die, but the plant does not have digestive enzymes and does not absorb nutrients from the insects. The plant can be considered protocarnivorous, but it is not carnivorous.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibicella_lutea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ibicella+lutea,Southern America (WGSRPD:8),GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 13
Scientific name: Ibicella lutea
Full species name: Ibicella lutea (Lindl.) Van Eselt.
Genus: Ibicella
Family: Martyniaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Ibicella lutea
Common names: double-claw; pumpkinvine; unicorn-plant; Yellow Devil's Claw; Yellow Martynia; Yellow Unicorn-plant; Yellow-flower Devil's-claw
GBIF description: Southern America (WGSRPD:8)
Wikipedia summary: Ibicella lutea is a species of flowering plant known by the common name yellow unicorn-plant. It grows in dry conditions, such as those in desert regions. It is native to South America, but has become established as a non-native species in various semi-arid regions around the world, including Southern Africa and the Central Valley of California. The plant is aromatic, with an unpleasant scent. It produces short, glandular hairs over most of its aerial surfaces and is coated in sticky resin. Insects often become stuck in the slimy exudate and die, but the plant does not have digestive enzymes and does not absorb nutrients from the insects. The plant can be considered protocarnivorous, but it is not carnivorous.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast; Argentina Northwest; Arizona (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Brazil Northeast; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; California (INTRODUCED); Cape Provinces (INTRODUCED); East Aegean Is. (INTRODUCED); Florida (INTRODUCED); France (INTRODUCED); Germany (INTRODUCED); KwaZulu-Natal (INTRODUCED); Mississippi (INTRODUCED); Northern Provinces (INTRODUCED); Paraguay
