Wikipedia summary: Lavandula dentata, the fringed lavender or French lavender, is a species of flowering plant in the family Lamiaceae, native to the Mediterranean basin, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Yemen, and the Arabian Peninsula. Growing to 60 cm (24 in) tall, it has gray-green, linear or lance-shaped leaves with toothed edges and a lightly woolly texture. The long-lasting, narrow spikes of purple flowers, topped with pale violet bracts, first appear in late spring. The whole plant is strongly aromatic with the typical lavender fragrance.
Distribution: Algeria; Baleares; Bulgaria (INTRODUCED); Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Cape Verde (INTRODUCED); Eritrea; Ethiopia; Greece (INTRODUCED); Italy (INTRODUCED); Madeira (INTRODUCED); Morocco; New Zealand North (INTRODUCED); Norfolk Is. (INTRODUCED); Palestine; Saudi Arabia; Sicilia (INTRODUCED); Spain; Tunisia (INTRODUCED); Yemen; E- & S-Spain; Gibraltar; Baleares; Italy [I]; Sicily [I]; Greece [I]; Morocco; Algeria; Madeira [I] (Madeira Isl. [I]); Canary Isl. (Lanzarote, Gran Canaria, Tenerife, La Gomera, La Palma); Cape Verde Isl. (Santo Antao Isl., Fogo Isl., Ilha Brava); Ethiopia; Eritrea; Saudi Arabia (Hejaz, C-Saudi Arabia, Asir); Yemen (W-Yemen); Australia [I] (Western Australia [I], South Australia [I]); New Zealand [I]; Chatham Isl. [I]
