26,Nephrolepis cordifolia (L.) C.Presl,Nephrolepis cordifolia,Nephrolepis,Nephrolepidaceae,cordifolia,(L.) C.Presl,,Not assessed,2650930,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Nephrolepis cordifolia,https://www.gbif.org/species/2650930,Boston fern; erect sword fern; fishbone fern; ladder fern; Ladder Sword Fern; Narrow sword fern; Narrow swordfern; sword fern; tuber fern; Tuber Ladder Fern; tuberous sword fern,"Habit, rhizome morphology. Plants forming tufts of 3 - 7 fronds. Runners 0.5 - 1.5 mm thick, branching angle divaricate. Scales on runners very sparse to dense, spreading or squarrose (occasionally). Tubers present or absent. Fronds to 40 - 120 by 2 - 6 cm, stipe 4 - 15 cm long. Lamina base strongly reduced, tapering over 10 - 25 cm, basal pinnae 4 - 10 cm long, 0.7 - 1.7 cm distant, middle pinnae slightly to distinctly falcate. Sterile pinnae 1 - 3.3 by 3 - 9 mm, herbaceous, thick, base slightly to strongly unequal, basiscopic base rounded or cordate, acroscopic base cordate, distinctly to strongly auricled, margin in basal part dentate, towards apex deeply dentate, apex rounded or obtuse. Fertile pinnae 1.6 - 3.2 by 0.4 - 0.8 cm, otherwise similar to sterile ones. Indument. Basal scales pseudopeltate, spreading, 8 by 1 mm, central part light brown, dull, margin in basal part irregularly lacerate, not hyaline, towards apex denticulate, without marginal glands, apex narrow, not long uniseriate. Rachis scales sparse or dense, spreading, light brown, with lacerate base and a well-developed protracted entire acumen. Scales on lamina absent. Hairs on lamina absent or sometimes present, costa absent. Sori medial, 6 - 15 pairs on fully fertile pinnae, elongated, not impressed. Indusium lunulate or broad, attached at broad base.",A conspectus of the native and naturalized species of Nephrolepis (Nephrolepidaceae) in the world,eng,"Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Bucaramanga | Charalá | El Peñón | Floridablanca | Girón | Los Santos | Tona; Parque Nacional Natural Tamá | Parque Nacional Natural Cocuy | Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (MANAGED); Subregiones: Cordillera occidental, Cordillera central, Norte, Zona central, Sur, Enclaves subxerofíticos; Amazonas, Antioquia, Boyacá, Caldas, Caquetá, Cauca, Chocó, Cundinamarca, Huila, Magdalena, Norte de Santander, Putumayo, Santander, Tolima, Valle del Cauca; Bogotá (INTRODUCED); Jardín Botánico de Bogotá; Otanche; Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Assam; Azores (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh; Belize (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED); Borneo","lifeForm: fern; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Campo de Altitude"",""Floresta Ciliar ou Galeria"",""Floresta de Terra Firme"",""Floresta Ombrófila (= Floresta Pluvial)"",""Floresta Ombrófila Mista"",""Vegetação Sobre Afloramentos Rochosos""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Nephrolepis cordifolia,"Nephrolepis cordifolia is a fern native to the global tropics, including northeastern Australia and Asia. It has many common names including fishbone fern, tuberous sword fern, tuber ladder fern, erect sword fern, narrow sword fern and ladder fern, and herringbone fern. It is similar to the related fern Nephrolepis exaltata.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nephrolepis_cordifolia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nephrolepis+cordifolia,"Habit, rhizome morphology. Plants forming tufts of 3 - 7 fronds. Runners 0.5 - 1.5 mm thick, branching angle divaricate. Scales on runners very sparse to dense, spreading or squarrose (occasionally). Tubers present or absent. Fronds to 40 - 120 by 2 - 6 cm, stipe 4 - 15 cm long. Lamina base strongly reduced, tapering over 10 - 25 cm, basal pinnae 4 - 10 cm long, 0.7 - 1.7 cm distant, middle pinnae slightly to distinctly falcate. Sterile pinnae 1 - 3.3 by 3 - 9 mm, herbaceous, thick, base slightly to strongly unequal, basiscopic base rounded or cordate, acroscopic base cordate, distinctly to strongly auricled, margin in basal part dentate, towards apex deeply dentate, apex rounded or obtuse. Fertile pinnae 1.6 - 3.2 by 0.4 - 0.8 cm, otherwise similar to sterile ones. Indument. Basal scales pseudopeltate, spreading, 8 by 1 mm, central part light brown, dull, margin in basal part irregularly lacerate, not hyaline, towards apex denticulate, without marginal glands, apex narrow, not long uniseriate. Rachis scales sparse or dense, spreading, light brown, with lacerate base and a well-developed protracted entire acumen. Scales on lamina absent. Hairs on lamina absent or sometimes present, costa absent. Sori medial, 6 - 15 pairs on fully fertile pinnae, elongated, not impressed. Indusium lunulate or broad, attached at broad base.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 26
