27,Nephrolepis exaltata (L.) Schott,Nephrolepis exaltata,Nephrolepis,Nephrolepidaceae,exaltata,(L.) Schott,,LC,2650927,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Nephrolepis exaltata,https://www.gbif.org/species/2650927,Boston fern; Boston sword fern; Boston Swordfern; fishbone fern; niʻaniʻau; southern sword fern; Sword Fern,"Notes - Nephrolepis exaltata is supposed to be the source for N. ' bostoniensis' and all cultivars derived from it, which are widely cultivated. The name has been widely, and mistakenly, applied to specimens from all over the world. Introductions: contrary to what might be expected, N. exaltata does not seem to naturalize often outside its native range. Most of the naturalized occurrences concern islands in the Atlantic, and may be diffcult to distinguish from native occurrences. On the Canary Islands, it is considered as an introduction by Hohenester & Wells (1993), but on Bermuda as native by Britton (1918). One collection was seen from St Helena (Packer HL 10, Jamestown), where it is possibly introduced. Some specimens are apparently collected in the wild in Africa and are regarded as naturalized escapes by Verdcourt (2001). Specimens were collected on the Hawaiian Islands as early as 1788 (David Nelson s. n., BM) 1825 (Macrae s. n., BM) and 1837 on Oahu (Barclay 1227, BM), and N. exaltata should be regarded as native there. Wagner et al. (1999) distinguished the Hawaiian population as subsp. hawaiiensis on basis of a comparison with the Caribbean population, but most of their distinguishing characteristics fall within the range of N. exaltata if the Florida specimens are taken into account.",A conspectus of the native and naturalized species of Nephrolepis (Nephrolepidaceae) in the world,eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Parque Nacional Natural Macuira (NATIVE); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Arizona; Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Azores (INTRODUCED); Bahamas; Bermuda; Bolivia; Brazil Northeast; Brazil North; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Colombia; Costa Rica; Cuba,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Rupícola"",""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Campo de Várzea"",""Cerrado (lato sensu)"",""Floresta Ciliar ou Galeria"",""Floresta de Várzea"",""Floresta Ombrófila (= Floresta Pluvial)"",""Floresta Ombrófila Mista"",""Vegetação Sobre Afloramentos Rochosos""]}; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Nephrolepis exaltata,"Nephrolepis exaltata, known as the sword fern or Boston fern, is a species of fern in the family Nephrolepidaceae. It is native to the Americas. This evergreen plant can reach as high as 40–90 centimetres (16–35 in), and in extreme cases up to 1.5 metres. It is also known as the Boston sword fern, wild Boston fern, Boston blue bell fern, tuber ladder fern, or fishbone fern.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nephrolepis_exaltata,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nephrolepis+exaltata,"Notes - Nephrolepis exaltata is supposed to be the source for N. ' bostoniensis' and all cultivars derived from it, which are widely cultivated. The name has been widely, and mistakenly, applied to specimens from all over the world. Introductions: contrary to what might be expected, N. exaltata does not seem to naturalize often outside its native range. Most of the naturalized occurrences concern islands in the Atlantic, and may be diffcult to distinguish from native occurrences. On the Canary Islands, it is considered as an introduction by Hohenester & Wells (1993), but on Bermuda as native by Britton (1918). One collection was seen from St Helena (Packer HL 10, Jamestown), where it is possibly introduced. Some specimens are apparently collected in the wild in Africa and are regarded as naturalized escapes by Verdcourt (2001). Specimens were collected on the Hawaiian Islands as early as 1788 (David Nelson s. n., BM) 1825 (Macrae s. n., BM) and 1837 on Oahu (Barclay 1227, BM), and N. exaltata should be regarded as native there. Wagner et al. (1999) distinguished the Hawaiian population as subsp. hawaiiensis on basis of a comparison with the Caribbean population, but most of their distinguishing characteristics fall within the range of N. exaltata if the Florida specimens are taken into account.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 27
Scientific name: Nephrolepis exaltata
Full species name: Nephrolepis exaltata (L.) Schott
Genus: Nephrolepis
Family: Nephrolepidaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Nephrolepis exaltata
Common names: Boston fern; Boston sword fern; Boston Swordfern; fishbone fern; niʻaniʻau; southern sword fern; Sword Fern
GBIF description: Notes - Nephrolepis exaltata is supposed to be the source for N. ' bostoniensis' and all cultivars derived from it, which are widely cultivated. The name has been widely, and mistakenly, applied to specimens from all over the world. Introductions: contrary to what might be expected, N. exaltata does not seem to naturalize often outside its native range. Most of the naturalized occurrences concern islands in the Atlantic, and may be diffcult to distinguish from native occurrences. On the Canary Islands, it is considered as an introduction by Hohenester & Wells (1993), but on Bermuda as native by Britton (1918). One collection was seen from St Helena (Packer HL 10, Jamestown), where it is possibly introduced. Some specimens are apparently collected in the wild in Africa and are regarded as naturalized escapes by Verdcourt (2001). Specimens were collected on the Hawaiian Islands as early as 1788 (David Nelson s. n., BM) 1825 (Macrae s. n., BM) and 1837 on Oahu (Barclay 1227, BM), and N. exaltata should be regarded as native there. Wagner et al. (1999) distinguished the Hawaiian population as subsp. hawaiiensis on basis of a comparison with the Caribbean population, but most of their distinguishing characteristics fall within the range of N. exaltata if the Florida specimens are taken into account.
Wikipedia summary: Nephrolepis exaltata, known as the sword fern or Boston fern, is a species of fern in the family Nephrolepidaceae. It is native to the Americas. This evergreen plant can reach as high as 40–90 centimetres (16–35 in), and in extreme cases up to 1.5 metres. It is also known as the Boston sword fern, wild Boston fern, Boston blue bell fern, tuber ladder fern, or fishbone fern.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Parque Nacional Natural Macuira (NATIVE); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Arizona; Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Azores (INTRODUCED); Bahamas; Bermuda; Bolivia; Brazil Northeast; Brazil North; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Colombia; Costa Rica; Cuba
