29,Achyranthes aspera L.,Achyranthes aspera,Achyranthes,Amaranthaceae,aspera,L.,,Not assessed,3085168,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Achyranthes aspera,https://www.gbif.org/species/3085168,burweed; Chaff-flower; chaffbur; Devil's Horsewhip; Devil’s Horsewhip; Man Better Man; prickly chaff-flower; Worry Vine,"General distribution. The exact origin of the species is unknown, but it seems to be native in tropical South and South-West Asia. Because of the confusion of A. aspera s. str. with other species and varieties, we have detailed its distribution across the World based on the specimens seen in the herbaria visited and online collections. Africa: see Appendix 1. Asia: Bangladesh, Bhutan, Cambodia, tropical China including Hong Kong and Taiwan, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Maldives, Myanmar, Nepal, Oman, Pakistan, Philippines, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand, UAE, Vietnam, Yemen (incl. Socotra). Australasian Realm: tropical Australia, Papua New Guinea. Melanesia: New Caledonia (probably other islands). Polynesia: Pitcairn Island, Samoa. Also reported for many other islands of Polynesia (Florence 2004). America: Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Bolivia, British Virgin Islands, Brazil (tropical regions, e. g. States of Bahia, Espírito Santo, Minas Gerais, Pará), Colombia, Costa Rica, Cuba, Cayman Islands, Dominica, Dominican Rep., French Guiana, Grenada, Guadeloupe, Guatemala, Guyana, Haiti, Jamaica, Kingdom of the Netherlands (Aruba, Bonaire, Curaçao, St. - Eustatius, St. - Martin), Martinique, Mexico, Montserrat (British Overseas Territory), Nicaragua, Panama, Puerto Rico, Salvador, St. Barthélemy (French Overseas Territory), St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Suriname, Trinidad and Tobago, USA (Alabama, Florida, Louisiana, Texas, and Hawaii), US Virgin Islands. It is common or frequent in disturbed places at lower altitudes in tropical America (e. g., Millspaugh 1900, as A. aspera obtusifolia; Robertson 1981; Acevedo-Rodríguez and Strong 2012; pers. obs. of APS in Grenada in 2016).","Africa and Arabia encompass a much greater species diversity in the Achyranthes aspera aggregate (Amaranthaceae, achyranthoid clade): Evidence from morphological and chorological data",eng,"Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Meta, Puerto López, vereda Remolino, predios de la plantacion forestal de Mavalle; Bucaramanga | Capitanejo | Cepitá | Cimitarra | Floridablanca | Los Santos; Núcleo Aceites S.A.; Vía Parque Isla de Salamanca | Parque Nacional Natural Tayrona | Parque Nacional Natural Sumapaz (NATURALISED); Complejo Humedales Hato Corozal. Cienaga Zapatosa; Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Alabama (INTRODUCED); Andaman Is.; Aruba (INTRODUCED); Assam; Austria (INTRODUCED); Bahamas (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh; Belize; Benin (INTRODUCED); Bismarck Archipelago","lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Caatinga (stricto sensu)"",""Campo rupestre""]}; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Achyranthes aspera,"Achyranthes aspera is a species of plant in the family Amaranthaceae. It is distributed throughout the tropical world. It can be found in many places growing as an introduced species and a common weed. It is an invasive species in some areas, including many Pacific Islands environments.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Achyranthes_aspera,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Achyranthes+aspera,"General distribution. The exact origin of the species is unknown, but it seems to be native in tropical South and South-West Asia. Because of the confusion of A. aspera s. str. with other species and varieties, we have detailed its distribution across the World based on the specimens seen in the herbaria visited and online collections. Africa: see Appendix 1. Asia: Bangladesh, Bhutan, Cambodia, tropical China including Hong Kong and Taiwan, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Maldives, Myanmar, Nepal, Oman, Pakistan, Philippines, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand, UAE, Vietnam, Yemen (incl. Socotra). Australasian Realm: tropical Australia, Papua New Guinea. Melanesia: New Caledonia (probably other islands). Polynesia: Pitcairn Island, Samoa. Also reported for many other islands of Polynesia (Florence 2004). America: Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Bolivia, British Virgin Islands, Brazil (tropical regions, e. g. States of Bahia, Espírito Santo, Minas Gerais, Pará), Colombia, Costa Rica, Cuba, Cayman Islands, Dominica, Dominican Rep., French Guiana, Grenada, Guadeloupe, Guatemala, Guyana, Haiti, Jamaica, Kingdom of the Netherlands (Aruba, Bonaire, Curaçao, St. - Eustatius, St. - Martin), Martinique, Mexico, Montserrat (British Overseas Territory), Nicaragua, Panama, Puerto Rico, Salvador, St. Barthélemy (French Overseas Territory), St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Suriname, Trinidad and Tobago, USA (Alabama, Florida, Louisiana, Texas, and Hawaii), US Virgin Islands. It is common or frequent in disturbed places at lower altitudes in tropical America (e. g., Millspaugh 1900, as A. aspera obtusifolia; Robertson 1981; Acevedo-Rodríguez and Strong 2012; pers. obs. of APS in Grenada in 2016).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 29
