44,Lactuca tenerrima Pourr.,Lactuca tenerrima,Lactuca,Asteraceae,tenerrima,Pourr.,,LC,3140457,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Lactuca tenerrima,https://www.gbif.org/species/3140457,,"Perennial. Stem erect, slender, prickly below, densely branched, often from the base. Leaves pinnatifid to pinnatisect. Segments narrow, usually linear, entire or roughly lobed, sagittate, glabrous or muricate at the nerves. Upper cauline leaves non-lobed, linear, sagittate. Inflorescence a loose corymbose panicle with long ascending branches. Heads solitary, smaller than in L. perennis, composed of 12-20 florets. Involucral bracts lanceolate, inner ones up to 15 mm long. Lingules lilac. Achenes obovate, 1-3 ribbed, 8-12 mm long, 1.5-2 mm broad, dark brown. Beak as long as body. Pappus yellowish, almost persistent. 2n = 6.\r\rfrom: Feráková, V. 1977: The Genus Lactuca in Europe – Bratislava.",Cichorieae Systematics Portal,eng,"Baleares; France; Germany (INTRODUCED); Morocco; Spain; Morocco (PRESENT); Albania (NATIVE); Albania (PRESENT); Germany [I]; Spain; Andorra; Gibraltar; Baleares (Ibiza & Formentera, Mallorca); France; Morocco; Italy (DOUBTFUL); Baleares (PRESENT); Gibraltar (PRESENT); Spain (PRESENT); France (PRESENT); Italy; Andorra (PRESENT); Albania (ABSENT); Channel Is. (PRESENT); Monaco (PRESENT); FR",,Lactuca tenerrima,"Lactuca tenerrima is a species of wild lettuce native to southern France, Spain, the Balearic Islands, and the Atlas Mountains of Morocco. Unlike other species in its genus Lactuca, even in its family Asteraceae, it does not produce bitter-tasting sesquiterpene lactones.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lactuca_tenerrima,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lactuca+tenerrima,"Perennial. Stem erect, slender, prickly below, densely branched, often from the base. Leaves pinnatifid to pinnatisect. Segments narrow, usually linear, entire or roughly lobed, sagittate, glabrous or muricate at the nerves. Upper cauline leaves non-lobed, linear, sagittate. Inflorescence a loose corymbose panicle with long ascending branches. Heads solitary, smaller than in L. perennis, composed of 12-20 florets. Involucral bracts lanceolate, inner ones up to 15 mm long. Lingules lilac. Achenes obovate, 1-3 ribbed, 8-12 mm long, 1.5-2 mm broad, dark brown. Beak as long as body. Pappus yellowish, almost persistent. 2n = 6.\r\rfrom: Feráková, V. 1977: The Genus Lactuca in Europe – Bratislava.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 44
Scientific name: Lactuca tenerrima
Full species name: Lactuca tenerrima Pourr.
Genus: Lactuca
Family: Asteraceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Lactuca tenerrima
GBIF description: Perennial. Stem erect, slender, prickly below, densely branched, often from the base. Leaves pinnatifid to pinnatisect. Segments narrow, usually linear, entire or roughly lobed, sagittate, glabrous or muricate at the nerves. Upper cauline leaves non-lobed, linear, sagittate. Inflorescence a loose corymbose panicle with long ascending branches. Heads solitary, smaller than in L. perennis, composed of 12-20 florets. Involucral bracts lanceolate, inner ones up to 15 mm long. Lingules lilac. Achenes obovate, 1-3 ribbed, 8-12 mm long, 1.5-2 mm broad, dark brown. Beak as long as body. Pappus yellowish, almost persistent. 2n = 6.\r\rfrom: Feráková, V. 1977: The Genus Lactuca in Europe – Bratislava.
Wikipedia summary: Lactuca tenerrima is a species of wild lettuce native to southern France, Spain, the Balearic Islands, and the Atlas Mountains of Morocco. Unlike other species in its genus Lactuca, even in its family Asteraceae, it does not produce bitter-tasting sesquiterpene lactones.
