72,Hypericum hircinum L.,Hypericum hircinum,Hypericum,Hypericaceae,hircinum,L.,,Not assessed,6436603,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Hypericum hircinum,https://www.gbif.org/species/6436603,Stinking Tutsan,"Note: Ramos Nunez (in Collect. Bot. (Barcelona) 15: 372. 1984) wrongly attributed the choice of lectotype to Robson (in Davis, Fl. Turkey 2: 372. 1967). However, Ramos Nunez's use of the term lectotype effects typification ahead of Robson (in Bull. Brit. Mus. (Nat. Hist.), Bot. 12: 307, 310. 1985).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part H),eng,Baleares; Corse; Cyprus; East Aegean Is.; France; Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Italy; Kriti; Lebanon-Syria; Morocco; NW. Balkan Pen. (INTRODUCED); Palestine; Portugal (INTRODUCED); Sardegna; Saudi Arabia; Sicilia; Spain; Türkiye,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Hypericum hircinum,"Hypericum hircinum is a species of perennial flowering plant in the St John's wort family, Hypericaceae. It is known as goat St John's wort and stinking tutsan; both names refer to the plant's distinctive odor. The species is a bushy shrub that can grow up to 1.5 meters tall, is many-stemmed, and has golden yellow flowers with conspicuous stamens. The plant has been well-documented in botanical literature, with mentions dating back to at least 1627. Carl Linnaeus described H. hircinum several times, including in his 1753 Species Plantarum which established its binomial. At one point the plant was placed into the defunct genus Androsaemum, but it was returned to Hypericum by Norman Robson in 1985.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypericum_hircinum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Hypericum+hircinum,"Note: Ramos Nunez (in Collect. Bot. (Barcelona) 15: 372. 1984) wrongly attributed the choice of lectotype to Robson (in Davis, Fl. Turkey 2: 372. 1967). However, Ramos Nunez's use of the term lectotype effects typification ahead of Robson (in Bull. Brit. Mus. (Nat. Hist.), Bot. 12: 307, 310. 1985).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 72
Scientific name: Hypericum hircinum
Full species name: Hypericum hircinum L.
Genus: Hypericum
Family: Hypericaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Hypericum hircinum
Common names: Stinking Tutsan
GBIF description: Note: Ramos Nunez (in Collect. Bot. (Barcelona) 15: 372. 1984) wrongly attributed the choice of lectotype to Robson (in Davis, Fl. Turkey 2: 372. 1967). However, Ramos Nunez's use of the term lectotype effects typification ahead of Robson (in Bull. Brit. Mus. (Nat. Hist.), Bot. 12: 307, 310. 1985).
Wikipedia summary: Hypericum hircinum is a species of perennial flowering plant in the St John's wort family, Hypericaceae. It is known as goat St John's wort and stinking tutsan; both names refer to the plant's distinctive odor. The species is a bushy shrub that can grow up to 1.5 meters tall, is many-stemmed, and has golden yellow flowers with conspicuous stamens. The plant has been well-documented in botanical literature, with mentions dating back to at least 1627. Carl Linnaeus described H. hircinum several times, including in his 1753 Species Plantarum which established its binomial. At one point the plant was placed into the defunct genus Androsaemum, but it was returned to Hypericum by Norman Robson in 1985.
Distribution: Baleares; Corse; Cyprus; East Aegean Is.; France; Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Italy; Kriti; Lebanon-Syria; Morocco; NW. Balkan Pen. (INTRODUCED); Palestine; Portugal (INTRODUCED); Sardegna; Saudi Arabia; Sicilia; Spain; Türkiye
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
