84,Lamium purpureum L.,Lamium purpureum,Lamium,Lamiaceae,purpureum,L.,,Not assessed,2926682,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Lamium purpureum,https://www.gbif.org/species/2926682,purple archangel; Purple Dead-nettle; Purple Deadnettle; purple henbit; Red Archangel; Red Dead-nettle,"Germany • Zschon [Zschoner] Grund; IX. 1949; T. K. Möbius s. n.; DR [DR 069208]! • Sachsen, Dresden, Gartensparte; 3. V. 2019; A. Lautenschläger 2; DR [DR 067780]! Italy • Giardino in loc. Bertacca, Massarosa (LUCCA); 17. III. 1982; A. Lunardini s. n.; (PI [PI 009143]!); Region of Toscana, Prov. Siena, north of Montepulciano, south of Podere Pietrose, little north of Il Granaio; W. Till 130016; WU [WU 0069675]! Russia • Yakutia, City Olekminsk, hill near the city; 16. VII. 1947; M. Karavayev s. n.; MW [MW 0129807] (photo!) • Mordovia, Mordovian State Reserve named after P. G. Smidovich, surrounding of the village Pushta; 9. IX. 1996; L. V. Teryoshkina; GMU (photo!) • Vologod region, Kirillovsky district, surroundings of the village Ferapontovo; 28. VI. 1998; N. Shvedchikova s. n.; MW [MW 0490795] (photo!). TAXONOMIC NOTES It is often found alongside Lamium amplexicaule L., which is easily mistaken for it since they have similar-looking leaves and similar bright purple flowers. Morphologically, they are easily distinguished from each other in that L. purpureum L. has stalked leaves on the flower stem (vs. without stalked leaves in L. amplexicaule L.) (Parnell & Curtis 2012).",New records of Lamiaceae from China and Uzbekistan,eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Alaska (INTRODUCED); Albania; Algeria; Altay; Antipodean Is. (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina South (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Austria; Azores; Baltic States; Belarus; Belgium; British Columbia (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is.; Central European Russia,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Lamium purpureum,"Lamium purpureum, known as red dead-nettle, purple dead-nettle, or purple archangel, is an annual herbaceous flowering plant in the mint family (Lamiaceae). It is native to Eurasia but can also be found in North America.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamium_purpureum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lamium+purpureum,"Germany • Zschon [Zschoner] Grund; IX. 1949; T. K. Möbius s. n.; DR [DR 069208]! • Sachsen, Dresden, Gartensparte; 3. V. 2019; A. Lautenschläger 2; DR [DR 067780]! Italy • Giardino in loc. Bertacca, Massarosa (LUCCA); 17. III. 1982; A. Lunardini s. n.; (PI [PI 009143]!); Region of Toscana, Prov. Siena, north of Montepulciano, south of Podere Pietrose, little north of Il Granaio; W. Till 130016; WU [WU 0069675]! Russia • Yakutia, City Olekminsk, hill near the city; 16. VII. 1947; M. Karavayev s. n.; MW [MW 0129807] (photo!) • Mordovia, Mordovian State Reserve named after P. G. Smidovich, surrounding of the village Pushta; 9. IX. 1996; L. V. Teryoshkina; GMU (photo!) • Vologod region, Kirillovsky district, surroundings of the village Ferapontovo; 28. VI. 1998; N. Shvedchikova s. n.; MW [MW 0490795] (photo!). TAXONOMIC NOTES It is often found alongside Lamium amplexicaule L., which is easily mistaken for it since they have similar-looking leaves and similar bright purple flowers. Morphologically, they are easily distinguished from each other in that L. purpureum L. has stalked leaves on the flower stem (vs. without stalked leaves in L. amplexicaule L.) (Parnell & Curtis 2012).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 84
