100,Trifolium campestre Schreb.,Trifolium campestre,Trifolium,Fabaceae,campestre,Schreb.,,Not assessed,5359477,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Trifolium campestre,https://www.gbif.org/species/5359477,"Big Hop Clover; Field Clover; Great Hop Trefoil; Hop Clover; Hop Clover, Large Hop Clover; Hop Trefoil; Large Hop Clover; Lesser Hop Clover; Low Hop Clover","Note: Stearn (in Biol. J. Linn. Soc. 5: 12. 1973), in an account of Linnaeus' Oeland and Gotland journey of 1741, treated Hoburg in Gotland as the restricted type locality, noting the existence of 930.63 (LINN) which was annotated by Linnaeus as from Gotland. Stearn noted that the name had been treated as a nomen ambiguum, and Turland & al. (in Taxon 45: 551. 1996) subsequently successfully proposed the name for rejection.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part T),eng,Saint Pierre and Miquelon (PRESENT); Bogotá (INTRODUCED); North America (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Alabama (INTRODUCED); Alaska (INTRODUCED); Albania; Algeria; Altay (INTRODUCED); Amur (INTRODUCED); Argentina South (INTRODUCED); Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Austria; Baleares; Baltic States; Belarus; Belgium; Brazil South (INTRODUCED); British Columbia (INTRODUCED),"habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Campo de Altitude"",""Campo Limpo""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Trifolium campestre,"Trifolium campestre, commonly known as hop trefoil, field clover and low hop clover, is a species of flowering plant native to Europe and western Asia.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trifolium_campestre,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Trifolium+campestre,"Note: Stearn (in Biol. J. Linn. Soc. 5: 12. 1973), in an account of Linnaeus' Oeland and Gotland journey of 1741, treated Hoburg in Gotland as the restricted type locality, noting the existence of 930.63 (LINN) which was annotated by Linnaeus as from Gotland. Stearn noted that the name had been treated as a nomen ambiguum, and Turland & al. (in Taxon 45: 551. 1996) subsequently successfully proposed the name for rejection.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 100
