131,Adonis aestivalis L.,Adonis aestivalis,Adonis,Ranunculaceae,aestivalis,L.,,Not assessed,5371707,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Adonis aestivalis,https://www.gbif.org/species/5371707,Summer pheasant's eye; Summer Pheasant's-eye; summer pheasants-eye,"Note: Bobrov (in Komarov, Fl. U. R. S. S. 7: 537. 1937) stated "" Type in the Linnaean herbarium "" (rather than the far commoner, and ineffective, "" Type in London ""). There are, however, two sheets at LINN associated with this name, so this is not an effective type choice (and 714.1 and 714.2 are not part of a single gathering so Art. 9.15 does not apply). Although Reidl (in Ann. Naturhist. Mus. Wien 66: 55. 1963) discussed the protologue, he did not designate a type. Steinberg (in Webbia 25: 305. 1971) reproduced the protologue and (p. 310) indicated Bauhin material in BAS as type but, as this was never seen by Linnaeus, it is not original material for the name.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part A),eng,North America (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Algeria; Austria; Baleares; Belarus; Belgium; Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Central European Russia (INTRODUCED); Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); East European Russia; France; Germany; Greece; Hungary; Idaho (INTRODUCED); Iran,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Adonis aestivalis,"Adonis aestivalis, the summer pheasant's-eye, is a medicinal and ornamental plant. It is native to Europe and Asia but has been introduced elsewhere, such as the western and eastern parts of the United States, as an ornamental plant. In particular, it has been known to invade alfalfa fields, contaminating feed used for horse hay. It is a member of the buttercup family. It is an annual herb.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adonis_aestivalis,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Adonis+aestivalis,"Note: Bobrov (in Komarov, Fl. U. R. S. S. 7: 537. 1937) stated "" Type in the Linnaean herbarium "" (rather than the far commoner, and ineffective, "" Type in London ""). There are, however, two sheets at LINN associated with this name, so this is not an effective type choice (and 714.1 and 714.2 are not part of a single gathering so Art. 9.15 does not apply). Although Reidl (in Ann. Naturhist. Mus. Wien 66: 55. 1963) discussed the protologue, he did not designate a type. Steinberg (in Webbia 25: 305. 1971) reproduced the protologue and (p. 310) indicated Bauhin material in BAS as type but, as this was never seen by Linnaeus, it is not original material for the name.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 131
Scientific name: Adonis aestivalis
Full species name: Adonis aestivalis L.
Genus: Adonis
Family: Ranunculaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Adonis aestivalis
Common names: Summer pheasant's eye; Summer Pheasant's-eye; summer pheasants-eye
GBIF description: Note: Bobrov (in Komarov, Fl. U. R. S. S. 7: 537. 1937) stated "" Type in the Linnaean herbarium "" (rather than the far commoner, and ineffective, "" Type in London ""). There are, however, two sheets at LINN associated with this name, so this is not an effective type choice (and 714.1 and 714.2 are not part of a single gathering so Art. 9.15 does not apply). Although Reidl (in Ann. Naturhist. Mus. Wien 66: 55. 1963) discussed the protologue, he did not designate a type. Steinberg (in Webbia 25: 305. 1971) reproduced the protologue and (p. 310) indicated Bauhin material in BAS as type but, as this was never seen by Linnaeus, it is not original material for the name.
Wikipedia summary: Adonis aestivalis, the summer pheasant's-eye, is a medicinal and ornamental plant. It is native to Europe and Asia but has been introduced elsewhere, such as the western and eastern parts of the United States, as an ornamental plant. In particular, it has been known to invade alfalfa fields, contaminating feed used for horse hay. It is a member of the buttercup family. It is an annual herb.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Algeria; Austria; Baleares; Belarus; Belgium; Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Central European Russia (INTRODUCED); Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); East European Russia; France; Germany; Greece; Hungary; Idaho (INTRODUCED); Iran
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/5371707 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adonis_aestivalis | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Adonis+aestivalis",ok
132,Adonis annua L.,Adonis annua,Adonis,Ranunculaceae,annua,L.,,Not assessed,5371709,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Adonis annua,https://www.gbif.org/species/5371709,autumn adonis; autumn pheasant’s eye; bird's-eye; Blooddrops; Pheasant's Eye; Pheasant's-eye,"Note: Bobrov stated "" Type in the Linnaean herbarium "" (rather than the far commoner, and ineffective, "" Type in London ""). 714.3 (LINN) is the only sheet there that can be associated with this name so this choice is accepted as the type. Steinberg (in Webbia 25: 305. 1971) reproduced the protologue and treated the name as a nomen ambiguum (rather than as a nomen illegitimum). Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 555. 1992) independently reached the same conclusion as Bobrov.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part A),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania; Algeria; Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Baleares; Belgium (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); East Aegean Is.; Finland (INTRODUCED); France; Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Iran; Iraq; Ireland (INTRODUCED),habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Adonis annua,"Adonis annua, also known as pheasant's-eye, Adonis' flower, autumn Adonis, autumn pheasant's-eye, blooddrops, red chamomile, red Morocco, rose-a-ruby, and soldiers-in-green, is an ornamental plant of the family Ranunculaceae. It is named after the Greek mythology character Adonis.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adonis_annua,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Adonis+annua,"Note: Bobrov stated "" Type in the Linnaean herbarium "" (rather than the far commoner, and ineffective, "" Type in London ""). 714.3 (LINN) is the only sheet there that can be associated with this name so this choice is accepted as the type. Steinberg (in Webbia 25: 305. 1971) reproduced the protologue and treated the name as a nomen ambiguum (rather than as a nomen illegitimum). Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 555. 1992) independently reached the same conclusion as Bobrov.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 132
