156,Leersia oryzoides (L.) Sw.,Leersia oryzoides,Leersia,Poaceae,oryzoides,(L.) Sw.,,LC,2702905,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Leersia oryzoides,https://www.gbif.org/species/2702905,Cut-Grass; Cutgrass; Rice Cut Grass; Rice Cutgrass; Ricegrass,Lectotype (Hitchcock in Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb. 12: 115. 1908): Herb. Linn. No. 78.10 (LINN).,Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part P),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Albania; Altay; Arizona; Arkansas; Austria; Azores; Baltic States; Belarus; Belgium; British Columbia; Bulgaria; California; Central European Russia; China Southeast; Colorado; Connecticut; Corse; Cuba (INTRODUCED),habitat: Terrestrial|Freshwater; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial,Leersia oryzoides,"Leersia oryzoides is a species of grass known by the common name rice cutgrass or just cut-grass. It is a widespread grass native to Europe, Asia, and North America and present in many other regions, such as Australia, as an introduced species. This is a rhizomatous perennial grass growing to a maximum height between 1 and 1.5 meters. The leaves are up to about 28 centimeters long and have very rough, minutely toothed edges. The inflorescence is a loose, open array of wavy, hairlike branches bearing rows of spikelets. Each spikelet is a flat fruit with a rough, bristly lemma without an awn, and no glumes. Some of the spikelet branches develop within the sheaths of the leaves and are cleistogamous. This grass is sometimes used for erosion control and restoring wetlands.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leersia_oryzoides,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Leersia+oryzoides,Lectotype (Hitchcock in Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb. 12: 115. 1908): Herb. Linn. No. 78.10 (LINN).,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 156
Scientific name: Leersia oryzoides
Full species name: Leersia oryzoides (L.) Sw.
Genus: Leersia
Family: Poaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Leersia oryzoides
Common names: Cut-Grass; Cutgrass; Rice Cut Grass; Rice Cutgrass; Ricegrass
GBIF description: Lectotype (Hitchcock in Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb. 12: 115. 1908): Herb. Linn. No. 78.10 (LINN).
Wikipedia summary: Leersia oryzoides is a species of grass known by the common name rice cutgrass or just cut-grass. It is a widespread grass native to Europe, Asia, and North America and present in many other regions, such as Australia, as an introduced species. This is a rhizomatous perennial grass growing to a maximum height between 1 and 1.5 meters. The leaves are up to about 28 centimeters long and have very rough, minutely toothed edges. The inflorescence is a loose, open array of wavy, hairlike branches bearing rows of spikelets. Each spikelet is a flat fruit with a rough, bristly lemma without an awn, and no glumes. Some of the spikelet branches develop within the sheaths of the leaves and are cleistogamous. This grass is sometimes used for erosion control and restoring wetlands.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Albania; Altay; Arizona; Arkansas; Austria; Azores; Baltic States; Belarus; Belgium; British Columbia; Bulgaria; California; Central European Russia; China Southeast; Colorado; Connecticut; Corse; Cuba (INTRODUCED)
Profile: habitat: Terrestrial|Freshwater; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2702905 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leersia_oryzoides | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Leersia+oryzoides",ok
