160,Neotinea maculata (Desf.) Stearn,Neotinea maculata,Neotinea,Orchidaceae,maculata,(Desf.) Stearn,,LC,2812458,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Neotinea maculata,https://www.gbif.org/species/2812458,Dense-Flowered Orchid,"Tubers c. 20 x 12 mm. Plant 8 - 25 (- 40) cm, glabrous, somewhat glaucous. Leaves 3 - 6, the basal 3 - 12 x 1 - 3 cm, oblong, mucronate, patent, the cauline smaller and erect, all usually with small, purplish-brown spots in longitudinal lines. Spike 2 - 6 cm, dense, sometimes secund. Flowers never opening fully and usually self-pollinated, dull pink or greenish-white. Perianth-segments 3 - 4 mm, acute to acuminate. Labellum horizontal; lateral lobes linear; middle lobe longer, oblong, often 2 - or 3 - lobed at apex. Spur 1 - 5 - 2 mm, broadly conical, obtuse. 2 n = 40.",CCIII Orchidaceae,eng,Algeria; Baleares; Canary Is.; Corse; Cyprus; East Aegean Is.; France; Great Britain; Greece; Ireland; Italy; Kriti; Lebanon-Syria; Libya; Madeira; Morocco; NW. Balkan Pen.; Palestine; Portugal; Sardegna,,Neotinea maculata,"Neotinea maculata, the dense-flowered orchid, is an orchid native to Asia Minor and parts of Europe and North Africa. (Codes)",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neotinea_maculata,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Neotinea+maculata,"Tubers c. 20 x 12 mm. Plant 8 - 25 (- 40) cm, glabrous, somewhat glaucous. Leaves 3 - 6, the basal 3 - 12 x 1 - 3 cm, oblong, mucronate, patent, the cauline smaller and erect, all usually with small, purplish-brown spots in longitudinal lines. Spike 2 - 6 cm, dense, sometimes secund. Flowers never opening fully and usually self-pollinated, dull pink or greenish-white. Perianth-segments 3 - 4 mm, acute to acuminate. Labellum horizontal; lateral lobes linear; middle lobe longer, oblong, often 2 - or 3 - lobed at apex. Spur 1 - 5 - 2 mm, broadly conical, obtuse. 2 n = 40.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 160
Scientific name: Neotinea maculata
Full species name: Neotinea maculata (Desf.) Stearn
Genus: Neotinea
Family: Orchidaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Neotinea maculata
Common names: Dense-Flowered Orchid
GBIF description: Tubers c. 20 x 12 mm. Plant 8 - 25 (- 40) cm, glabrous, somewhat glaucous. Leaves 3 - 6, the basal 3 - 12 x 1 - 3 cm, oblong, mucronate, patent, the cauline smaller and erect, all usually with small, purplish-brown spots in longitudinal lines. Spike 2 - 6 cm, dense, sometimes secund. Flowers never opening fully and usually self-pollinated, dull pink or greenish-white. Perianth-segments 3 - 4 mm, acute to acuminate. Labellum horizontal; lateral lobes linear; middle lobe longer, oblong, often 2 - or 3 - lobed at apex. Spur 1 - 5 - 2 mm, broadly conical, obtuse. 2 n = 40.
Wikipedia summary: Neotinea maculata, the dense-flowered orchid, is an orchid native to Asia Minor and parts of Europe and North Africa. (Codes)
Distribution: Algeria; Baleares; Canary Is.; Corse; Cyprus; East Aegean Is.; France; Great Britain; Greece; Ireland; Italy; Kriti; Lebanon-Syria; Libya; Madeira; Morocco; NW. Balkan Pen.; Palestine; Portugal; Sardegna
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2812458 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neotinea_maculata | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Neotinea+maculata",ok
161,Ophrys apifera Huds.,Ophrys apifera,Ophrys,Orchidaceae,apifera,Huds.,,LC,2792998,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Ophrys apifera,https://www.gbif.org/species/2792998,Bee Orchid,"Plant 15 - 50 cm. Basal leaves lanceolate to ovate, obtuse, the cauline similar, acute. Spike 2 - to 7 (- ll) - flowered, lax. Outer perianth-segments (8 -) 10 - 15 mm, oblong-ovate, patent or deflexed, purplish or purplish-violet, rarely whitish, green-striate; inner triangular to linear-lanceolate, green or purplish. Labellum 10 - 13 mm, broadly ovate, strongly convex, brownish- or blackish-purple, rarely yellowish-green or bicolorous, partly papillose, partly villous, with long, yellow, deflexed appendage, or appendage absent; lateral lobes triangular-ovate, deflexed, with externally hairy basal protuberances up to 3 mm; speculum scutelliform at the base, violet or reddish-brown, with a yellow margin, with clear yellow spots towards apex. Connective long-acuminate. 2 n — 36.",CCIII Orchidaceae,eng,Albania; Algeria; Austria; Baleares; Belgium; Bulgaria; Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; East Aegean Is.; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Hungary; Iran; Iraq; Ireland; Italy,,Ophrys apifera,"Ophrys apifera, known in Europe as the bee orchid, is a perennial herbaceous plant of the genus Ophrys, in the family of Orchidaceae. It serves as an example of sexually deceptive pollination and floral mimicry, a highly selective and highly evolved plant–pollinator relationship.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_apifera,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+apifera,"Plant 15 - 50 cm. Basal leaves lanceolate to ovate, obtuse, the cauline similar, acute. Spike 2 - to 7 (- ll) - flowered, lax. Outer perianth-segments (8 -) 10 - 15 mm, oblong-ovate, patent or deflexed, purplish or purplish-violet, rarely whitish, green-striate; inner triangular to linear-lanceolate, green or purplish. Labellum 10 - 13 mm, broadly ovate, strongly convex, brownish- or blackish-purple, rarely yellowish-green or bicolorous, partly papillose, partly villous, with long, yellow, deflexed appendage, or appendage absent; lateral lobes triangular-ovate, deflexed, with externally hairy basal protuberances up to 3 mm; speculum scutelliform at the base, violet or reddish-brown, with a yellow margin, with clear yellow spots towards apex. Connective long-acuminate. 2 n — 36.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 161
Scientific name: Ophrys apifera
Full species name: Ophrys apifera Huds.
Genus: Ophrys
Family: Orchidaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Ophrys apifera
Common names: Bee Orchid
GBIF description: Plant 15 - 50 cm. Basal leaves lanceolate to ovate, obtuse, the cauline similar, acute. Spike 2 - to 7 (- ll) - flowered, lax. Outer perianth-segments (8 -) 10 - 15 mm, oblong-ovate, patent or deflexed, purplish or purplish-violet, rarely whitish, green-striate; inner triangular to linear-lanceolate, green or purplish. Labellum 10 - 13 mm, broadly ovate, strongly convex, brownish- or blackish-purple, rarely yellowish-green or bicolorous, partly papillose, partly villous, with long, yellow, deflexed appendage, or appendage absent; lateral lobes triangular-ovate, deflexed, with externally hairy basal protuberances up to 3 mm; speculum scutelliform at the base, violet or reddish-brown, with a yellow margin, with clear yellow spots towards apex. Connective long-acuminate. 2 n — 36.
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys apifera, known in Europe as the bee orchid, is a perennial herbaceous plant of the genus Ophrys, in the family of Orchidaceae. It serves as an example of sexually deceptive pollination and floral mimicry, a highly selective and highly evolved plant–pollinator relationship.
Distribution: Albania; Algeria; Austria; Baleares; Belgium; Bulgaria; Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; East Aegean Is.; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Hungary; Iran; Iraq; Ireland; Italy
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2792998 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_apifera | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+apifera",ok
162,Ophrys bombyliflora Link,Ophrys bombyliflora,Ophrys,Orchidaceae,bombyliflora,Link,,LC,2793699,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Ophrys bombyliflora,https://www.gbif.org/species/2793699,,,,,Albania; Algeria; Baleares; Canary Is.; Corse; East Aegean Is.; France; Greece; Italy; Kriti; Libya; Morocco; NW. Balkan Pen.; Portugal; Sardegna; Sicilia; Spain; Tunisia; Türkiye-in-Europe; Türkiye,,Ophrys bombyliflora,"Ophrys bombyliflora, the bumblebee orchid, is a species of Ophrys, native from the Mediterranean region from Portugal and the Canary Islands to Turkey and Lebanon. The genus name Ophrys is from the Greek in reference to the hairy lips of the flowers of this genus; the specific epithet bombyliflora is from the Greek bombylios (bumblebee) in reference to the appearance of the flowers of this species.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_bombyliflora,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+bombyliflora,"Ophrys bombyliflora, the bumblebee orchid, is a species of Ophrys, native from the Mediterranean region from Portugal and the Canary Islands to Turkey and Lebanon. The genus name Ophrys is from the Greek in reference to the hairy lips of the flowers of this genus; the specific epithet bombyliflora is from the Greek bombylios (bumblebee) in reference to the appearance of the flowers of this species.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 162
