GBIF description: Plant up to 60 cm. Basal leaves linear-lanceolate, erect, acute. Spike 3 - to 14 - flowered, lax. Outer perianth-segments 6 - 8 mm, oblong-ovate, green, glabrous, the lateral patent, the median suberect, more or less concave; inner perianth-segments 4 - 6 mm, linear, revolute, blackish-violet, velutinous. Labellum 9 - 10 x 6 - 7 mm, deflexed, blackish-violet or - purple, paler at apex, papillose, 3 - lobed, not globose-inflated; lateral lobes patent, obtuse; middle lobe flat or concave, ovate, wider and longer than the lateral, deeply emarginate or 2 - lobed, sometimes with a tooth in the sinus; speculum reniform or square, shiny, pale blue-violet. Connective obtuse. 2 n = 36.
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys insectifera, the fly orchid, is a species of orchid and the type species of the genus Ophrys. It is remarkable as an example of the use of sexually deceptive pollination and floral mimicry, as well as a highly selective and highly evolved plant–pollinator relationship.
