206,Zannichellia palustris L.,Zannichellia palustris,Zannichellia,Potamogetonaceae,palustris,L.,,LC,2756540,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Zannichellia palustris,https://www.gbif.org/species/2756540,Horned Pondweed; Horned Poolmat; horned-pondweed,"Note: Most authors since Obermeyer have treated 1085.1 (LINN) as the type, although van Vierssen (in Aquatic Bot. 12: 125 - 126. 1982) indicated Herb. Burser X: 126 (UPS) as type (illustrating the fruits as f. 10) and has been followed by several later authors. However, Obermeyer's choice of type has priority.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part Z),eng,Reunion (PRESENT); Africa (PRESENT); Australia (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); Europe & Northern Asia (excluding China) (PRESENT); Middle America (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); South America (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Alabama; Alaska; Albania; Alberta; Algeria; Altay; Argentina Northeast; Argentina Northwest; Argentina South; Arizona,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Aquática""],""vegetationType"":[""Restinga"",""Vegetação Aquática""]}; habitat: freshwater|marine; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; Freshwater-marine; habitat: Freshwater; Freshwater-marine",Zannichellia palustris,"Zannichellia palustris, the horned pondweed, is a plant found in fresh to brackish waters in the United States, Europe, Asia, Australasia, and South America. It is recognizable by its long, thread-like leaves and ""stringy"" appearance. Its roots are long and tendril-like, and its seeds bear a distinctive horned shape, hence the common name. The species epithet palustris is Latin for ""of the marsh"" and indicates its common habitat. A diploid, its chromosome number was confirmed as 2n = 24.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zannichellia_palustris,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Zannichellia+palustris,"Note: Most authors since Obermeyer have treated 1085.1 (LINN) as the type, although van Vierssen (in Aquatic Bot. 12: 125 - 126. 1982) indicated Herb. Burser X: 126 (UPS) as type (illustrating the fruits as f. 10) and has been followed by several later authors. However, Obermeyer's choice of type has priority.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 206
Scientific name: Zannichellia palustris
Full species name: Zannichellia palustris L.
Genus: Zannichellia
Family: Potamogetonaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Zannichellia palustris
Common names: Horned Pondweed; Horned Poolmat; horned-pondweed
GBIF description: Note: Most authors since Obermeyer have treated 1085.1 (LINN) as the type, although van Vierssen (in Aquatic Bot. 12: 125 - 126. 1982) indicated Herb. Burser X: 126 (UPS) as type (illustrating the fruits as f. 10) and has been followed by several later authors. However, Obermeyer's choice of type has priority.
Wikipedia summary: Zannichellia palustris, the horned pondweed, is a plant found in fresh to brackish waters in the United States, Europe, Asia, Australasia, and South America. It is recognizable by its long, thread-like leaves and ""stringy"" appearance. Its roots are long and tendril-like, and its seeds bear a distinctive horned shape, hence the common name. The species epithet palustris is Latin for ""of the marsh"" and indicates its common habitat. A diploid, its chromosome number was confirmed as 2n = 24.
Distribution: Reunion (PRESENT); Africa (PRESENT); Australia (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); Europe & Northern Asia (excluding China) (PRESENT); Middle America (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); South America (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Alabama; Alaska; Albania; Alberta; Algeria; Altay; Argentina Northeast; Argentina Northwest; Argentina South; Arizona
