207,Secale cereale L.,Secale cereale,Secale,Poaceae,cereale,L.,,,2705966,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Secale cereale,https://www.gbif.org/species/2705966,Cereal Rye; Cultivated Annual Rye; cultivated rye; harvest rye; Rye; Ryecorn,"Neotype (Cope in Cafferty & al. in Taxon 49: 257. 2000): Italy. Florence, "" Straw from which the hats are made "", 1830, Herb. Shuttleworth s. n. (BM- 000576273).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part S),eng,North America (PRESENT); South America (PRESENT); Afghanistan (INTRODUCED); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Alaska (INTRODUCED); Alberta (INTRODUCED); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Amur (INTRODUCED); Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belarus (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Brazil South (INTRODUCED); British Columbia (INTRODUCED); California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Central European Russia (INTRODUCED),"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Rye,"Rye is a grass grown extensively as a grain, a cover crop and a forage crop. It is grown principally in an area from Eastern and Northern Europe into Russia. It is much more tolerant of cold weather and poor soil than other cereals, making it useful in those regions; its vigorous growth suppresses weeds and provides abundant forage for animals early in the year. It is a member of the wheat tribe (Triticeae) which includes the cereals wheat and barley. It is likely that rye arrived in Europe as a secondary crop, meaning that it was a minor admixture in wheat as a result of Vavilovian mimicry, and was only later cultivated in its own right.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rye,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Secale+cereale,"Neotype (Cope in Cafferty & al. in Taxon 49: 257. 2000): Italy. Florence, "" Straw from which the hats are made "", 1830, Herb. Shuttleworth s. n. (BM- 000576273).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 207
Scientific name: Secale cereale
Full species name: Secale cereale L.
Genus: Secale
Family: Poaceae
IUCN status: 
Accepted scientific name: Secale cereale
Common names: Cereal Rye; Cultivated Annual Rye; cultivated rye; harvest rye; Rye; Ryecorn
GBIF description: Neotype (Cope in Cafferty & al. in Taxon 49: 257. 2000): Italy. Florence, "" Straw from which the hats are made "", 1830, Herb. Shuttleworth s. n. (BM- 000576273).
Wikipedia summary: Rye is a grass grown extensively as a grain, a cover crop and a forage crop. It is grown principally in an area from Eastern and Northern Europe into Russia. It is much more tolerant of cold weather and poor soil than other cereals, making it useful in those regions; its vigorous growth suppresses weeds and provides abundant forage for animals early in the year. It is a member of the wheat tribe (Triticeae) which includes the cereals wheat and barley. It is likely that rye arrived in Europe as a secondary crop, meaning that it was a minor admixture in wheat as a result of Vavilovian mimicry, and was only later cultivated in its own right.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); South America (PRESENT); Afghanistan (INTRODUCED); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Alaska (INTRODUCED); Alberta (INTRODUCED); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Amur (INTRODUCED); Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belarus (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Brazil South (INTRODUCED); British Columbia (INTRODUCED); California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); Central European Russia (INTRODUCED)
