242,Tagetes erecta L.,Tagetes erecta,Tagetes,Asteraceae,patula,L.,,Not assessed,3088488,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Tagetes erecta,https://www.gbif.org/species/3088488,African Marigold; African Or French Marigold; American Marigold; Aztec Marigold; Big Marigold; French Marigold; Marigold; Mexican Marigold; Saffron Marigold,"Tagetes erecta L. Names. Myanmar: dewali-pan, kala-pan. English: African marigold, Aztec marigold, marigold. Range. Mexico and Central America. Cultivated in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used as an analgesic and antiseptic. Notes. Medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The leaf is applied to carbuncles ad boils; leaf juice is used for earache; the flower is used as a remedy for eye diseases and ulcers; flower juice is used for bleeding piles; flowers are also taken as a blood purifier. Medicinal uses of this species in China are discussed by Duke and Ayensu (1985). Here the leaf is used to treat sores and ulcers; the flower heads are decocted for colds, conjunctivitis, cough, mastitis, mumps, and sore eyes; they are also cooked with chicken liver to improve vision. Reference. Nordal (1963).",The medicinal plants of Myanmar,eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Floridablanca | Tona; Parque Nacional Natural Serranía de Los Yariguíes (MANAGED); Bogotá (INTRODUCED); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Altay (INTRODUCED); Angola (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Baleares (INTRODUCED); Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belarus (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Belize (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED),"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial",Tagetes erecta,"Tagetes erecta, the Aztec marigold, Mexican marigold, big marigold, cempaxochitl or cempasúchil, is a species of flowering plant in the genus Tagetes native to Mexico and Central America. Despite being native to the Americas, it is often called the African marigold. In Mexico, this plant is found in the wild in the states of México, Michoacán, Puebla, Veracruz and Guerrero.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tagetes_erecta,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Tagetes+erecta,"Tagetes erecta L. Names. Myanmar: dewali-pan, kala-pan. English: African marigold, Aztec marigold, marigold. Range. Mexico and Central America. Cultivated in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used as an analgesic and antiseptic. Notes. Medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The leaf is applied to carbuncles ad boils; leaf juice is used for earache; the flower is used as a remedy for eye diseases and ulcers; flower juice is used for bleeding piles; flowers are also taken as a blood purifier. Medicinal uses of this species in China are discussed by Duke and Ayensu (1985). Here the leaf is used to treat sores and ulcers; the flower heads are decocted for colds, conjunctivitis, cough, mastitis, mumps, and sore eyes; they are also cooked with chicken liver to improve vision. Reference. Nordal (1963).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 242
Scientific name: Tagetes erecta
Full species name: Tagetes erecta L.
Genus: Tagetes
Family: Asteraceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Tagetes erecta
Common names: African Marigold; African Or French Marigold; American Marigold; Aztec Marigold; Big Marigold; French Marigold; Marigold; Mexican Marigold; Saffron Marigold
GBIF description: Tagetes erecta L. Names. Myanmar: dewali-pan, kala-pan. English: African marigold, Aztec marigold, marigold. Range. Mexico and Central America. Cultivated in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used as an analgesic and antiseptic. Notes. Medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The leaf is applied to carbuncles ad boils; leaf juice is used for earache; the flower is used as a remedy for eye diseases and ulcers; flower juice is used for bleeding piles; flowers are also taken as a blood purifier. Medicinal uses of this species in China are discussed by Duke and Ayensu (1985). Here the leaf is used to treat sores and ulcers; the flower heads are decocted for colds, conjunctivitis, cough, mastitis, mumps, and sore eyes; they are also cooked with chicken liver to improve vision. Reference. Nordal (1963).
Wikipedia summary: Tagetes erecta, the Aztec marigold, Mexican marigold, big marigold, cempaxochitl or cempasúchil, is a species of flowering plant in the genus Tagetes native to Mexico and Central America. Despite being native to the Americas, it is often called the African marigold. In Mexico, this plant is found in the wild in the states of México, Michoacán, Puebla, Veracruz and Guerrero.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Floridablanca | Tona; Parque Nacional Natural Serranía de Los Yariguíes (MANAGED); Bogotá (INTRODUCED); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Altay (INTRODUCED); Angola (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Baleares (INTRODUCED); Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belarus (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Belize (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED)
