266,Vachellia drepanolobium (Harms ex Y.Sjöstedt) P.J.H.Hurter,Vachellia drepanolobium,Vachellia,Fabaceae,drepanolobium,(Harms ex Y.Sjöstedt) P.J.H.Hurter,,LC,3974788,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Vachellia drepanolobium,https://www.gbif.org/species/3974788,ant-gall acacia; black-gall acacia; whistlethorn; Whistling Thorn; whistling thorn acacia,,,,"DR Congo; Ethiopia; Kenya; Somalia; Sudan-South Sudan; Tanzania; Uganda; Global (PRESENT); Africa, Democratic Republic of Congo (NATIVE); Africa, Ethiopia (NATIVE); Africa, Kenya (NATIVE); Africa, Somalia (NATIVE); Africa, Sudan (NATIVE); Africa, Tanzania (NATIVE); Africa, Uganda (NATIVE)",,Vachellia drepanolobium,"Vachellia drepanolobium, more commonly known as Acacia drepanolobium or whistling thorn, is a swollen-thorn acacia native to East Africa. The whistling thorn grows up to 6 meters tall. It produces a pair of straight spines at each node, some of which have large bulbous bases. These swollen spines are naturally hollow and occupied by any one of several symbiotic ant species. The common name of the plant is derived from the observation that when wind blows over bulbous spines in which ants have made entry and exit holes, they produce a whistling noise.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vachellia_drepanolobium,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Vachellia+drepanolobium,"Vachellia drepanolobium, more commonly known as Acacia drepanolobium or whistling thorn, is a swollen-thorn acacia native to East Africa. The whistling thorn grows up to 6 meters tall. It produces a pair of straight spines at each node, some of which have large bulbous bases. These swollen spines are naturally hollow and occupied by any one of several symbiotic ant species. The common name of the plant is derived from the observation that when wind blows over bulbous spines in which ants have made entry and exit holes, they produce a whistling noise.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 266
Scientific name: Vachellia drepanolobium
