268,Acaciella angustissima (Mill.) Britton & Rose,Acaciella angustissima,Acaciella,Fabaceae,angustissima,(Mill.) Britton & Rose,,LC,2981071,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Acaciella angustissima,https://www.gbif.org/species/2981071,fern acacia; Prairie Acacia; white-ball acacia,Estados Unidos a Argentina; República Dominicana; introducida en Oceanía,Catálogo de Plantas y Líquenes de Colombia,,Rionegro; SFF Iguaque | Área Natural Única Los Estoraques | Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (NATIVE); Jardín Botánico de Bogotá; Argentina Northwest; Arizona; Arkansas; Belize; Bolivia; California; Colombia; Costa Rica; Cuba (INTRODUCED); Ecuador; El Salvador; Florida; Guatemala; Honduras; India (INTRODUCED); Kansas; Louisiana,"habitat: terrestrial; lifeForm: Arbusto, Árbol; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Acaciella angustissima,"Acaciella angustissima, commonly known as the prairie acacia, white-ball acacia, ocpatl, or palo de pulque, is a species of legume most recognized for its drought tolerance and its ability to be used as a green manure and ground covering. It is a perennial, deciduous, and belongs to the family Fabaceae (beans/legumes) and as it grows it starts as a shrub but eventually matures to a small tree. The tree has a high density of leaves along with small clumps of white flowers and creates 4–7 cm (1.6–2.8 in) long seed pods.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acaciella_angustissima,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Acaciella+angustissima,Estados Unidos a Argentina; República Dominicana; introducida en Oceanía,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 268
Scientific name: Acaciella angustissima
Full species name: Acaciella angustissima (Mill.) Britton & Rose
