GBIF description: Note: Although originally appearing as "" M. fr. [fructu] frondoso "", the name is to be cited as "" M. frondosa "" (Art. 23.7, Ex. 18). Smith (in J. Arnold Arbor. 26: 104. 1945) stated that "" the actual type is a collection of Hermann from Ceylon "" but did not indicate where this might be held (BM, L, etc.). Jayaweera's explicit statement is therefore accepted here as typifying the name.
Wikipedia summary: Mussaenda frondosa, commonly known as the wild mussaenda or dhobi tree, is a plant of family Rubiaceae. It is a shrub that grows to about 1.5–2 m tall. Like most other Mussaenda species, they have a bract beneath their flowers, which in this species is white in colour.
Distribution: Andaman Is.; Assam; Bangladesh; Borneo; Cambodia; Caroline Is.; China Southeast (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; Hainan (INTRODUCED); India; Jawa; Lesser Sunda Is.; Malaya; Maluku; Nepal; New Guinea; Nicobar Is.; Queensland (INTRODUCED); Sri Lanka; Sulawesi
