277,Morinda citrifolia L.,Morinda citrifolia,Morinda,Rubiaceae,citrifolia,L.,,LC,5339879,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Morinda citrifolia,https://www.gbif.org/species/5339879,canary-wood; cheesefruit; French mulberry; great morinda; Indian Mulberry; Indian-mulberry; Noni; noni-tree; rotten cheesefruit,"Morinda citrifolia L. Names. Myanmar: nibase, noni, nyagyi. English: Indian mulberry. Range. East Indies and Australia. Cultivated in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf and Fruit: Used to alleviate arthritis, as an emmenagogue, and to promote menstrual flow. Notes. Medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991). Indigenous medicinal uses of this species in the Andaman and Nicobar Islands (India) are discussed by Dagar and Singh (1999). The medicinal uses of this plant in the Caribbean region, as well as its chemistry, biological activity, toxicity and dosages, are discussed by Germosén-Robineau (1997). Details of the active chemical compounds, effects, herbal usage, and pharmacological literature of this plant are given in Fleming (2000). Traditional medicinal uses, chemical constituents, and pharmacological activity of this species are discussed by Ross (2001). Reference. Nordal (1963).",The medicinal plants of Myanmar,eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Cimitarra; Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Andaman Is.; Assam; Bahamas (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh; Belize (INTRODUCED); Bismarck Archipelago; Borneo; Cambodia; Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); Cayman Is. (INTRODUCED); Chagos Archipelago (INTRODUCED); China Southeast; Christmas I.; Cocos (Keeling) Is.; Colombia (INTRODUCED),"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Árvore""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Morinda citrifolia,"Morinda citrifolia is a fruit-bearing tree in the coffee family, Rubiaceae. There are over 100 names for this fruit across different regions, including great morinda, Indian mulberry, noni, beach mulberry, vomit fruit, awl tree, and cheesefruit.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morinda_citrifolia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Morinda+citrifolia,"Morinda citrifolia L. Names. Myanmar: nibase, noni, nyagyi. English: Indian mulberry. Range. East Indies and Australia. Cultivated in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf and Fruit: Used to alleviate arthritis, as an emmenagogue, and to promote menstrual flow. Notes. Medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991). Indigenous medicinal uses of this species in the Andaman and Nicobar Islands (India) are discussed by Dagar and Singh (1999). The medicinal uses of this plant in the Caribbean region, as well as its chemistry, biological activity, toxicity and dosages, are discussed by Germosén-Robineau (1997). Details of the active chemical compounds, effects, herbal usage, and pharmacological literature of this plant are given in Fleming (2000). Traditional medicinal uses, chemical constituents, and pharmacological activity of this species are discussed by Ross (2001). Reference. Nordal (1963).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 277
