289,Acalypha hispida Burm.f.,Acalypha hispida,Acalypha,Euphorbiaceae,hispida,Burm.f.,,Not assessed,3056375,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Acalypha hispida,https://www.gbif.org/species/3056375,bristly copperleaf; chenilleplant; Philippine-medusa; red-cattail; Red-Hot Cat's Tail; red-hot-cattail,"DESCRIPTION Shrubs or subshrubs, probably evergreen, to 4 m tall, possibly dioecious, only female plants known. Branches tomentose and short-hispid, glabrescent when mature. Axillary buds naked, densely pubescent with simple, short trichomes. Stipules to 1 cm long, triangular-lanceolate, appressed-pubescent. Petioles (2 -) 4 - 11 cm long, indumentum similar to that on young branches, glabrescent. Leaf blades not variegated, (8 -) 10 - 17 (- 19) × (5.5 -) 7 - 10 (- 13) cm, usually ovate to elliptic-lanceolate, sometimes subrhombic, membranous; base usually rounded, sometimes subcuneate to subcordate; apex acute to subacuminate, acumen to 5 mm long, obtuse, mucronate; margin serrate to crenate-serrate, teeth acute or obtuse, sometimes slightly callose-edged; upper and lower surfaces subglabrous, with some sparse, simple trichomes on veins; venation actinodromous, basal veins 5 or 7, secondary veins 7 - 9 per side. Stipels absent. Inflorescences spiciform, unisexual, axillary. Male inflorescences unknown. Female inflorescences pendulous, densely flowered, to 40 cm long; peduncle to 30 mm long, pubescent with simple, curved trichomes; bracts numerous, sessile, not enlarging in fruit, to 1 mm long, elliptic-lanceolate, sparsely hairy and ciliate; margin entire; bracteoles absent. Male flowers unknown. Female flowers 4 - 6 per bract, sessile; sepals 3 - 4, to 1 mm long, triangular-lanceolate, ciliate; ovary c. 1 mm diameter, 3 - lobed, smooth, surface densely hispid; styles 3, to 8 mm long, distinct, glabrous, each divided into 6 - 16 segments. Allomorphic flowers not seen. Capsules and seeds not seen.","Monograph of Acalypha L. (Euphorbiaceae) of the Western Indian Ocean Region, with the description of a new species from Mayotte",eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Complejo Humedales Hato Corozal. Cienaga Zapatosa; Caribbean (PRESENT); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bismarck Archipelago; Burundi (INTRODUCED); Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); Cayman Is. (INTRODUCED); Comoros (INTRODUCED); Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Cuba (INTRODUCED); Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); Ecuador (INTRODUCED); Equatorial Guinea (INTRODUCED); Gambia (INTRODUCED); Gilbert Is. (INTRODUCED); Gulf of Guinea Is. (INTRODUCED); Haiti (INTRODUCED),habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Acalypha hispida,"Acalypha hispida, the chenille plant, is a flowering shrub which belongs to the family Euphorbiaceae, the subfamily Acalyphinae, and the genus Acalypha. Acalypha is the fourth largest genus of the family Euphorbiaceae, and contains many plants native to Oceania.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acalypha_hispida,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Acalypha+hispida,"DESCRIPTION Shrubs or subshrubs, probably evergreen, to 4 m tall, possibly dioecious, only female plants known. Branches tomentose and short-hispid, glabrescent when mature. Axillary buds naked, densely pubescent with simple, short trichomes. Stipules to 1 cm long, triangular-lanceolate, appressed-pubescent. Petioles (2 -) 4 - 11 cm long, indumentum similar to that on young branches, glabrescent. Leaf blades not variegated, (8 -) 10 - 17 (- 19) × (5.5 -) 7 - 10 (- 13) cm, usually ovate to elliptic-lanceolate, sometimes subrhombic, membranous; base usually rounded, sometimes subcuneate to subcordate; apex acute to subacuminate, acumen to 5 mm long, obtuse, mucronate; margin serrate to crenate-serrate, teeth acute or obtuse, sometimes slightly callose-edged; upper and lower surfaces subglabrous, with some sparse, simple trichomes on veins; venation actinodromous, basal veins 5 or 7, secondary veins 7 - 9 per side. Stipels absent. Inflorescences spiciform, unisexual, axillary. Male inflorescences unknown. Female inflorescences pendulous, densely flowered, to 40 cm long; peduncle to 30 mm long, pubescent with simple, curved trichomes; bracts numerous, sessile, not enlarging in fruit, to 1 mm long, elliptic-lanceolate, sparsely hairy and ciliate; margin entire; bracteoles absent. Male flowers unknown. Female flowers 4 - 6 per bract, sessile; sepals 3 - 4, to 1 mm long, triangular-lanceolate, ciliate; ovary c. 1 mm diameter, 3 - lobed, smooth, surface densely hispid; styles 3, to 8 mm long, distinct, glabrous, each divided into 6 - 16 segments. Allomorphic flowers not seen. Capsules and seeds not seen.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 289
Scientific name: Acalypha hispida
Full species name: Acalypha hispida Burm.f.
Genus: Acalypha
Family: Euphorbiaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Acalypha hispida
Common names: bristly copperleaf; chenilleplant; Philippine-medusa; red-cattail; Red-Hot Cat's Tail; red-hot-cattail
GBIF description: DESCRIPTION Shrubs or subshrubs, probably evergreen, to 4 m tall, possibly dioecious, only female plants known. Branches tomentose and short-hispid, glabrescent when mature. Axillary buds naked, densely pubescent with simple, short trichomes. Stipules to 1 cm long, triangular-lanceolate, appressed-pubescent. Petioles (2 -) 4 - 11 cm long, indumentum similar to that on young branches, glabrescent. Leaf blades not variegated, (8 -) 10 - 17 (- 19) × (5.5 -) 7 - 10 (- 13) cm, usually ovate to elliptic-lanceolate, sometimes subrhombic, membranous; base usually rounded, sometimes subcuneate to subcordate; apex acute to subacuminate, acumen to 5 mm long, obtuse, mucronate; margin serrate to crenate-serrate, teeth acute or obtuse, sometimes slightly callose-edged; upper and lower surfaces subglabrous, with some sparse, simple trichomes on veins; venation actinodromous, basal veins 5 or 7, secondary veins 7 - 9 per side. Stipels absent. Inflorescences spiciform, unisexual, axillary. Male inflorescences unknown. Female inflorescences pendulous, densely flowered, to 40 cm long; peduncle to 30 mm long, pubescent with simple, curved trichomes; bracts numerous, sessile, not enlarging in fruit, to 1 mm long, elliptic-lanceolate, sparsely hairy and ciliate; margin entire; bracteoles absent. Male flowers unknown. Female flowers 4 - 6 per bract, sessile; sepals 3 - 4, to 1 mm long, triangular-lanceolate, ciliate; ovary c. 1 mm diameter, 3 - lobed, smooth, surface densely hispid; styles 3, to 8 mm long, distinct, glabrous, each divided into 6 - 16 segments. Allomorphic flowers not seen. Capsules and seeds not seen.
Wikipedia summary: Acalypha hispida, the chenille plant, is a flowering shrub which belongs to the family Euphorbiaceae, the subfamily Acalyphinae, and the genus Acalypha. Acalypha is the fourth largest genus of the family Euphorbiaceae, and contains many plants native to Oceania.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Complejo Humedales Hato Corozal. Cienaga Zapatosa; Caribbean (PRESENT); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bismarck Archipelago; Burundi (INTRODUCED); Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); Cayman Is. (INTRODUCED); Comoros (INTRODUCED); Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Cuba (INTRODUCED); Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); Ecuador (INTRODUCED); Equatorial Guinea (INTRODUCED); Gambia (INTRODUCED); Gilbert Is. (INTRODUCED); Gulf of Guinea Is. (INTRODUCED); Haiti (INTRODUCED)
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
