298,Hypericum annulatum Moris,Hypericum annulatum,Hypericum,Hypericaceae,annulatum,Moris,,Not assessed,7329869,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Hypericum annulatum,https://www.gbif.org/species/7329869,,,,,Albania; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); Eritrea; Ethiopia; Germany (INTRODUCED); Greece; Kenya; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sardegna; Saudi Arabia; Sudan-South Sudan; Switzerland (INTRODUCED); Tanzania; Uganda; CZ (PRESENT); DK (PRESENT); DK; SE (ABSENT),habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Hypericum annulatum,"Hypericum annulatum is a species of flowering plant in the family Hypericaceae. It is a perennial herb of varying heights which grows upright, with more than a hundred flowers of a golden yellow color. First described in 1827, the species has a wide distribution from Eastern Europe to East Africa, and its appearance can vary greatly based on its geographic location. It has been used in Bulgarian folk medicine, and has more recently been investigated for its effectiveness in slowing the growth of or killing certain types of human cancer.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypericum_annulatum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Hypericum+annulatum,"Hypericum annulatum is a species of flowering plant in the family Hypericaceae. It is a perennial herb of varying heights which grows upright, with more than a hundred flowers of a golden yellow color. First described in 1827, the species has a wide distribution from Eastern Europe to East Africa, and its appearance can vary greatly based on its geographic location. It has been used in Bulgarian folk medicine, and has more recently been investigated for its effectiveness in slowing the growth of or killing certain types of human cancer.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 298
Scientific name: Hypericum annulatum
Full species name: Hypericum annulatum Moris
Genus: Hypericum
Family: Hypericaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Hypericum annulatum
Wikipedia summary: Hypericum annulatum is a species of flowering plant in the family Hypericaceae. It is a perennial herb of varying heights which grows upright, with more than a hundred flowers of a golden yellow color. First described in 1827, the species has a wide distribution from Eastern Europe to East Africa, and its appearance can vary greatly based on its geographic location. It has been used in Bulgarian folk medicine, and has more recently been investigated for its effectiveness in slowing the growth of or killing certain types of human cancer.
Distribution: Albania; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); Eritrea; Ethiopia; Germany (INTRODUCED); Greece; Kenya; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sardegna; Saudi Arabia; Sudan-South Sudan; Switzerland (INTRODUCED); Tanzania; Uganda; CZ (PRESENT); DK (PRESENT); DK; SE (ABSENT)
