311,Luffa acutangula (L.) Roxb.,Luffa acutangula,Luffa,Cucurbitaceae,acutangula,(L.) Roxb.,,Not assessed,2874601,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Luffa acutangula,https://www.gbif.org/species/2874601,angled loofah; angled luffa; Chinese Okra; Chinese squash; Chinese-okra; dishcloth gourd; ribbed gourd; ribbed loofah; ridged gourd; silky gourd; Sinkwa Towelsponge; sponge gourd,"Note: Jeffrey (in Kew Bull. 34: 792. 1980), and many later authors have treated 1152.7 (LINN) as the type. However, this collection lacks the relevant Species Plantarum number (i. e. "" 3 "") and was a post- 1753 addition to the herbarium, and is not original material for the name.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part C),eng,Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Assam; Bangladesh; Benin (INTRODUCED); Burkina (INTRODUCED); Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); Chad (INTRODUCED); Chagos Archipelago (INTRODUCED); China South-Central (INTRODUCED); China Southeast (INTRODUCED); Cuba (INTRODUCED); DR Congo (INTRODUCED); Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; Gulf States (INTRODUCED); Gulf of Guinea Is. (INTRODUCED); Haiti (INTRODUCED); India,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Luffa acutangula,"Luffa acutangula is a cucurbitaceous vine commercially grown for its unripe fruits as a vegetable. Mature fruits are used as natural cleaning sponges. Its fruit slightly resembles a cucumber or zucchini with ridges. It is native to South Asia and has been naturalised in other regions. It is also grown as a houseplant in places with colder climates. English common English names include angled luffa, Chinese okra, dish cloth gourd, ridged gourd, sponge gourd, vegetable gourd, strainer vine, ribbed loofah, silky gourd, and silk gourd.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luffa_acutangula,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Luffa+acutangula,"Note: Jeffrey (in Kew Bull. 34: 792. 1980), and many later authors have treated 1152.7 (LINN) as the type. However, this collection lacks the relevant Species Plantarum number (i. e. "" 3 "") and was a post- 1753 addition to the herbarium, and is not original material for the name.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 311
