312,Lagenaria siceraria (Molina) Standl.,Lagenaria siceraria,Lagenaria,Cucurbitaceae,siceraria,(Molina) Standl.,,Not assessed,2874672,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Lagenaria siceraria,https://www.gbif.org/species/2874672,Birdhouse Gourd; Bottle Gourd; Calabash; Calabash Gourd; Dipper Gourd; Flask Calabash; Hercules Club Gourd; Italian Edible Gourd; Large African Calabash; New Guinea bean; Pipe Calabash; South African Pipe Calabash,"Description: — Herb, climbing and trailing by means of tendrils; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, angular, pubescent, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils 2 - fid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, apex acute, dentate, 4 – 15 × 5 – 15 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, pubescent. Inflorescence axillary. Male flowers calyx tubular; corolla white, with 5 free petals, slightly hairy. Fruit round, cylindrical, sometimes irregular in shape, 5 – 15 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green.","Morphology and distribution of species of the family Cucurbitaceae in Akwa Ibom State, Nigeria",eng,"Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (MANAGED); Conocida solo en cultivo, ocasionalmente escapada (INTRODUCED); Africa (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania (INTRODUCED); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Angola (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Azores (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belize (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED)","lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Liana/volúvel/trepadeira""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Cerrado (lato sensu)"",""Floresta Estacional Semidecidual""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Calabash,"Calabash, also known as bottle gourd, white-flowered gourd, long melon, birdhouse gourd, New Guinea bean, New Guinea butter bean, Tasmania bean, zucca melon and opo squash, is a vine which is grown for its fruit. It belongs to the family Cucurbitaceae, is native to tropical Africa, and cultivated across the tropics. It can be either harvested young to be consumed as a vegetable, or harvested mature to be dried and used as a kitchen utensil, beverage container or a musical instrument. When it is fresh, the fruit has a light green smooth skin and white flesh.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calabash,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lagenaria+siceraria,"Description: — Herb, climbing and trailing by means of tendrils; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, angular, pubescent, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils 2 - fid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, apex acute, dentate, 4 – 15 × 5 – 15 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, pubescent. Inflorescence axillary. Male flowers calyx tubular; corolla white, with 5 free petals, slightly hairy. Fruit round, cylindrical, sometimes irregular in shape, 5 – 15 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 312
Scientific name: Lagenaria siceraria
Full species name: Lagenaria siceraria (Molina) Standl.
Genus: Lagenaria
Family: Cucurbitaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Lagenaria siceraria
Common names: Birdhouse Gourd; Bottle Gourd; Calabash; Calabash Gourd; Dipper Gourd; Flask Calabash; Hercules Club Gourd; Italian Edible Gourd; Large African Calabash; New Guinea bean; Pipe Calabash; South African Pipe Calabash
GBIF description: Description: — Herb, climbing and trailing by means of tendrils; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, angular, pubescent, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils 2 - fid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, apex acute, dentate, 4 – 15 × 5 – 15 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, pubescent. Inflorescence axillary. Male flowers calyx tubular; corolla white, with 5 free petals, slightly hairy. Fruit round, cylindrical, sometimes irregular in shape, 5 – 15 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green.
Wikipedia summary: Calabash, also known as bottle gourd, white-flowered gourd, long melon, birdhouse gourd, New Guinea bean, New Guinea butter bean, Tasmania bean, zucca melon and opo squash, is a vine which is grown for its fruit. It belongs to the family Cucurbitaceae, is native to tropical Africa, and cultivated across the tropics. It can be either harvested young to be consumed as a vegetable, or harvested mature to be dried and used as a kitchen utensil, beverage container or a musical instrument. When it is fresh, the fruit has a light green smooth skin and white flesh.
Distribution: Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (MANAGED); Conocida solo en cultivo, ocasionalmente escapada (INTRODUCED); Africa (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania (INTRODUCED); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Angola (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Azores (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh (INTRODUCED); Belize (INTRODUCED); Benin (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED)
