313,Lagenaria sphaerica (Sond.) Naudin,Lagenaria sphaerica,Lagenaria,Cucurbitaceae,sphaerica,(Sond.) Naudin,,Not assessed,3623251,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Lagenaria sphaerica,https://www.gbif.org/species/3623251,Wild Melon,"Description: — Herb, climbing by means of tendrils, up to 50 m high; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, cylindrical, scabrid, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils bifid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, dentate to undulate, apex acute, 7 – 15 × 6 – 20 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, smooth. Inflorescence cymose; male flowers with tubular calyx, corolla white with 5 free petals, slightly hairy with patches of green towards calyx tube. Fruit round pepos, ± 7 – 5 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green with white and yellow patches all over, many seeded. Seed flat, 1.0 – 1.4 × 0.6 – 0.8 cm.","Morphology and distribution of species of the family Cucurbitaceae in Akwa Ibom State, Nigeria",eng,"Cameroon; Bioko Isl. [Fernando Poo]; Annobon Isl.; E-D.R.Congo [Zaire]; Rwanda; Burundi; S-Somalia; Uganda; Kenya; Tanzania; Zambia; Malawi; Zimbabwe; Mozambique; Botswana; South Africa (Limpopo, KwaZulu-Natal, W-Cape Prov., E-Cape Prov.); La Réunion [I]",,Lagenaria sphaerica,Lagenaria sphaerica is a herbaceous climber in the family Cucurbitaceae. It is commonly known as the wild melon.,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagenaria_sphaerica,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lagenaria+sphaerica,"Description: — Herb, climbing by means of tendrils, up to 50 m high; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, cylindrical, scabrid, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils bifid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, dentate to undulate, apex acute, 7 – 15 × 6 – 20 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, smooth. Inflorescence cymose; male flowers with tubular calyx, corolla white with 5 free petals, slightly hairy with patches of green towards calyx tube. Fruit round pepos, ± 7 – 5 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green with white and yellow patches all over, many seeded. Seed flat, 1.0 – 1.4 × 0.6 – 0.8 cm.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 313
Scientific name: Lagenaria sphaerica
Full species name: Lagenaria sphaerica (Sond.) Naudin
Genus: Lagenaria
Family: Cucurbitaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Lagenaria sphaerica
Common names: Wild Melon
GBIF description: Description: — Herb, climbing by means of tendrils, up to 50 m high; monoecious. Stem herbaceous, climbing, cylindrical, scabrid, 0.2 – 0.3 cm diam.; tendrils bifid, spirally coiled just above branching point. Leaves simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, exstipulate, scabrid, palmately lobed, deep green, dentate to undulate, apex acute, 7 – 15 × 6 – 20 cm; petiole cylindrical, 3 – 5 cm long, herbaceous, smooth. Inflorescence cymose; male flowers with tubular calyx, corolla white with 5 free petals, slightly hairy with patches of green towards calyx tube. Fruit round pepos, ± 7 – 5 cm diam., pedunculate, smooth, green with white and yellow patches all over, many seeded. Seed flat, 1.0 – 1.4 × 0.6 – 0.8 cm.
Wikipedia summary: Lagenaria sphaerica is a herbaceous climber in the family Cucurbitaceae. It is commonly known as the wild melon.
Distribution: Cameroon; Bioko Isl. [Fernando Poo]; Annobon Isl.; E-D.R.Congo [Zaire]; Rwanda; Burundi; S-Somalia; Uganda; Kenya; Tanzania; Zambia; Malawi; Zimbabwe; Mozambique; Botswana; South Africa (Limpopo, KwaZulu-Natal, W-Cape Prov., E-Cape Prov.); La Réunion [I]
