318,Raphia farinifera (Gaertn.) Hyl.,Raphia farinifera,Raphia,Arecaceae,farinifera,(Gaertn.) Hyl.,,LC,5293210,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Raphia farinifera,https://www.gbif.org/species/5293210,Raffia Palm; Raphia Palm,,,,Africa (PRESENT); Angola; Benin; Burkina; Cameroon; Comoros; Congo; Gambia; Ghana; Ivory Coast; Kenya; Madagascar; Malawi; Mauritius (INTRODUCED); Mozambique; Nigeria; Réunion (INTRODUCED); Senegal; Seychelles (INTRODUCED); Sierra Leone,"habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Palmeira""],""habitat"":[""Aquática""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Raphia farinifera,"Raphia farinifera is a tropical African palm tree occurring in lowland riparian and swamp forest, also around human habitations and cultivated locations, on stream banks and other moist situations at altitudes of 50–1000 m. Found in Angola, Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Nigeria, Réunion, Senegal, Seychelles, Sierra Leone, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, and naturalised in east lowlands of Madagascar. Its generic epithet is derived from raphis = 'needle', probably in reference to the 4 mm long yellowish spines on the margins and main veins of the leaflets. The specific name refers to a type of starchy flour obtained from the trunk pith – farina = 'flour', fera = 'bearing'.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raphia_farinifera,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Raphia+farinifera,"Raphia farinifera is a tropical African palm tree occurring in lowland riparian and swamp forest, also around human habitations and cultivated locations, on stream banks and other moist situations at altitudes of 50–1000 m. Found in Angola, Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Nigeria, Réunion, Senegal, Seychelles, Sierra Leone, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, and naturalised in east lowlands of Madagascar. Its generic epithet is derived from raphis = 'needle', probably in reference to the 4 mm long yellowish spines on the margins and main veins of the leaflets. The specific name refers to a type of starchy flour obtained from the trunk pith – farina = 'flour', fera = 'bearing'.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 318
Scientific name: Raphia farinifera
Full species name: Raphia farinifera (Gaertn.) Hyl.
Genus: Raphia
Family: Arecaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Raphia farinifera
Common names: Raffia Palm; Raphia Palm
Wikipedia summary: Raphia farinifera is a tropical African palm tree occurring in lowland riparian and swamp forest, also around human habitations and cultivated locations, on stream banks and other moist situations at altitudes of 50–1000 m. Found in Angola, Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Nigeria, Réunion, Senegal, Seychelles, Sierra Leone, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, and naturalised in east lowlands of Madagascar. Its generic epithet is derived from raphis = 'needle', probably in reference to the 4 mm long yellowish spines on the margins and main veins of the leaflets. The specific name refers to a type of starchy flour obtained from the trunk pith – farina = 'flour', fera = 'bearing'.
Distribution: Africa (PRESENT); Angola; Benin; Burkina; Cameroon; Comoros; Congo; Gambia; Ghana; Ivory Coast; Kenya; Madagascar; Malawi; Mauritius (INTRODUCED); Mozambique; Nigeria; Réunion (INTRODUCED); Senegal; Seychelles (INTRODUCED); Sierra Leone
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Palmeira""],""habitat"":[""Aquática""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
