GBIF description: Plant 15 ^ 40 cm. Basal leaves ovate-lanceolate, obtuse, the cauline bract-like. Spike 2 - to 9 - flowered, lax. Perianth-segments usually pink, rarely purplish- violet, whitish or pale greenish; lateral outer perianth-segments c. 10 mm, oblong-ovate, obtuse, the median outer oblong-elliptical or - lanceolate; inner perianth-segments 6 - 7 mm, oblong-, tri­ angular- or linear-lanceolate, more intensely coloured than the outer, glabrous, papillose or densely hairy. Labellum 8 - 10 mm, suborbicular, obovate or somewhat square, subentire, rarely indistinctly 3 - lobed, velutinous, with broadly conical, short, inconspicuous basal protuberances, sometimes with a narrow, yellow, glabrous marginal zone, usually with a small appendage; speculum annular or square, usually H-shaped, blue or dark purplish, with whitish or yellow margin. Connective acute. 2 / 2 = 36, 38.
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys × arachnitiformis, the false spider orchid, is an orchid native to Europe. It is apparently a hybrid resulting from a cross between O. fuciflora × O. sphegodes, but has become established in the wild in Britain, France, Germany, parts of Italy, Austria, Switzerland, Hungary, and the former Yugoslavia.
Distribution: Austria; Corse; France; Germany; Great Britain; Hungary; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sardegna; Spain; Switzerland; FR
