346,Nothofagus obliqua (Mirb.) Oerst.,Nothofagus obliqua,Nothofagus,Nothofagaceae,obliqua,(Mirb.) Oerst.,,LC,2874984,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Nothofagus obliqua,https://www.gbif.org/species/2874984,roble beech,,,,Argentina South; Chile Central; Chile South; Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Ireland (INTRODUCED); Global (PRESENT); Belgium (DOUBTFUL); France (DOUBTFUL); Great Britain (PRESENT); GB (PRESENT); IE (PRESENT); The Netherlands (DOUBTFUL); PT (PRESENT),habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Nothofagus obliqua,"Nothofagus obliqua, commonly known as Patagonian oak, roble, pellín, roble pellín, and hualle in its early state of growth or roble beech, is a deciduous tree from Chile and Argentina. It grows from 33 to 43° south latitude. The northern extent of this tree's range in Chile is considered to be the Vizcachas Mountains and La Campana National Park. N. obliqua was proposed to be renamed Lophozonia obliqua in 2013.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nothofagus_obliqua,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nothofagus+obliqua,"Nothofagus obliqua, commonly known as Patagonian oak, roble, pellín, roble pellín, and hualle in its early state of growth or roble beech, is a deciduous tree from Chile and Argentina. It grows from 33 to 43° south latitude. The northern extent of this tree's range in Chile is considered to be the Vizcachas Mountains and La Campana National Park. N. obliqua was proposed to be renamed Lophozonia obliqua in 2013.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 346
