372,Daphne cneorum L.,Daphne cneorum,Daphne,Thymelaeaceae,cneorum,L.,,Not assessed,7150059,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Daphne cneorum,https://www.gbif.org/species/7150059,Garland-flower; rose daphne,"8. Daphne floribus congestis terminalibus sessilibus, foliis lanceolatis nudis. Daphne humifusa, foliis oblongis flores sessiles terminales subcingentibus. Sauv. monsp. 57. Thymelaea affinis facie externa. Bauh. pin. 463. Cneorum. Matth. hist. 46. Clus. hist. 89.","Species plantarum: exhibentes plantas rite cognitas, ad genera relatas, cum differentiis specificis, nominibus trivialibus, synonymis selectis, locis natalibus, secundum systema sexuale digestas",eng,"Albania; Austria; Belarus; Bulgaria; Central European Russia; Czechia-Slovakia; France; Germany; Hungary; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Poland; Romania; Spain; Switzerland; Ukraine; Germany (Baden-Württemberg, Bayern, +Hessen, Rheinland-Pfalz); Switzerland; Austria; Poland; Czech Republic; Slovakia; Hungary; N-Spain; Andorra; France; Italy; Slovenia; Croatia; Serbia; Kosovo; North Macedonia; Albania; Romania; Bulgaria; Belarus; C-European Russia; Ukraine; Turkey (NW-Anatolia: Bithynia); CH; DE; FR",,Daphne cneorum,"Daphne cneorum, the rose daphne or garland flower, is a species of flowering plant in the family Thymelaeaceae, native across the mountains of central and southern Europe from the Pyrenees east through the Alps, the Apennine, Carpathian and the Balkan Peninsula mountains, and locally in lowlands further north and east to Ukraine and westernmost Russia. It is a prostrate spreading evergreen shrub growing to 50 cm (20 in) high, with downy stems bearing oblanceolate to spatulate, hairless, evergreen leaves 10–20 mm long and 3–5 mm wide, and highly fragrant pink flowers in dense clusters of 6–8 together in spring. All parts of the plant are poisonous to humans.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daphne_cneorum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Daphne+cneorum,"8. Daphne floribus congestis terminalibus sessilibus, foliis lanceolatis nudis. Daphne humifusa, foliis oblongis flores sessiles terminales subcingentibus. Sauv. monsp. 57. Thymelaea affinis facie externa. Bauh. pin. 463. Cneorum. Matth. hist. 46. Clus. hist. 89.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 372
