Wikipedia summary: Daphne mezereum, the mezereon, is a species of Daphne in the flowering plant family Thymelaeaceae, native to most of Europe and Western Asia, north to northern Scandinavia and Russia. In southern Europe it is confined to medium to higher elevations in the subalpine vegetation zone, but descends to sea level in northern Europe. It is generally confined to soils derived from limestone. In the United Kingdom, the native population became a protected species in 1975 under the Conservation of Wild Creatures and Wild Plants Act.
Distribution: Vefsand; Trøndelag; Norway; Elverum; Snåsa; Tjøme; Nordnorge; Telemark; Nidaros (Trondheim); Vest-Sildre; Grane; Harran; Nord-Rana; Uvdal; Bindal; Lårdal; Europe & Northern Asia (excluding China) (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Alaska (INTRODUCED); Albania
Profile: habitat: Terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/5420852 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daphne_mezereum | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Daphne+mezereum",ok
