375,Cleretum bellidiforme (Burm.f.) G.D.Rowley,Cleretum bellidiforme,Cleretum,Aizoaceae,bellidiformis,(Burm.f.) G.D.Rowley,,Not assessed,3707306,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Cleretum bellidiforme,https://www.gbif.org/species/3707306,Bokbaai Sandfig; Bokbaai Vygie; Buckbay-Vygie; Livingstone daisy; Livingstone-daisy,,,,"Cape Provinces; South Africa (N-Cape Prov., W-Cape Prov.); ZA (NATIVE); ZA; NorthernCape (NATIVE); SouthAfrica; SouthernAfrica_FSA; WesternCape (NATIVE)",,Cleretum bellidiforme,"Cleretum bellidiforme, commonly called Livingstone daisy, Bokbaaivygie (Afrikaans), or Buck Bay vygie, is a species of flowering plant in the family Aizoaceae, native to the Cape Peninsula in South Africa. It is a low-growing succulent annual growing to 25 cm (10 in), and cultivated for its iridescent, many-petalled, daisy-like blooms in shades of white, yellow, orange, cream, pink and crimson. In temperate areas it is popularly grown as a half-hardy annual, and lends itself to mass plantings or as edging plants in summer bedding schemes in parks and gardens. It is still widely referenced under its former names, Mesembryanthemum criniflorum, Mesembryanthemum bellidiformis and Dorotheanthus bellidiformis.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleretum_bellidiforme,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Cleretum+bellidiforme,"Cleretum bellidiforme, commonly called Livingstone daisy, Bokbaaivygie (Afrikaans), or Buck Bay vygie, is a species of flowering plant in the family Aizoaceae, native to the Cape Peninsula in South Africa. It is a low-growing succulent annual growing to 25 cm (10 in), and cultivated for its iridescent, many-petalled, daisy-like blooms in shades of white, yellow, orange, cream, pink and crimson. In temperate areas it is popularly grown as a half-hardy annual, and lends itself to mass plantings or as edging plants in summer bedding schemes in parks and gardens. It is still widely referenced under its former names, Mesembryanthemum criniflorum, Mesembryanthemum bellidiformis and Dorotheanthus bellidiformis.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 375
