391,Hirschfeldia incana (L.) Lagr.-Foss.,Hirschfeldia incana,Hirschfeldia,Brassicaceae,incanum,(L.) Lagr.-Foss.,,Not assessed,3050595,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Hirschfeldia incana,https://www.gbif.org/species/3050595,buchanweed; Greek Mustard; hairy brassica; Hoary Cabbage; Hoary Mustard; Mediterranean mustard; Shortpod Mustard; summer mustard,Eastern Europe,Global Register of Introduced and Invasive Species - Belgium,eng,North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Albania; Algeria; Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Argentina South (INTRODUCED); Arizona (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED); Azores (INTRODUCED); Baleares; Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Belarus (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED); California (INTRODUCED); Canary Is.; Cape Provinces (INTRODUCED); Central European Russia (INTRODUCED); Chile Central (INTRODUCED),habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Hirschfeldia,"Hirschfeldia incana is a species of flowering plant in the mustard family known by many common names, including shortpod mustard, buchanweed, hoary mustard and Mediterranean mustard. It is the only species in the monotypic genus Hirschfeldia, which is closely related to Brassica. The species is native to the Mediterranean Basin but it can be found in many parts of the world as an introduced species and often a very abundant noxious weed. This mustard is very similar in appearance to black mustard, but is generally shorter. It forms a wide basal rosette of lobed leaves which lie flat on the ground, and it keeps its leaves while flowering. Its stem and foliage have soft white hairs. Unlike black mustard, H. incana is a perennial plant.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hirschfeldia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Hirschfeldia+incana,Eastern Europe,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 391
