417,Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallr.,Cicerbita alpina,Cicerbita,Asteraceae,alpina,(L.) Wallr.,,Not assessed,3087634,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Cicerbita alpina,https://www.gbif.org/species/3087634,alpine blue sow thistle; Alpine Blue sow-thistle; Alpine Blue-Sow-Thistle; Alpine Sow-Thistle; Blue Sowthistle; mountain sow thistle; tall blue-lettuce,"The tall perennial hemicryptophytic herb Cicerbita alpina developes in spring c. 0.5–1.2 cm thick shoots from its oblique rhizome, similar to asparagus. These young, c. 7–>10 cm long subterraneous shoots have traditionally been collected from wild plants and eaten in some areas of NE Italy, including the province of Trento, mainly under oil, and in the 21th century have also started to appear on local markets as ""Insalata dell' orso"" or ""Radic di mont"" (Scartezzini & al. 2012).\r\rThe shoots are rich in caffeic acid derivatives (chlorogenic acid, 3,5-dicaffeoylquinic acid, caffeoyltartric acid, and cichoric acid) known to possess a beneficial high radical scavenging activity (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). To avoid threatening the long-term survival of this species by collecting shoots from wild populations, cultivating the species has been explored in the recent years. Cultivation also aims at the selection of cultivars rich in antioxidants but with moderate levels of the bitter sesquiterpene lactone glucoside derivative of lactucin (8-O-Acetyl-15-b-D-glucopyranosyllactucin), which is also present in the shoots (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). \r References \rFusani P. & Zidorn C. 2010: Phenolics and a sesquiterpene lactone in the edible shoots of Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallroth. – J. Food Composition Analysis 23: 658–663. // ➪ // .\r\rScartezzini F., Fusani P., Aiello N. & Vender C. 2012: Domestication of Alpine blue-sow-thistle ( Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallr.): six year trial results. – Genet. Resources Crop Evol. 59: 465–471 .",Cichorieae Systematics Portal,eng,Nordland; Albania; Austria; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia; Finland; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; North European Russia; Norway; Poland; Romania; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland; Ukraine,habitat: Terrestrial,Cicerbita alpina,"Cicerbita alpina, commonly known as the alpine sow-thistle or alpine blue-sow-thistle is a perennial herbaceous species of plant formerly placed in the genus Lactuca as Lactuca alpina. It is native to upland and mountainous parts of Europe.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cicerbita_alpina,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Cicerbita+alpina,"The tall perennial hemicryptophytic herb Cicerbita alpina developes in spring c. 0.5–1.2 cm thick shoots from its oblique rhizome, similar to asparagus. These young, c. 7–>10 cm long subterraneous shoots have traditionally been collected from wild plants and eaten in some areas of NE Italy, including the province of Trento, mainly under oil, and in the 21th century have also started to appear on local markets as ""Insalata dell' orso"" or ""Radic di mont"" (Scartezzini & al. 2012).\r\rThe shoots are rich in caffeic acid derivatives (chlorogenic acid, 3,5-dicaffeoylquinic acid, caffeoyltartric acid, and cichoric acid) known to possess a beneficial high radical scavenging activity (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). To avoid threatening the long-term survival of this species by collecting shoots from wild populations, cultivating the species has been explored in the recent years. Cultivation also aims at the selection of cultivars rich in antioxidants but with moderate levels of the bitter sesquiterpene lactone glucoside derivative of lactucin (8-O-Acetyl-15-b-D-glucopyranosyllactucin), which is also present in the shoots (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). \r References \rFusani P. & Zidorn C. 2010: Phenolics and a sesquiterpene lactone in the edible shoots of Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallroth. – J. Food Composition Analysis 23: 658–663. // ➪ // .\r\rScartezzini F., Fusani P., Aiello N. & Vender C. 2012: Domestication of Alpine blue-sow-thistle ( Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallr.): six year trial results. – Genet. Resources Crop Evol. 59: 465–471 .",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 417
Scientific name: Cicerbita alpina
Full species name: Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallr.
Genus: Cicerbita
Family: Asteraceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Cicerbita alpina
Common names: alpine blue sow thistle; Alpine Blue sow-thistle; Alpine Blue-Sow-Thistle; Alpine Sow-Thistle; Blue Sowthistle; mountain sow thistle; tall blue-lettuce
GBIF description: The tall perennial hemicryptophytic herb Cicerbita alpina developes in spring c. 0.5–1.2 cm thick shoots from its oblique rhizome, similar to asparagus. These young, c. 7–>10 cm long subterraneous shoots have traditionally been collected from wild plants and eaten in some areas of NE Italy, including the province of Trento, mainly under oil, and in the 21th century have also started to appear on local markets as ""Insalata dell' orso"" or ""Radic di mont"" (Scartezzini & al. 2012).\r\rThe shoots are rich in caffeic acid derivatives (chlorogenic acid, 3,5-dicaffeoylquinic acid, caffeoyltartric acid, and cichoric acid) known to possess a beneficial high radical scavenging activity (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). To avoid threatening the long-term survival of this species by collecting shoots from wild populations, cultivating the species has been explored in the recent years. Cultivation also aims at the selection of cultivars rich in antioxidants but with moderate levels of the bitter sesquiterpene lactone glucoside derivative of lactucin (8-O-Acetyl-15-b-D-glucopyranosyllactucin), which is also present in the shoots (Fusani & Zidorn 2010). \r References \rFusani P. & Zidorn C. 2010: Phenolics and a sesquiterpene lactone in the edible shoots of Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallroth. – J. Food Composition Analysis 23: 658–663. // ➪ // .\r\rScartezzini F., Fusani P., Aiello N. & Vender C. 2012: Domestication of Alpine blue-sow-thistle ( Cicerbita alpina (L.) Wallr.): six year trial results. – Genet. Resources Crop Evol. 59: 465–471 .
Wikipedia summary: Cicerbita alpina, commonly known as the alpine sow-thistle or alpine blue-sow-thistle is a perennial herbaceous species of plant formerly placed in the genus Lactuca as Lactuca alpina. It is native to upland and mountainous parts of Europe.
Distribution: Nordland; Albania; Austria; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia; Finland; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; North European Russia; Norway; Poland; Romania; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland; Ukraine
Profile: habitat: Terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3087634 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cicerbita_alpina | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Cicerbita+alpina",ok
