Wikipedia summary: Bourreria is a genus of flowering plants in the family Ehretiaceae. Members of the genus are commonly known as strongbark or strongback. The generic name was chosen by Patrick Browne to honour German pharmacist Johann Ambrosius Beurer. The genus is native to the tropical Americas and to eastern Africa and Madagascar. American species are distributed from Mexico to northern South America, and in the Caribbean and Florida in the United States. The center of diversity is in the Caribbean, Central America, and Mexico. The eastern African species range from Ethiopia to Mozambique and to Madagascar, the Comoro Islands, and Mauritius.
Distribution: Costa Rica; Guatemala; Honduras; Mexico Central; Mexico Southeast; Mexico Southwest; Nicaragua; Global (PRESENT); Mexico (Chiapas, Guerrero, México State, Michoacán, Morelos, Oaxaca, Puebla); Guatemala; Honduras; Nicaragua; Costa Rica
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/4063410 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bourreria | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Bourreria+andrieuxii",ok
448,Ophrys bertolonii Moretti,Ophrys bertolonii,Ophrys,Orchidaceae,bertolonii,Moretti,,LC,2792833,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Ophrys bertolonii,https://www.gbif.org/species/2792833,Bertoloni's Bee Orchid; Bertoloni's Bee-orchid,"Plants of hybrid origin between 9 and 6 (d) have been called O. bertoloniiformis O. & E. Danesch, Orchidee 22: 117 (1971); they differ from 9 chiefly in being 15 - 25 cm high, in having both the inner and outer perianth-segments greenish and more or less undulate, and the labellum 10 - 12 x 9 - 11 mm, scarcely curved upwards and without or with an inconspicuous appendage. They have 2 / z = 36. Because of frequent confusion between this and 9 the distribution given above refers to both these taxa. O. bertholoniiformis is probably the more widespread, and 9 is per­ haps confined to the E. part of the range. O. promontorii O. & E. Danesch, op. cit. 258 (1971), described from S. E. Italy (Mte Gargano), is probably of hybrid origin between 9 and O. gar­ ganica (vide 6). It has 2 ft = 36, 37, 38.",CCIII Orchidaceae,eng,Albania; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sicilia; Global (PRESENT); FR,,Ophrys bertolonii,"Ophrys bertolonii, commonly known as Bertoloni's bee orchid, is a species of orchid native to the western and central Mediterranean.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_bertolonii,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+bertolonii,"Plants of hybrid origin between 9 and 6 (d) have been called O. bertoloniiformis O. & E. Danesch, Orchidee 22: 117 (1971); they differ from 9 chiefly in being 15 - 25 cm high, in having both the inner and outer perianth-segments greenish and more or less undulate, and the labellum 10 - 12 x 9 - 11 mm, scarcely curved upwards and without or with an inconspicuous appendage. They have 2 / z = 36. Because of frequent confusion between this and 9 the distribution given above refers to both these taxa. O. bertholoniiformis is probably the more widespread, and 9 is per­ haps confined to the E. part of the range. O. promontorii O. & E. Danesch, op. cit. 258 (1971), described from S. E. Italy (Mte Gargano), is probably of hybrid origin between 9 and O. gar­ ganica (vide 6). It has 2 ft = 36, 37, 38.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 448
Scientific name: Ophrys bertolonii
Full species name: Ophrys bertolonii Moretti
Genus: Ophrys
Family: Orchidaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Ophrys bertolonii
Common names: Bertoloni's Bee Orchid; Bertoloni's Bee-orchid
GBIF description: Plants of hybrid origin between 9 and 6 (d) have been called O. bertoloniiformis O. & E. Danesch, Orchidee 22: 117 (1971); they differ from 9 chiefly in being 15 - 25 cm high, in having both the inner and outer perianth-segments greenish and more or less undulate, and the labellum 10 - 12 x 9 - 11 mm, scarcely curved upwards and without or with an inconspicuous appendage. They have 2 / z = 36. Because of frequent confusion between this and 9 the distribution given above refers to both these taxa. O. bertholoniiformis is probably the more widespread, and 9 is per­ haps confined to the E. part of the range. O. promontorii O. & E. Danesch, op. cit. 258 (1971), described from S. E. Italy (Mte Gargano), is probably of hybrid origin between 9 and O. gar­ ganica (vide 6). It has 2 ft = 36, 37, 38.
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys bertolonii, commonly known as Bertoloni's bee orchid, is a species of orchid native to the western and central Mediterranean.
Distribution: Albania; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sicilia; Global (PRESENT); FR
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2792833 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_bertolonii | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+bertolonii",ok
449,Ophrys × flavicans Vis.,Ophrys × flavicans,Ophrys,Orchidaceae,catalaunica,Vis.,,Not assessed,2792725,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Ophrys flavicans,https://www.gbif.org/species/2792725,,,,,Baleares; France; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sicilia; Spain,,Ophrys × flavicans,"Ophrys × flavicans is a hybrid species of orchid found in Spain, the Balearic Islands, France, mainland Italy, Sicily and former Yugoslavia. It is a hybrid between Ophrys bertolonii and Ophrys sphegodes. It has a large number of synonyms, either as other hybrid species, such as Ophrys × drumana and Ophrys × bertoloniiformis, or as infrataxa of other species, such as Ophrys bertolonii subsp. flavicans.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_%C3%97_flavicans,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+%C3%97+flavicans,"Ophrys × flavicans is a hybrid species of orchid found in Spain, the Balearic Islands, France, mainland Italy, Sicily and former Yugoslavia. It is a hybrid between Ophrys bertolonii and Ophrys sphegodes. It has a large number of synonyms, either as other hybrid species, such as Ophrys × drumana and Ophrys × bertoloniiformis, or as infrataxa of other species, such as Ophrys bertolonii subsp. flavicans.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 449
Scientific name: Ophrys × flavicans
Full species name: Ophrys × flavicans Vis.
Genus: Ophrys
Family: Orchidaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Ophrys flavicans
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys × flavicans is a hybrid species of orchid found in Spain, the Balearic Islands, France, mainland Italy, Sicily and former Yugoslavia. It is a hybrid between Ophrys bertolonii and Ophrys sphegodes. It has a large number of synonyms, either as other hybrid species, such as Ophrys × drumana and Ophrys × bertoloniiformis, or as infrataxa of other species, such as Ophrys bertolonii subsp. flavicans.
Distribution: Baleares; France; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sicilia; Spain
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2792725 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_%C3%97_flavicans | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+%C3%97+flavicans",ok
450,Ophrys sphegodes (Rchb.f.) A.Bolòs,Ophrys sphegodes,Ophrys,Orchidaceae,incubacea,(Rchb.f.) A.Bolòs,,Not assessed,2793334,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Ophrys sphegodes,https://www.gbif.org/species/2793334,Early spider orchid; Early Spider-Orchid,"Plant 10 - 45 cm. Basal leaves ovate-lanceo­ late, obtuse, usually mucronate. Spike 2 - to 10 - flowered, lax. Perianth-segments glabrous, rarely papillose; outer 6 - 10 (- 12) mm, oblong-ovate to - lanceolate, more or less obtuse, green, rarely purplish or whitish, the median usually narrower; inner perianth-segments 4 - 8 mm, at least 1 / 2 as long as the outer and usually narrower, oblong-triangular to - lanceolate, green, green­ ish-purple or brownish-red, 1 - to 3 - veined, usually with undulate margin. Labellum with margins deflexed or flattened, orbicular to ovate, velutinous, rarely with a small appendage, not globose- inflated; speculum usually H-shaped (the cross-line sometimes absent), rarely scutelliform, bluish-violet or blackish-purple. Connective acute.",CCIII Orchidaceae,eng,Albania; Austria; Baleares; Belgium; Bulgaria; Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia; East Aegean Is.; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Hungary; Iran; Iraq; Italy; Kriti; Krym; Lebanon-Syria,,Ophrys sphegodes,"Ophrys sphegodes, commonly known as the early spider-orchid, is a species of sexually-deceptive orchid native to Europe and the Middle East. It is a highly varied species with many subspecies recognised.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_sphegodes,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+sphegodes,"Plant 10 - 45 cm. Basal leaves ovate-lanceo­ late, obtuse, usually mucronate. Spike 2 - to 10 - flowered, lax. Perianth-segments glabrous, rarely papillose; outer 6 - 10 (- 12) mm, oblong-ovate to - lanceolate, more or less obtuse, green, rarely purplish or whitish, the median usually narrower; inner perianth-segments 4 - 8 mm, at least 1 / 2 as long as the outer and usually narrower, oblong-triangular to - lanceolate, green, green­ ish-purple or brownish-red, 1 - to 3 - veined, usually with undulate margin. Labellum with margins deflexed or flattened, orbicular to ovate, velutinous, rarely with a small appendage, not globose- inflated; speculum usually H-shaped (the cross-line sometimes absent), rarely scutelliform, bluish-violet or blackish-purple. Connective acute.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 450
Scientific name: Ophrys sphegodes
Full species name: Ophrys sphegodes (Rchb.f.) A.Bolòs
Genus: Ophrys
Family: Orchidaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Ophrys sphegodes
Common names: Early spider orchid; Early Spider-Orchid
GBIF description: Plant 10 - 45 cm. Basal leaves ovate-lanceo­ late, obtuse, usually mucronate. Spike 2 - to 10 - flowered, lax. Perianth-segments glabrous, rarely papillose; outer 6 - 10 (- 12) mm, oblong-ovate to - lanceolate, more or less obtuse, green, rarely purplish or whitish, the median usually narrower; inner perianth-segments 4 - 8 mm, at least 1 / 2 as long as the outer and usually narrower, oblong-triangular to - lanceolate, green, green­ ish-purple or brownish-red, 1 - to 3 - veined, usually with undulate margin. Labellum with margins deflexed or flattened, orbicular to ovate, velutinous, rarely with a small appendage, not globose- inflated; speculum usually H-shaped (the cross-line sometimes absent), rarely scutelliform, bluish-violet or blackish-purple. Connective acute.
Wikipedia summary: Ophrys sphegodes, commonly known as the early spider-orchid, is a species of sexually-deceptive orchid native to Europe and the Middle East. It is a highly varied species with many subspecies recognised.
Distribution: Albania; Austria; Baleares; Belgium; Bulgaria; Corse; Cyprus; Czechia-Slovakia; East Aegean Is.; France; Germany; Great Britain; Greece; Hungary; Iran; Iraq; Italy; Kriti; Krym; Lebanon-Syria
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2793334 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophrys_sphegodes | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Ophrys+sphegodes",ok
