Wikipedia summary: Anemonoides apennina, the Apennine anemone or blue anemone, is a flowering plant in the family Ranunculaceae. It is a rhizomatous perennial plant, native to southern central Europe, taking its name from the Apennine Mountains, but widely naturalised elsewhere in Europe, including the United Kingdom. It can be confused with Anemonoides nemorosa which it resembles. It grows to 20 cm. In early spring it produces single blue flowers above ferny foliage, which dies down in summer. The flowers are about 3.5 cm across, with 10-15 narrow petals. The leaves are palmate with dark green 3-lobed, toothed leaflets. The leaves are hairy underneath, which is how this plant may be distinguished from the similar Anemone blanda. It is especially valued for its ability to colonise deciduous woodlands, but it is also found in open scrub, under park trees, and near former habitation. This plant has gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
Distribution: Albania; Austria (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; Corse; Denmark (INTRODUCED); France (INTRODUCED); Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Italy; Kazakhstan; NW. Balkan Pen.; Netherlands (INTRODUCED); Sicilia; Sweden (INTRODUCED); England [I] (England [I], Wales [I], Scotland [I], Isle of Man [I]); Ireland [I] (Ireland [I], Northern Ireland [I]); France [I]; Channel Isl. [I] (Jersey [I], Guernsey [I]); Corsica; Italy; Sicily; Croatia; Bosnia & Hercegovina; Montenegro; Serbia; Kosovo; North Macedonia; Albania; Greece (very rare NW- & C-Greece); AT (PRESENT); Belgium (PRESENT)
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
