470,Pulsatilla montana (Hoppe) Rchb.,Pulsatilla montana,Pulsatilla,Ranunculaceae,montana,(Hoppe) Rchb.,,Not assessed,7277925,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Pulsatilla montana,https://www.gbif.org/species/7277925,Mountain pasqueflower,"Description Pulsatilla montana is a perennial hemicryptophyte characterised by its deeply dissected basal leaves and solitary, nodding, bell-shaped flowers, which are typically dark purple to bluish-purple. The entire plant is densely covered with soft hairs, especially in the early phenological stages. It is one of the earliest flowering Pulsatilla species in Europe (Jäger et al. 2017), with anthesis taking place from March to April.",Notes on the genus Pulsatilla (Ranunculaceae) in Kosovo – Southeast Europe,eng,Bulgaria; France; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Romania; Switzerland; CH,,Pulsatilla,"Pulsatilla is a genus that contains about 40 species of herbaceous perennial plants native to meadows and prairies of North America, Europe, and Asia. Common names include pasque flower, wind flower, prairie crocus, Easter flower, and meadow anemone. Several species are valued ornamentals because of their finely-dissected leaves, solitary bell-shaped flowers, and plumed seed heads. The showy part of the flower consists of sepals, not petals.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulsatilla,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Pulsatilla+montana,"Description Pulsatilla montana is a perennial hemicryptophyte characterised by its deeply dissected basal leaves and solitary, nodding, bell-shaped flowers, which are typically dark purple to bluish-purple. The entire plant is densely covered with soft hairs, especially in the early phenological stages. It is one of the earliest flowering Pulsatilla species in Europe (Jäger et al. 2017), with anthesis taking place from March to April.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 470
Scientific name: Pulsatilla montana
Full species name: Pulsatilla montana (Hoppe) Rchb.
Genus: Pulsatilla
Family: Ranunculaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Pulsatilla montana
Common names: Mountain pasqueflower
GBIF description: Description Pulsatilla montana is a perennial hemicryptophyte characterised by its deeply dissected basal leaves and solitary, nodding, bell-shaped flowers, which are typically dark purple to bluish-purple. The entire plant is densely covered with soft hairs, especially in the early phenological stages. It is one of the earliest flowering Pulsatilla species in Europe (Jäger et al. 2017), with anthesis taking place from March to April.
Wikipedia summary: Pulsatilla is a genus that contains about 40 species of herbaceous perennial plants native to meadows and prairies of North America, Europe, and Asia. Common names include pasque flower, wind flower, prairie crocus, Easter flower, and meadow anemone. Several species are valued ornamentals because of their finely-dissected leaves, solitary bell-shaped flowers, and plumed seed heads. The showy part of the flower consists of sepals, not petals.
Distribution: Bulgaria; France; Greece; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Romania; Switzerland; CH
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/7277925 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulsatilla | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Pulsatilla+montana",ok
