477,Pulsatilla vernalis (L.) Mill.,Pulsatilla vernalis,Pulsatilla,Ranunculaceae,vernalis,(L.) Mill.,,LC,3928615,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Pulsatilla vernalis,https://www.gbif.org/species/3928615,arctic violet; lady of the snows; Spring Pasque Flower,"Distribution and habitat Ecologically, it is native to subalpine to alpine zones and thrives in acidic, nutrient-poor grasslands, heathlands, and alpine meadows. It prefers well-drained, siliceous soils on open, sunny slopes near or above the tree line. It is well adapted to the harsh climate and short growing seasons and flowers soon after the snow melts (Ronikier et al. 2008; Nikolić 2020). In terms of distribution, P. vernalis is widespread in Central and Northern Europe, ranging from the Alps and Carpathians to the Scandinavian mountains. It also occurs sporadically on the Balkan Peninsula (Dakskobler et al. 2008), but is generally considered rare and localised there. Due to habitat loss, climate change, and changes in land use, the species is considered threatened or declining in several parts of its range in Europe (IUCN 2014; Scheuerer 2020). In Kosovo, the taxon has been recorded in the subalpine to alpine silicate grasslands and heathlands, just near the treeline up to the alpine grasslands.",Notes on the genus Pulsatilla (Ranunculaceae) in Kosovo – Southeast Europe,eng,"Albania; Austria; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; Finland; France; Germany; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Northwest European Russia; Norway; Poland; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland; Global (PRESENT); Denmark; Norway; Sweden; Finland; Germany (Brandenburg, +Berlin, Bayern, +Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, +Niedersachsen, +Rheinland-Pfalz, +Sachsen, +Sachsen-Anhalt, Thüringen); Switzerland; Liechtenstein; Austria; Poland; Czech Republic; Slovakia; Spain; Andorra; France; Italy; Slovenia; Croatia; Bosnia & Hercegovina; Montenegro; Serbia; Kosovo; North Macedonia; Bulgaria; C-European Russia; N-European Russia; CH; DE",,Pulsatilla vernalis,"Pulsatilla vernalis is a species of flowering plant in the family Ranunculaceae, native to mountainous habitats in Europe. Growing to 10 cm (4 in) high and wide, it is a semi-evergreen perennial with hairy, divided leaves. In early spring it bears anemone-like flowers which are up to 6 cm (2 in) in diameter, white flushed with violet on the outer surface of the petals, and prominent yellow stamens.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulsatilla_vernalis,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Pulsatilla+vernalis,"Distribution and habitat Ecologically, it is native to subalpine to alpine zones and thrives in acidic, nutrient-poor grasslands, heathlands, and alpine meadows. It prefers well-drained, siliceous soils on open, sunny slopes near or above the tree line. It is well adapted to the harsh climate and short growing seasons and flowers soon after the snow melts (Ronikier et al. 2008; Nikolić 2020). In terms of distribution, P. vernalis is widespread in Central and Northern Europe, ranging from the Alps and Carpathians to the Scandinavian mountains. It also occurs sporadically on the Balkan Peninsula (Dakskobler et al. 2008), but is generally considered rare and localised there. Due to habitat loss, climate change, and changes in land use, the species is considered threatened or declining in several parts of its range in Europe (IUCN 2014; Scheuerer 2020). In Kosovo, the taxon has been recorded in the subalpine to alpine silicate grasslands and heathlands, just near the treeline up to the alpine grasslands.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 477
Scientific name: Pulsatilla vernalis
Full species name: Pulsatilla vernalis (L.) Mill.
Genus: Pulsatilla
Family: Ranunculaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Pulsatilla vernalis
Common names: arctic violet; lady of the snows; Spring Pasque Flower
GBIF description: Distribution and habitat Ecologically, it is native to subalpine to alpine zones and thrives in acidic, nutrient-poor grasslands, heathlands, and alpine meadows. It prefers well-drained, siliceous soils on open, sunny slopes near or above the tree line. It is well adapted to the harsh climate and short growing seasons and flowers soon after the snow melts (Ronikier et al. 2008; Nikolić 2020). In terms of distribution, P. vernalis is widespread in Central and Northern Europe, ranging from the Alps and Carpathians to the Scandinavian mountains. It also occurs sporadically on the Balkan Peninsula (Dakskobler et al. 2008), but is generally considered rare and localised there. Due to habitat loss, climate change, and changes in land use, the species is considered threatened or declining in several parts of its range in Europe (IUCN 2014; Scheuerer 2020). In Kosovo, the taxon has been recorded in the subalpine to alpine silicate grasslands and heathlands, just near the treeline up to the alpine grasslands.
Wikipedia summary: Pulsatilla vernalis is a species of flowering plant in the family Ranunculaceae, native to mountainous habitats in Europe. Growing to 10 cm (4 in) high and wide, it is a semi-evergreen perennial with hairy, divided leaves. In early spring it bears anemone-like flowers which are up to 6 cm (2 in) in diameter, white flushed with violet on the outer surface of the petals, and prominent yellow stamens.
Distribution: Albania; Austria; Bulgaria; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; Finland; France; Germany; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Northwest European Russia; Norway; Poland; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland; Global (PRESENT); Denmark; Norway; Sweden; Finland; Germany (Brandenburg, +Berlin, Bayern, +Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, +Niedersachsen, +Rheinland-Pfalz, +Sachsen, +Sachsen-Anhalt, Thüringen); Switzerland; Liechtenstein; Austria; Poland; Czech Republic; Slovakia; Spain; Andorra; France; Italy; Slovenia; Croatia; Bosnia & Hercegovina; Montenegro; Serbia; Kosovo; North Macedonia; Bulgaria; C-European Russia; N-European Russia; CH; DE
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3928615 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulsatilla_vernalis | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Pulsatilla+vernalis",ok
478,Angelica heterocarpa M.J.Lloyd,Angelica heterocarpa,Angelica,Apiaceae,heterocarpa,M.J.Lloyd,,LC,5928331,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Angelica heterocarpa,https://www.gbif.org/species/5928331,,,,,Global (PRESENT); FR,,Angelica,"Angelica is a genus of about 90 species of tall biennial and perennial herbs in the family Apiaceae, native to temperate and subarctic regions of the Northern Hemisphere, reaching as far north as Iceland, Sápmi, and Greenland. They grow to 1–3 m tall, with large bipinnate leaves and large compound umbels of white or greenish-white flowers. It shows variations in fruit anatomy, leaf morphology, and subterranean structures. The genes are extremely polymorphic.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelica,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Angelica+heterocarpa,"Angelica is a genus of about 90 species of tall biennial and perennial herbs in the family Apiaceae, native to temperate and subarctic regions of the Northern Hemisphere, reaching as far north as Iceland, Sápmi, and Greenland. They grow to 1–3 m tall, with large bipinnate leaves and large compound umbels of white or greenish-white flowers. It shows variations in fruit anatomy, leaf morphology, and subterranean structures. The genes are extremely polymorphic.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 478
