480,Angelica sylvestris L.,Angelica sylvestris,Angelica,Apiaceae,sylvestris,L.,,LC,5371818,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Angelica sylvestris,https://www.gbif.org/species/5371818,Wild Angelica,"Note: Angelica sylvestris, with Herb. Clifford: 97, Angelica 2 (BM) as the type, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Reduron & Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 557. 1992). However, the proposal was eventually ruled unnecessary by the General Committee (see Barrie, l. c. 55: 795 - 796. 2006 for a review of the history of this and related proposals). When Reduron & Jarvis (l. c. 41: 557. 1992) proposed the Clifford sheet as a conserved type, they were unaware of the earlier typification made by Gutierrez Bustillo (1981) based on 354.3 (LINN). Unfortunately, this specimen is identifiable as A. montana Brot. (sometimes recognised as a subspecies of A. sylvestris). With the failure of the generitype proposal, the type of A. sylvestris is now 354.3 (LINN). While Art. 57 provides some protection to the usage of A. sylvestris in its traditional sense, it seems that a proposal for its conservation with a conserved type is now necessary.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part A),eng,Nord Odal; Lunde; Jølster; Uvdal; Brekken; Meråker; Eid; Nord Vågsøy; Skånland; Velfjord; Vik; Volda; Østlandet; Sigdal; Vestre Sildre; North America (PRESENT); Albania; Altay; Austria; Baltic States,habitat: Terrestrial,Angelica sylvestris,"Angelica sylvestris or wild angelica is a species of flowering plant, native to Europe and central Asia. An annual or short-lived perennial growing to a maximum of 2.5 m (8.2 ft), it has erect purplish stems and rounded umbels of minuscule white or pale pink flowers in late summer.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelica_sylvestris,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Angelica+sylvestris,"Note: Angelica sylvestris, with Herb. Clifford: 97, Angelica 2 (BM) as the type, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Reduron & Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 557. 1992). However, the proposal was eventually ruled unnecessary by the General Committee (see Barrie, l. c. 55: 795 - 796. 2006 for a review of the history of this and related proposals). When Reduron & Jarvis (l. c. 41: 557. 1992) proposed the Clifford sheet as a conserved type, they were unaware of the earlier typification made by Gutierrez Bustillo (1981) based on 354.3 (LINN). Unfortunately, this specimen is identifiable as A. montana Brot. (sometimes recognised as a subspecies of A. sylvestris). With the failure of the generitype proposal, the type of A. sylvestris is now 354.3 (LINN). While Art. 57 provides some protection to the usage of A. sylvestris in its traditional sense, it seems that a proposal for its conservation with a conserved type is now necessary.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 480
Scientific name: Angelica sylvestris
Full species name: Angelica sylvestris L.
Genus: Angelica
Family: Apiaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Angelica sylvestris
Common names: Wild Angelica
GBIF description: Note: Angelica sylvestris, with Herb. Clifford: 97, Angelica 2 (BM) as the type, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Reduron & Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 557. 1992). However, the proposal was eventually ruled unnecessary by the General Committee (see Barrie, l. c. 55: 795 - 796. 2006 for a review of the history of this and related proposals). When Reduron & Jarvis (l. c. 41: 557. 1992) proposed the Clifford sheet as a conserved type, they were unaware of the earlier typification made by Gutierrez Bustillo (1981) based on 354.3 (LINN). Unfortunately, this specimen is identifiable as A. montana Brot. (sometimes recognised as a subspecies of A. sylvestris). With the failure of the generitype proposal, the type of A. sylvestris is now 354.3 (LINN). While Art. 57 provides some protection to the usage of A. sylvestris in its traditional sense, it seems that a proposal for its conservation with a conserved type is now necessary.
Wikipedia summary: Angelica sylvestris or wild angelica is a species of flowering plant, native to Europe and central Asia. An annual or short-lived perennial growing to a maximum of 2.5 m (8.2 ft), it has erect purplish stems and rounded umbels of minuscule white or pale pink flowers in late summer.
Distribution: Nord Odal; Lunde; Jølster; Uvdal; Brekken; Meråker; Eid; Nord Vågsøy; Skånland; Velfjord; Vik; Volda; Østlandet; Sigdal; Vestre Sildre; North America (PRESENT); Albania; Altay; Austria; Baltic States
