483,Anthericum ramosum L.,Anthericum ramosum,Anthericum,Asparagaceae,ramosum,L.,,Not assessed,2773942,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Anthericum ramosum,https://www.gbif.org/species/2773942,Branched St Bernard's Lily; Branched St Bernard's-lily; branched St. Bernard's-lily,"A new record for the Greek flora. Anthericum ramosum , the generitype of Anthericum L., has a predominantly central European distribution that reaches parts of Russia and Asiatic Turkey to the East (Webb 1980, Matthews 1984). Although reported “ in Europae australioris ” by Linnaeus (1762) (type: Herb. Linn. no. 432.6, LINN !, see Jarvis et al. 1993) it has not been reported in Greece so far. Our specimen from the foothills of Mt. Orvilos (Fig. 1), at a linear distance of ca. 5.5 km south of the Greek-Bulgarian border, has a paniculate inflorescence with 2-6, 6.5-11 cm long branches, white tepals 9-12 mm long, a straight style and an almost spherical, obtuse capsule 5-5.5 x 4.5-6 mm with a short remnant of the style base. It differs considerably from A. liliago L., which is widespread in Greece, being reported from the south mainland (north Peloponnisos) to the northern borders (Andersson 1991a). The latter has a simple or sparingly branched inflorescence, larger tepals (13-20 mm), a somewhat curved style and a longer (8-11 x 6-7 mm) capsule with an acute apex.",Thirty-two new and noteworthy floristic records from north-eastern Greece,eng,Albania; Austria; Baltic States; Belarus; Bulgaria; Central European Russia; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; France; Germany; Greece; Hungary; Krym; NW. Balkan Pen.; North Caucasus; Poland; Romania; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland,,Anthericum ramosum,"Anthericum ramosum, known as branched St Bernard's-lily, is a herbaceous perennial plant with a rhizome. The genus Anthericum is currently placed in the family Asparagaceae, subfamily Agavoideae. It was formerly placed in its own family, Anthericaceae, and before that in the Liliaceae.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthericum_ramosum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Anthericum+ramosum,"A new record for the Greek flora. Anthericum ramosum , the generitype of Anthericum L., has a predominantly central European distribution that reaches parts of Russia and Asiatic Turkey to the East (Webb 1980, Matthews 1984). Although reported “ in Europae australioris ” by Linnaeus (1762) (type: Herb. Linn. no. 432.6, LINN !, see Jarvis et al. 1993) it has not been reported in Greece so far. Our specimen from the foothills of Mt. Orvilos (Fig. 1), at a linear distance of ca. 5.5 km south of the Greek-Bulgarian border, has a paniculate inflorescence with 2-6, 6.5-11 cm long branches, white tepals 9-12 mm long, a straight style and an almost spherical, obtuse capsule 5-5.5 x 4.5-6 mm with a short remnant of the style base. It differs considerably from A. liliago L., which is widespread in Greece, being reported from the south mainland (north Peloponnisos) to the northern borders (Andersson 1991a). The latter has a simple or sparingly branched inflorescence, larger tepals (13-20 mm), a somewhat curved style and a longer (8-11 x 6-7 mm) capsule with an acute apex.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 483
Scientific name: Anthericum ramosum
Full species name: Anthericum ramosum L.
Genus: Anthericum
Family: Asparagaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Anthericum ramosum
Common names: Branched St Bernard's Lily; Branched St Bernard's-lily; branched St. Bernard's-lily
GBIF description: A new record for the Greek flora. Anthericum ramosum , the generitype of Anthericum L., has a predominantly central European distribution that reaches parts of Russia and Asiatic Turkey to the East (Webb 1980, Matthews 1984). Although reported “ in Europae australioris ” by Linnaeus (1762) (type: Herb. Linn. no. 432.6, LINN !, see Jarvis et al. 1993) it has not been reported in Greece so far. Our specimen from the foothills of Mt. Orvilos (Fig. 1), at a linear distance of ca. 5.5 km south of the Greek-Bulgarian border, has a paniculate inflorescence with 2-6, 6.5-11 cm long branches, white tepals 9-12 mm long, a straight style and an almost spherical, obtuse capsule 5-5.5 x 4.5-6 mm with a short remnant of the style base. It differs considerably from A. liliago L., which is widespread in Greece, being reported from the south mainland (north Peloponnisos) to the northern borders (Andersson 1991a). The latter has a simple or sparingly branched inflorescence, larger tepals (13-20 mm), a somewhat curved style and a longer (8-11 x 6-7 mm) capsule with an acute apex.
Wikipedia summary: Anthericum ramosum, known as branched St Bernard's-lily, is a herbaceous perennial plant with a rhizome. The genus Anthericum is currently placed in the family Asparagaceae, subfamily Agavoideae. It was formerly placed in its own family, Anthericaceae, and before that in the Liliaceae.
Distribution: Albania; Austria; Baltic States; Belarus; Bulgaria; Central European Russia; Czechia-Slovakia; Denmark; France; Germany; Greece; Hungary; Krym; NW. Balkan Pen.; North Caucasus; Poland; Romania; Spain; Sweden; Switzerland
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2773942 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthericum_ramosum | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Anthericum+ramosum",ok
484,Pyracantha coccinea M.Roem.,Pyracantha coccinea,Pyracantha,Rosaceae,coccinea,M.Roem.,,Not assessed,2988188,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Pyracantha coccinea,https://www.gbif.org/species/2988188,buisson ardent; Firethorn; pyracanth; Red Firethorn; Scarlet firethorn,"Note: Munoz Garmendia & Aedo typified the name in a proposal to conserve P. coccinea M. Roem., which is a nomen novum based on this Linnaean name.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part M),eng,Bogotá (INTRODUCED); North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania; Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); British Columbia (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Corse (INTRODUCED); France; Free State (INTRODUCED); Georgia (INTRODUCED); Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Indiana (INTRODUCED); Iran; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Italy,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Arbusto""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Pyracantha coccinea,"Pyracantha coccinea, the scarlet firethorn is the European species of firethorn or red firethorn that has been cultivated in gardens since the late 16th century. The tree has small white flowers. It produces small, bright red berries. Its leaves are slightly toothed and grow opposite to one another. The fruit is bitter and astringent, making it inedible when raw. The fruit can be cooked to make jellies, jams, sauces and marmalade. It ranges from southern Europe to western Asia. It has been introduced to North America and cultivated there as an ornamental plant since the 18th century.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyracantha_coccinea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Pyracantha+coccinea,"Note: Munoz Garmendia & Aedo typified the name in a proposal to conserve P. coccinea M. Roem., which is a nomen novum based on this Linnaean name.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 484
Scientific name: Pyracantha coccinea
Full species name: Pyracantha coccinea M.Roem.
Genus: Pyracantha
Family: Rosaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Pyracantha coccinea
Common names: buisson ardent; Firethorn; pyracanth; Red Firethorn; Scarlet firethorn
GBIF description: Note: Munoz Garmendia & Aedo typified the name in a proposal to conserve P. coccinea M. Roem., which is a nomen novum based on this Linnaean name.
Wikipedia summary: Pyracantha coccinea, the scarlet firethorn is the European species of firethorn or red firethorn that has been cultivated in gardens since the late 16th century. The tree has small white flowers. It produces small, bright red berries. Its leaves are slightly toothed and grow opposite to one another. The fruit is bitter and astringent, making it inedible when raw. The fruit can be cooked to make jellies, jams, sauces and marmalade. It ranges from southern Europe to western Asia. It has been introduced to North America and cultivated there as an ornamental plant since the 18th century.
Distribution: Bogotá (INTRODUCED); North America (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania; Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); British Columbia (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; California (INTRODUCED); Corse (INTRODUCED); France; Free State (INTRODUCED); Georgia (INTRODUCED); Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Greece; Indiana (INTRODUCED); Iran; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Italy
