504,Tradescantia virginiana L.,Tradescantia virginiana,Tradescantia,Commelinaceae,virginiana,L.,,Not assessed,2765272,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Tradescantia virginiana,https://www.gbif.org/species/2765272,Spider Lily; Spiderwort; Virginia Spiderwort; White Spiderwort; Widow's-tears,"Note: This name presents particular difficulties because the original material, 406.1 (LINN) and Herb. Burser III: 104 b (UPS), is identifiable as Tradescantia ohiensis Raf. As noted by Jarvis & al. (Regnum Veg. 127: 6. 1993), their Linnaean Generic List was conceived as a possible "" Names in Current Use "" (NCU) List which, if the concept had been adopted, could have allowed types listed there some protection. With this in mind, Reveal there (p. 95) designated a neotype from Virginia. However, as the NCU proposals were not adopted, this neotypification is invalid, because original material is in existence. It appears that a conservation proposal is necessary if the application of T. virginiana is not to change.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part T),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Arkansas (DOUBTFUL); California (INTRODUCED); Connecticut; Cuba; Delaware; France (INTRODUCED); Georgia; Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Illinois; Indiana; Iowa; Italy (INTRODUCED); Kentucky; Louisiana; Madeira (INTRODUCED); Maine; Maryland,habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Tradescantia virginiana,"Tradescantia virginiana, the Virginia spiderwort, is a species of flowering plant in the family Commelinaceae. It is the type species of the genus Tradescantia, native to the eastern United States. Common names include Virginia spiderwort, common spiderwort, lady's tears, and spider lily.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tradescantia_virginiana,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Tradescantia+virginiana,"Note: This name presents particular difficulties because the original material, 406.1 (LINN) and Herb. Burser III: 104 b (UPS), is identifiable as Tradescantia ohiensis Raf. As noted by Jarvis & al. (Regnum Veg. 127: 6. 1993), their Linnaean Generic List was conceived as a possible "" Names in Current Use "" (NCU) List which, if the concept had been adopted, could have allowed types listed there some protection. With this in mind, Reveal there (p. 95) designated a neotype from Virginia. However, as the NCU proposals were not adopted, this neotypification is invalid, because original material is in existence. It appears that a conservation proposal is necessary if the application of T. virginiana is not to change.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 504
Scientific name: Tradescantia virginiana
Full species name: Tradescantia virginiana L.
Genus: Tradescantia
Family: Commelinaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Tradescantia virginiana
Common names: Spider Lily; Spiderwort; Virginia Spiderwort; White Spiderwort; Widow's-tears
GBIF description: Note: This name presents particular difficulties because the original material, 406.1 (LINN) and Herb. Burser III: 104 b (UPS), is identifiable as Tradescantia ohiensis Raf. As noted by Jarvis & al. (Regnum Veg. 127: 6. 1993), their Linnaean Generic List was conceived as a possible "" Names in Current Use "" (NCU) List which, if the concept had been adopted, could have allowed types listed there some protection. With this in mind, Reveal there (p. 95) designated a neotype from Virginia. However, as the NCU proposals were not adopted, this neotypification is invalid, because original material is in existence. It appears that a conservation proposal is necessary if the application of T. virginiana is not to change.
Wikipedia summary: Tradescantia virginiana, the Virginia spiderwort, is a species of flowering plant in the family Commelinaceae. It is the type species of the genus Tradescantia, native to the eastern United States. Common names include Virginia spiderwort, common spiderwort, lady's tears, and spider lily.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Arkansas (DOUBTFUL); California (INTRODUCED); Connecticut; Cuba; Delaware; France (INTRODUCED); Georgia; Germany (INTRODUCED); Great Britain (INTRODUCED); Illinois; Indiana; Iowa; Italy (INTRODUCED); Kentucky; Louisiana; Madeira (INTRODUCED); Maine; Maryland
