513,Eriocapitella vitifolia (Buch.-Ham. ex DC.) Nakai,Eriocapitella vitifolia,Eriocapitella,Ranunculaceae,vitifolia,(Buch.-Ham. ex DC.) Nakai,,Not assessed,3925297,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Eriocapitella vitifolia,https://www.gbif.org/species/3925297,grape-leaved anemone; grape-leaved windflower,,,,"China South-Central; East Himalaya; Myanmar; Nepal; Pakistan; Tibet; West Himalaya; China (SW-Sichuan, Yunnan); S-Tibet; Pakistan (Hazara, Murree); Nepal; Bhutan; India (Arunachal Pradesh, Assam, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu & Kashmir, Sikkim, Uttarakhand, West Bengal); N-Myanmar (Kachin); Philippines (Luzon); NO",,Eriocapitella vitifolia,"Eriocapitella vitifolia, a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family Ranunculaceae, is native to Asia. The specific epithet vitifolia means ""vine-leaved, with leaves resembling those of Vitis"", the genus of grapevines, and so the plant is commonly called the grape-leaved anemone or grape-leaved windflower. In Chinese, a common name is ye mian hua, which means ""wild cotton"".",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eriocapitella_vitifolia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Eriocapitella+vitifolia,"Eriocapitella vitifolia, a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family Ranunculaceae, is native to Asia. The specific epithet vitifolia means ""vine-leaved, with leaves resembling those of Vitis"", the genus of grapevines, and so the plant is commonly called the grape-leaved anemone or grape-leaved windflower. In Chinese, a common name is ye mian hua, which means ""wild cotton"".",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 513
