Wikipedia summary: Eriocapitella vitifolia, a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family Ranunculaceae, is native to Asia. The specific epithet vitifolia means ""vine-leaved, with leaves resembling those of Vitis"", the genus of grapevines, and so the plant is commonly called the grape-leaved anemone or grape-leaved windflower. In Chinese, a common name is ye mian hua, which means ""wild cotton"".
Distribution: China South-Central; East Himalaya; Myanmar; Nepal; Pakistan; Tibet; West Himalaya; China (SW-Sichuan, Yunnan); S-Tibet; Pakistan (Hazara, Murree); Nepal; Bhutan; India (Arunachal Pradesh, Assam, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu & Kashmir, Sikkim, Uttarakhand, West Bengal); N-Myanmar (Kachin); Philippines (Luzon); NO
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3925297 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eriocapitella_vitifolia | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Eriocapitella+vitifolia",ok
514,Adenostyles alpina (L.) Bluff & Fingerh.,Adenostyles alpina,Adenostyles,Asteraceae,alpina,(L.) Bluff & Fingerh.,,Not assessed,3133705,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Adenostyles alpina,https://www.gbif.org/species/3133705,,"Note: Cacalia alpina, with the type designated by Jeffrey, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 559. 1992). The Committee for Spermatophyta, however, noting that conservation would result in Cacalia displacing Adenostyles Cass., voted (see Taxon 44: 612. 1995) not to accept the proposal. Wagenitz (in Taxon 44: 445. 1995) subsequently proposed the rejection of Cacalia, with C. alpina as type, recommended by the Committee for Spermatophyta (in Taxon 47: 444. 1998).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part C),eng,Albania; Austria; France; Germany; Italy; NW. Balkan Pen.; Sicilia; Spain; Switzerland; Austria (PRESENT); Germany (PRESENT); Switzerland (PRESENT); Yugoslavia (PRESENT); Liechtenstein (PRESENT); Croatia (PRESENT); Slovenia (PRESENT); CH; DE; France (PRESENT); Channel Is. (PRESENT),,Adenostyles alpina,Adenostyles alpina is herbaceous perennial plant belonging to the genus Adenostyles of the family Asteraceae. It is native to the Alps and southern Europe.,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenostyles_alpina,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Adenostyles+alpina,"Note: Cacalia alpina, with the type designated by Jeffrey, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 559. 1992). The Committee for Spermatophyta, however, noting that conservation would result in Cacalia displacing Adenostyles Cass., voted (see Taxon 44: 612. 1995) not to accept the proposal. Wagenitz (in Taxon 44: 445. 1995) subsequently proposed the rejection of Cacalia, with C. alpina as type, recommended by the Committee for Spermatophyta (in Taxon 47: 444. 1998).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 514
Scientific name: Adenostyles alpina
Full species name: Adenostyles alpina (L.) Bluff & Fingerh.
Genus: Adenostyles
Family: Asteraceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Adenostyles alpina
GBIF description: Note: Cacalia alpina, with the type designated by Jeffrey, was proposed as conserved type of the genus by Jarvis (in Taxon 41: 559. 1992). The Committee for Spermatophyta, however, noting that conservation would result in Cacalia displacing Adenostyles Cass., voted (see Taxon 44: 612. 1995) not to accept the proposal. Wagenitz (in Taxon 44: 445. 1995) subsequently proposed the rejection of Cacalia, with C. alpina as type, recommended by the Committee for Spermatophyta (in Taxon 47: 444. 1998).
Wikipedia summary: Adenostyles alpina is herbaceous perennial plant belonging to the genus Adenostyles of the family Asteraceae. It is native to the Alps and southern Europe.
