Wikipedia summary: Angelica archangelica, commonly known as angelica, garden angelica, wild celery, and Norwegian angelica, is a biennial plant from the family Apiaceae, a subspecies of which is cultivated for its sweetly scented edible stems and roots. Like several other species in Apiaceae, its appearance is similar to several poisonous species, and should not be consumed unless it has been identified with absolute certainty. Synonyms include Archangelica officinalis Hoffm. and Angelica officinalis Moench.
Distribution: Nordland; North America (PRESENT); Albania; Baltic States; Belarus; Belgium (INTRODUCED); Bulgaria; Central European Russia; Czechia-Slovakia (INTRODUCED); Denmark; East European Russia; Finland; France; Føroyar; Germany; Great Britain; Greenland; Iceland; Ireland (INTRODUCED); Nepal (INTRODUCED)
