Wikipedia summary: Cymbalaria muralis, commonly called ivy-leaved toadflax, is a low, spreading, trailing plant with small purple flowers, native to rocky habitats in southern Europe. It belongs to the plantain family (Plantaginaceae), and is introduced and naturalised in many other temperate locations. The flower stalk is unusual for seeking light until it is fertilized, after which it grows away from the light. Other names include coliseum ivy, Kenilworth ivy, mother of thousands, Oxford ivy, and wandering sailor.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Chía, vereda Yerbabuena, Sede del Instituto Caro y Cuervo; Bogotá (INTRODUCED); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania (INTRODUCED); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Austria; Azores (INTRODUCED); Baleares (INTRODUCED); Baltic States (INTRODUCED); Belgium (INTRODUCED); Bermuda (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED); Brazil Southeast (INTRODUCED); Brazil South (INTRODUCED)
