599,Guarea gomma Pulle,Guarea gomma,Guarea,Meliaceae,gomma,Pulle,,LC,3852128,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Guarea gomma,https://www.gbif.org/species/3852128,,El tallo se usa como larguero o tablas en la construcción de viviendas.,Listado de plantas de uso y aprovechamiento sostenible en Ecuador,,"Parque Nacional Natutral de Amacayacu | Parque Nacional Natural Yaigojé Apaporis | Santuario de Flora Plantas Medicinales Orito Ingi - Ande | Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (NATIVE); Bolivia; Brazil North; Brazil West-Central; Colombia; Ecuador; French Guiana; Guyana; Peru; Suriname; Venezuela; Global (PRESENT); Colombia (Amazonas, Caquetá, Putumayo, Vaupés); Venezuela (Bolívar); ?Guyana; Surinam; French Guiana; Ecuador; Peru; Bolivia (Beni, Cochabamba, La Paz, Pando); N-Brazil (Amazonas, Acre); Leticia; BR (NATIVE); Amazonas, Caquetá, Putumayo, Vaupés (NATIVE); Ecuador (PRESENT)","lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Árvore""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Floresta de Terra Firme"",""Floresta de Várzea""]}; lifeForm: Arbusto, Arbolito, Árbol",Guarea,"Guarea is a genus of evergreen trees or shrubs in the family Meliaceae, native to tropical Africa and Central and South America. At their largest, they are large trees 20–45 m tall, with a trunk over 1 m diameter, often buttressed at the base. The leaves are pinnate, with 4–6 pairs of leaflets, the terminal leaflet present. They are dioecious, with male and female flowers on separate plants. The flowers are produced in loose inflorescences, each flower small, with 4–5 yellowish petals. The fruit is a four or five-valved capsule, containing several seeds, each surrounded by a yellow-orange fleshy aril; the seeds are dispersed by hornbills and monkeys which eat the aril.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guarea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Guarea+gomma,El tallo se usa como larguero o tablas en la construcción de viviendas.,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 599
