Common names: Cantaloupe; Hami melon; honeydew; Melon; Melons; musk melon; muskmelon; Oriental melon; Rock melon
GBIF description: Lectotype (Jeffrey, Cucurbitaceae Eastern Asia: 20. 1980): [icon] "" Melo variegatus, Aurantii figura, odoratissimus "" in Dillenius, Hort. Eltham. 2: 223, t. 177, f. 218. 1732. - Typotype: Herb. Dillenius (OXF).
Wikipedia summary: Cucumis melo, also known as melon or true melon, is a species of Cucumis that has been developed into many cultivated varieties. The fruit is a pepo. The flesh is either sweet or bland, with or without an aroma, and the rind can be smooth, ribbed, wrinkled, or netted. The species is sometimes referred to as muskmelon. However, there is no consensus about the usage of this term, as it can also be used as a specific name for the musky netted-rind American cantaloupe, or as a generic name for any sweet-flesh variety such the inodorous smooth-rind honeydew melon.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Bucaramanga; Distrito Regional de Manejo Integrado (DRMI) Laguna de Sonso, municipio de Guadalajara de Buga, Valle del Cauca, Colombia; Complejo Humedales Hato Corozal. Cienaga Zapatosa; Africa (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Afghanistan; Alabama (INTRODUCED); Albania (INTRODUCED); Algeria (INTRODUCED); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Angola; Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northwest (INTRODUCED); Arizona (INTRODUCED); Arkansas (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Austria (INTRODUCED)
