635,Eranthemum pulchellum Andrews,Eranthemum pulchellum,Eranthemum,Acanthaceae,pulchellum,Andrews,,Not assessed,3172936,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Eranthemum pulchellum,https://www.gbif.org/species/3172936,Blue-Sage,Nativa de Asia tropical,"Especies introducidas, exóticas, trasplantadas, invasoras y potencialmente invasoras obtenidas a partir de fuentes primarias y secundarias, incorporadas en el diagnóstico del Plan Nacional de Prevención, Control y Manejo",,Assam; Bangladesh; China South-Central; Cuba (INTRODUCED); Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; El Salvador (INTRODUCED); Florida (INTRODUCED); Haiti (INTRODUCED); India; Jamaica (INTRODUCED); Laos; Leeward Is. (INTRODUCED); Marianas (INTRODUCED); Myanmar; Nepal; New Caledonia (INTRODUCED); Pakistan; Solomon Is. (INTRODUCED); Suriname (INTRODUCED),"habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: Subarbusto; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Arbusto""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}",Eranthemum pulchellum,"Eranthemum pulchellum, the blue eranthemum or blue sage, is a species of flowering plant in the acanthus family Acanthaceae, native to the Himalayas, western China, India and Nepal. A strongly branched evergreen shrub, it is popular with gardeners because of the spikes of flowers that are bright gentian blue – an unusual color in the tropics. The flowers appear from green-and-white veined bracts that remain after the blooms fall, forming a column several centimetres long. The hairy leaves are large and dark green. A sprawling shrub which may reach a metre or more in height, E. pulchellum is usually kept lower and bushier through pruning. Light shade is preferred in a garden; in a greenhouse it needs warm conditions. It is easily propagated from cuttings.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eranthemum_pulchellum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Eranthemum+pulchellum,Nativa de Asia tropical,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 635
