Family: Acanthaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Eranthemum pulchellum
Common names: Blue-Sage
GBIF description: Nativa de Asia tropical
Wikipedia summary: Eranthemum pulchellum, the blue eranthemum or blue sage, is a species of flowering plant in the acanthus family Acanthaceae, native to the Himalayas, western China, India and Nepal. A strongly branched evergreen shrub, it is popular with gardeners because of the spikes of flowers that are bright gentian blue – an unusual color in the tropics. The flowers appear from green-and-white veined bracts that remain after the blooms fall, forming a column several centimetres long. The hairy leaves are large and dark green. A sprawling shrub which may reach a metre or more in height, E. pulchellum is usually kept lower and bushier through pruning. Light shade is preferred in a garden; in a greenhouse it needs warm conditions. It is easily propagated from cuttings.
Distribution: Assam; Bangladesh; China South-Central; Cuba (INTRODUCED); Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; El Salvador (INTRODUCED); Florida (INTRODUCED); Haiti (INTRODUCED); India; Jamaica (INTRODUCED); Laos; Leeward Is. (INTRODUCED); Marianas (INTRODUCED); Myanmar; Nepal; New Caledonia (INTRODUCED); Pakistan; Solomon Is. (INTRODUCED); Suriname (INTRODUCED)
