636,Alocasia cucullata (Lour.) G.Don,Alocasia cucullata,Alocasia,Araceae,cucullata,(Lour.) G.Don,,Not assessed,5329867,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Alocasia cucullata,https://www.gbif.org/species/5329867,Buddha's hand; Chinese ape; Chinese Taro,"Small to medium sized, somewhat robust, evergreen, clumping herb to 1 m. Stems erect, hypogeal, basally much–branched. Leaves many together; petiole weakly D-shaped in cross-section, 25–30(–80) cm; petiolar sheath reaching to ca ½ way, margins membranous; leaf blade broadly ovate-cordate, 10–40 × 7–28 cm, apex acute, base shallowly cordate; primary veins 4 on each side, radiating from petiole, arching; interprimary veins not forming a collecting vein; secondary veins rather obscure. Inflorescences rarely produced, usually solitary, sometimes paired, among the leaf bases, subtended by membranous cataphylls; peduncle 20–30 cm; spathe 9–15 cm long, green; lower spathe 4–8 × ca 2.5 cm; spathe limb narrowly cymbiform, 5–10 × 3–5 cm; spadix 8–14 cm; pistillate flower zone cylindrical, 1.5–2.5 cm × 7 mm; sterile interstice 2–3 cm × 3 mm. staminate flower zone 34 × 8 mm, yellow; appendix narrowly conical ca 35 × 5 mm, yellowish; fruit rarely produced, a subglobose berry, 6–8 mm diam., ripening red.",CATE Araceae,eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Assam; Bangladesh; Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); China South-Central; China Southeast; Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Costa Rica (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; Hainan; Honduras (INTRODUCED); Japan (INTRODUCED); Laos; Myanmar; Nansei-shoto (INTRODUCED); Ogasawara-shoto (INTRODUCED); Sri Lanka; Taiwan,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Alocasia cucullata,"Alocasia cucullata is a species of flowering plant in the arum family, Araceae. It is known by the common names Chinese taro, Chinese ape, Buddha's hand, and hooded dwarf elephant ear. It is kept as an ornamental plant.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alocasia_cucullata,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Alocasia+cucullata,"Small to medium sized, somewhat robust, evergreen, clumping herb to 1 m. Stems erect, hypogeal, basally much–branched. Leaves many together; petiole weakly D-shaped in cross-section, 25–30(–80) cm; petiolar sheath reaching to ca ½ way, margins membranous; leaf blade broadly ovate-cordate, 10–40 × 7–28 cm, apex acute, base shallowly cordate; primary veins 4 on each side, radiating from petiole, arching; interprimary veins not forming a collecting vein; secondary veins rather obscure. Inflorescences rarely produced, usually solitary, sometimes paired, among the leaf bases, subtended by membranous cataphylls; peduncle 20–30 cm; spathe 9–15 cm long, green; lower spathe 4–8 × ca 2.5 cm; spathe limb narrowly cymbiform, 5–10 × 3–5 cm; spadix 8–14 cm; pistillate flower zone cylindrical, 1.5–2.5 cm × 7 mm; sterile interstice 2–3 cm × 3 mm. staminate flower zone 34 × 8 mm, yellow; appendix narrowly conical ca 35 × 5 mm, yellowish; fruit rarely produced, a subglobose berry, 6–8 mm diam., ripening red.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 636
Scientific name: Alocasia cucullata
Full species name: Alocasia cucullata (Lour.) G.Don
Genus: Alocasia
Family: Araceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Alocasia cucullata
Common names: Buddha's hand; Chinese ape; Chinese Taro
GBIF description: Small to medium sized, somewhat robust, evergreen, clumping herb to 1 m. Stems erect, hypogeal, basally much–branched. Leaves many together; petiole weakly D-shaped in cross-section, 25–30(–80) cm; petiolar sheath reaching to ca ½ way, margins membranous; leaf blade broadly ovate-cordate, 10–40 × 7–28 cm, apex acute, base shallowly cordate; primary veins 4 on each side, radiating from petiole, arching; interprimary veins not forming a collecting vein; secondary veins rather obscure. Inflorescences rarely produced, usually solitary, sometimes paired, among the leaf bases, subtended by membranous cataphylls; peduncle 20–30 cm; spathe 9–15 cm long, green; lower spathe 4–8 × ca 2.5 cm; spathe limb narrowly cymbiform, 5–10 × 3–5 cm; spadix 8–14 cm; pistillate flower zone cylindrical, 1.5–2.5 cm × 7 mm; sterile interstice 2–3 cm × 3 mm. staminate flower zone 34 × 8 mm, yellow; appendix narrowly conical ca 35 × 5 mm, yellowish; fruit rarely produced, a subglobose berry, 6–8 mm diam., ripening red.
Wikipedia summary: Alocasia cucullata is a species of flowering plant in the arum family, Araceae. It is known by the common names Chinese taro, Chinese ape, Buddha's hand, and hooded dwarf elephant ear. It is kept as an ornamental plant.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Assam; Bangladesh; Caroline Is. (INTRODUCED); China South-Central; China Southeast; Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Costa Rica (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya; Hainan; Honduras (INTRODUCED); Japan (INTRODUCED); Laos; Myanmar; Nansei-shoto (INTRODUCED); Ogasawara-shoto (INTRODUCED); Sri Lanka; Taiwan
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
