nt), native to tropical Africa and the Indian Subcontinent. It can also be found growing abundantly in much of Latin America, Southeast Asia, the West Indies, and the Southeastern United States. It grows to a height of 3 metres and has whorls of striking lipped flowers, that are most commonly orange, but can vary to red, white, and purple. It has drooping dark green, very soft serrated leaves that can grow up to 10 centimetres (4 in) wide. Sunbirds and ants are attracted to the flowers. It has been found growing on roadsides, rubbish heaps or waste land.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonotis_nepetifolia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Leonotis+nepetifolia,"Lectotype (Iwarsson in Leistner, Fl. Southern Africa 28 (4): 37. 1985): [icon] "" Cardiaca Americana annua Nepetae folio, floribus brevibus phoeniceis villosis "" in Hermann, Hort. Lugd. - Bat. Cat.: 115, 117. 1687.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 646
