Wikipedia summary: Leonotis nepetifolia,, is a species of plant in the genus Leonotis and the family Lamiaceae (mint), native to tropical Africa and the Indian Subcontinent. It can also be found growing abundantly in much of Latin America, Southeast Asia, the West Indies, and the Southeastern United States. It grows to a height of 3 metres and has whorls of striking lipped flowers, that are most commonly orange, but can vary to red, white, and purple. It has drooping dark green, very soft serrated leaves that can grow up to 10 centimetres (4 in) wide. Sunbirds and ants are attracted to the flowers. It has been found growing on roadsides, rubbish heaps or waste land.
Distribution: Floridablanca | Girón | Lebrija; Distrito Regional de Manejo Integrado (DRMI) Laguna de Sonso, municipio de Guadalajara de Buga, Valle del Cauca, Colombia; Tuluá; Subregiones: Cordillera occidental, Cordillera central, Norte, Zona central, Sur, Enclaves subxerofíticos; Antioquia, Bolívar, Boyacá, Cundinamarca, Huila, Santander, Tolima, Valle del Cauca; Bogotá (INTRODUCED); Africa (PRESENT); Caribbean (PRESENT); Middle America (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); South America (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Aldabra (INTRODUCED); Angola; Argentina Northeast (INTRODUCED); Assam (INTRODUCED); Bahamas (INTRODUCED); Bangladesh
