657,Acacia podalyriifolia A.Cunn. ex G.Don,Acacia podalyriifolia,Acacia,Fabaceae,podalyriifolia,A.Cunn. ex G.Don,,LC,2979014,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Acacia podalyriifolia,https://www.gbif.org/species/2979014,glaucous acacia; golden-ball wattle; Mount Morgan wattle; Mt. Morgan wattle; pearl acacia; Pearl Wattle; Queensland silver wattle; Queensland wattle,,,,North America (PRESENT); Assam (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED); Brazil Southeast (INTRODUCED); DR Congo (INTRODUCED); Eswatini (INTRODUCED); Ethiopia (INTRODUCED); India (INTRODUCED); Jawa (INTRODUCED); Kenya (INTRODUCED); KwaZulu-Natal (INTRODUCED); Malawi (INTRODUCED); Malaya (INTRODUCED); Mauritius (INTRODUCED); New Caledonia (INTRODUCED); New South Wales; Northern Provinces (INTRODUCED); Puerto Rico (INTRODUCED); Queensland; Rwanda (INTRODUCED),habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Acacia podalyriifolia,"Acacia podalyriifolia is a perennial tree which is fast-growing and widely cultivated. It is native to Australia but is also naturalised in Malaysia, Africa, India and South America. Its uses include environmental management and it is also used as an ornamental tree. It is very closely related to Acacia uncifera. It grows to about 5 m in height and about the same in total width. It blooms during winter.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acacia_podalyriifolia,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Acacia+podalyriifolia,"Acacia podalyriifolia is a perennial tree which is fast-growing and widely cultivated. It is native to Australia but is also naturalised in Malaysia, Africa, India and South America. Its uses include environmental management and it is also used as an ornamental tree. It is very closely related to Acacia uncifera. It grows to about 5 m in height and about the same in total width. It blooms during winter.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 657
Scientific name: Acacia podalyriifolia
Full species name: Acacia podalyriifolia A.Cunn. ex G.Don
Genus: Acacia
Family: Fabaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Acacia podalyriifolia
Common names: glaucous acacia; golden-ball wattle; Mount Morgan wattle; Mt. Morgan wattle; pearl acacia; Pearl Wattle; Queensland silver wattle; Queensland wattle
Wikipedia summary: Acacia podalyriifolia is a perennial tree which is fast-growing and widely cultivated. It is native to Australia but is also naturalised in Malaysia, Africa, India and South America. Its uses include environmental management and it is also used as an ornamental tree. It is very closely related to Acacia uncifera. It grows to about 5 m in height and about the same in total width. It blooms during winter.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Assam (INTRODUCED); Bolivia (INTRODUCED); Brazil Southeast (INTRODUCED); DR Congo (INTRODUCED); Eswatini (INTRODUCED); Ethiopia (INTRODUCED); India (INTRODUCED); Jawa (INTRODUCED); Kenya (INTRODUCED); KwaZulu-Natal (INTRODUCED); Malawi (INTRODUCED); Malaya (INTRODUCED); Mauritius (INTRODUCED); New Caledonia (INTRODUCED); New South Wales; Northern Provinces (INTRODUCED); Puerto Rico (INTRODUCED); Queensland; Rwanda (INTRODUCED)
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial
