683,Crotalaria brevidens Benth.,Crotalaria brevidens,Crotalaria,Fabaceae,brevidens,Benth.,,Not assessed,2942220,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Crotalaria brevidens,https://www.gbif.org/species/2942220,Ethiopian Rattlebox; Slenderleaf,Plantas vasculares,"Especies introducidas, exóticas, trasplantadas, invasoras y potencialmente invasoras obtenidas a partir de fuentes primarias y secundarias, incorporadas en el diagnóstico del Plan Nacional de Prevención, Control y Manejo",,Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Alabama (INTRODUCED); Burundi; Cameroon; Central African Republic; Chad; Colombia (INTRODUCED); Congo; DR Congo; Dominican Republic (INTRODUCED); Eswatini (INTRODUCED); Ethiopia; Gabon; Hawaii (INTRODUCED); Honduras (INTRODUCED); Kenya; Mozambique (INTRODUCED); Nigeria,habitat: terrestrial; lifeForm: Subarbusto; lifeForm: Subarbusto,Crotalaria,"Crotalaria is a genus of flowering plants in the family Fabaceae commonly known as rattlepods. The genus includes over 700 species of herbaceous plants and shrubs. Africa is the continent with the majority of Crotalaria species, which are mainly found in damp grassland, especially in floodplains, depressions and along edges of swamps and rivers, but also in deciduous bush land, roadsides and fields. Some species of Crotalaria are grown as ornamentals. The common name rattlepod or rattlebox is derived from the fact that the seeds become loose in the pod as they mature, and rattle when the pod is shaken. The name derives from the Ancient Greek κρόταλον, meaning ""castanet"", and is the same root as the name for the rattlesnakes (Crotalus).",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crotalaria,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Crotalaria+brevidens,Plantas vasculares,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 683
