688,Entada gigas (L.) Fawc. & Rendle,Entada gigas,Entada,Fabaceae,gigas,(L.) Fawc. & Rendle,,Not assessed,2976183,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Entada gigas,https://www.gbif.org/species/2976183,Cacoon; Mackay-bean; monkey-ladder; Nicker Bean; nicker-bean; sea bean; sea heart; sea-bean; sword-bean,"Description. Liana to 45 m long (Fig. 13 A). Leaves: rachis 5.9 - 7.5 cm long, terminating in a bifurcating tendril; pinnae (1 -) 2 pairs per leaf, with (3 -) 4 (- 5) pairs of leaflets; leaflets oblong to elliptic, often asymmetric, apex obtuse or rounded, emarginate, both surfaces of lamina essentially glabrous, except beneath near the base and the mid-rib puberulous above and sometimes below (Fig. 13 A, B). Inflorescence: a spiciform raceme, 8 - 25 cm long, solitary, supra-axillary (3 - 5 mm above the axil) with tufted glands between the axil and point of insertion of the rachis, + / - pubescent, peduncle 1.5 - 6 cm long (Fig. 13 C). Flowers: creamy white to greenish-yellow, pedicels 1 - 1.5 mm long; calyx 1 - 1.25 mm long, glabrous to pubescent; petals 2.5 - 3 mm long; stamen filaments 3.5 - 6 mm long (Fig. 13 E). Fruit: a gigantic craspedium, 40 - 120 x 7.5 - 12 cm, less woody than in the morphologically similar E. rheedei, twisted into a lax spiral, with transverse septa between seeds dividing the fruit into one-seeded segments which, upon ripening, fall from the persistent replum; epicarp falling away to expose an inflexible chartaceous endocarp; 10 - 12 - seeded (Figs 2 K, 13 E). Seeds: circular to slightly cordate, laterally compressed, 4 - 5.5 cm in diameter, hard; cotyledons separated by an intervening air space, enabling flotation (Fig. 2 O).","Re-circumscription of the mimosoid genus Entada including new combinations for all species of the phylogenetically nested Elephantorrhiza (Leguminosae, Caesalpinioideae, mimosoid clade)",eng,Puerto Wilches | Sabana de Torres | San Vicente de Chucurí; Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta | Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (NATIVE); Angola; Belize; Benin; Cameroon; Central African Republic; Central American Pacific Is.; Colombia; Congo; Costa Rica; Cuba; DR Congo; Dominican Republic; Ecuador; Equatorial Guinea; Gabon; Ghana; Gulf of Guinea Is.; Haiti,habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: Liana; habitat: Freshwater; Freshwater-terrestrial,Entada gigas,"Entada gigas, commonly known as the monkey-ladder, sea bean, cœur de la mer or sea heart, is a species of flowering liana in the pea family, Fabaceae, subfamily Mimosoideae. It is native to Central America, the Caribbean, northern South America, and Africa. It is notable for having the largest seedpods in the Fabaceae.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entada_gigas,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Entada+gigas,"Description. Liana to 45 m long (Fig. 13 A). Leaves: rachis 5.9 - 7.5 cm long, terminating in a bifurcating tendril; pinnae (1 -) 2 pairs per leaf, with (3 -) 4 (- 5) pairs of leaflets; leaflets oblong to elliptic, often asymmetric, apex obtuse or rounded, emarginate, both surfaces of lamina essentially glabrous, except beneath near the base and the mid-rib puberulous above and sometimes below (Fig. 13 A, B). Inflorescence: a spiciform raceme, 8 - 25 cm long, solitary, supra-axillary (3 - 5 mm above the axil) with tufted glands between the axil and point of insertion of the rachis, + / - pubescent, peduncle 1.5 - 6 cm long (Fig. 13 C). Flowers: creamy white to greenish-yellow, pedicels 1 - 1.5 mm long; calyx 1 - 1.25 mm long, glabrous to pubescent; petals 2.5 - 3 mm long; stamen filaments 3.5 - 6 mm long (Fig. 13 E). Fruit: a gigantic craspedium, 40 - 120 x 7.5 - 12 cm, less woody than in the morphologically similar E. rheedei, twisted into a lax spiral, with transverse septa between seeds dividing the fruit into one-seeded segments which, upon ripening, fall from the persistent replum; epicarp falling away to expose an inflexible chartaceous endocarp; 10 - 12 - seeded (Figs 2 K, 13 E). Seeds: circular to slightly cordate, laterally compressed, 4 - 5.5 cm in diameter, hard; cotyledons separated by an intervening air space, enabling flotation (Fig. 2 O).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 688
Scientific name: Entada gigas
Full species name: Entada gigas (L.) Fawc. & Rendle
Genus: Entada
Family: Fabaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Entada gigas
Common names: Cacoon; Mackay-bean; monkey-ladder; Nicker Bean; nicker-bean; sea bean; sea heart; sea-bean; sword-bean
GBIF description: Description. Liana to 45 m long (Fig. 13 A). Leaves: rachis 5.9 - 7.5 cm long, terminating in a bifurcating tendril; pinnae (1 -) 2 pairs per leaf, with (3 -) 4 (- 5) pairs of leaflets; leaflets oblong to elliptic, often asymmetric, apex obtuse or rounded, emarginate, both surfaces of lamina essentially glabrous, except beneath near the base and the mid-rib puberulous above and sometimes below (Fig. 13 A, B). Inflorescence: a spiciform raceme, 8 - 25 cm long, solitary, supra-axillary (3 - 5 mm above the axil) with tufted glands between the axil and point of insertion of the rachis, + / - pubescent, peduncle 1.5 - 6 cm long (Fig. 13 C). Flowers: creamy white to greenish-yellow, pedicels 1 - 1.5 mm long; calyx 1 - 1.25 mm long, glabrous to pubescent; petals 2.5 - 3 mm long; stamen filaments 3.5 - 6 mm long (Fig. 13 E). Fruit: a gigantic craspedium, 40 - 120 x 7.5 - 12 cm, less woody than in the morphologically similar E. rheedei, twisted into a lax spiral, with transverse septa between seeds dividing the fruit into one-seeded segments which, upon ripening, fall from the persistent replum; epicarp falling away to expose an inflexible chartaceous endocarp; 10 - 12 - seeded (Figs 2 K, 13 E). Seeds: circular to slightly cordate, laterally compressed, 4 - 5.5 cm in diameter, hard; cotyledons separated by an intervening air space, enabling flotation (Fig. 2 O).
Wikipedia summary: Entada gigas, commonly known as the monkey-ladder, sea bean, cœur de la mer or sea heart, is a species of flowering liana in the pea family, Fabaceae, subfamily Mimosoideae. It is native to Central America, the Caribbean, northern South America, and Africa. It is notable for having the largest seedpods in the Fabaceae.
Distribution: Puerto Wilches | Sabana de Torres | San Vicente de Chucurí; Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta | Parque Nacional Natural Los Katíos (NATIVE); Angola; Belize; Benin; Cameroon; Central African Republic; Central American Pacific Is.; Colombia; Congo; Costa Rica; Cuba; DR Congo; Dominican Republic; Ecuador; Equatorial Guinea; Gabon; Ghana; Gulf of Guinea Is.; Haiti
Profile: habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: Liana; habitat: Freshwater; Freshwater-terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2976183 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entada_gigas | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Entada+gigas",ok
