690,Illicium verum Hook.f.,Illicium verum,Illicium,Schisandraceae,verum,Hook.f.,,Not assessed,2889756,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Illicium verum,https://www.gbif.org/species/2889756,Chinese star-anise; Star Anise; star-anise; Staranise Tree,,,,Cambodia (INTRODUCED); China South-Central (INTRODUCED); China Southeast; Vietnam; China (Guangxi); Laos [c]; Cambodia [c]; Vietnam [c]; BR (MANAGED); TW (INTRODUCED),"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Árvore""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}",Illicium verum,"Illicium verum is a medium-sized evergreen tree native to South China and northeast Vietnam. Its star-shaped pericarp fruits harvested just before ripening are a spice that closely resembles anise in flavor. Its primary production country is China, followed by Vietnam and other Southeast Asian countries. Star anise oil is highly fragrant, used in cooking, perfumery, soaps, toothpastes, mouthwashes, and skin creams. Until 2012, when they switched to using genetically modified E. coli, Roche Pharmaceuticals used up to 90% of the world's annual star anise crop to produce oseltamivir (Tamiflu) via shikimic acid.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illicium_verum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Illicium+verum,"Illicium verum is a medium-sized evergreen tree native to South China and northeast Vietnam. Its star-shaped pericarp fruits harvested just before ripening are a spice that closely resembles anise in flavor. Its primary production country is China, followed by Vietnam and other Southeast Asian countries. Star anise oil is highly fragrant, used in cooking, perfumery, soaps, toothpastes, mouthwashes, and skin creams. Until 2012, when they switched to using genetically modified E. coli, Roche Pharmaceuticals used up to 90% of the world's annual star anise crop to produce oseltamivir (Tamiflu) via shikimic acid.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 690
Scientific name: Illicium verum
Full species name: Illicium verum Hook.f.
Genus: Illicium
Family: Schisandraceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Illicium verum
Common names: Chinese star-anise; Star Anise; star-anise; Staranise Tree
Wikipedia summary: Illicium verum is a medium-sized evergreen tree native to South China and northeast Vietnam. Its star-shaped pericarp fruits harvested just before ripening are a spice that closely resembles anise in flavor. Its primary production country is China, followed by Vietnam and other Southeast Asian countries. Star anise oil is highly fragrant, used in cooking, perfumery, soaps, toothpastes, mouthwashes, and skin creams. Until 2012, when they switched to using genetically modified E. coli, Roche Pharmaceuticals used up to 90% of the world's annual star anise crop to produce oseltamivir (Tamiflu) via shikimic acid.
Distribution: Cambodia (INTRODUCED); China South-Central (INTRODUCED); China Southeast; Vietnam; China (Guangxi); Laos [c]; Cambodia [c]; Vietnam [c]; BR (MANAGED); TW (INTRODUCED)
Profile: lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Árvore""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}
