698,Selenicereus anthonyanus (Alexander) D.R.Hunt,Selenicereus anthonyanus,Selenicereus,Cactaceae,anthonyanus,(Alexander) D.R.Hunt,,LC,3944930,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Selenicereus anthonyanus,https://www.gbif.org/species/3944930,Fishbone cactus; Rick Rack Cactus,,,,"Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Mexico Gulf; Mexico Southeast; Mexico Southwest; Global (PRESENT); Society Isl. [I] (Tahiti [I]); Tuamotu Arch. [I] (Makatea [I]); Mexico (Chiapas, Oaxaca, Tabasco, Veracruz); SE-Brazil [I]; BR (PRESENT); BR (MANAGED)","lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Arbusto"",""Suculenta""],""habitat"":[""Epífita""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Selenicereus anthonyanus,"Selenicereus anthonyanus is a cactus species native to southern Mexico. It is grown as an ornamental because of its nocturnal flowers and unusual, leaf-like stems. Common names include fishbone cactus, rickrack cactus, zig-zag cactus and St. Anthony's rickrack, and is sometimes referred to as an orchid cactus.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selenicereus_anthonyanus,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Selenicereus+anthonyanus,"Selenicereus anthonyanus is a cactus species native to southern Mexico. It is grown as an ornamental because of its nocturnal flowers and unusual, leaf-like stems. Common names include fishbone cactus, rickrack cactus, zig-zag cactus and St. Anthony's rickrack, and is sometimes referred to as an orchid cactus.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 698
