709,Dalea purpurea Vent.,Dalea purpurea,Dalea,Fabaceae,purpurea,Vent.,,Not assessed,5353342,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Dalea purpurea,https://www.gbif.org/species/5353342,purple prairie clover; purple prairie-clover; purple prairieclover; violet dalea; violet prairie clover; violet prairie-clover,"Notes. – In the Ventenat herbarium, two specimens have been found. One is clearly the one sent by Michaux from Illinois and the second is a sterile collection cultivated in Cels’s garden [G 00341561]. We choose to designate as the lectotype the Michaux s. n. collection as it is fertile and better represents the morphology of Dalea purpurea. Michaux collections determined as Petalostemon violaceus Michx. and kept in P and P-MICH are considered as isolectotypes as they do represent the same collection that Ventenat received from Illinois which would be described by him as Dalea purpurea. In P-MICH [P 00667210] only the collections on the far left and far right are type material.",Etienne-Pierre Ventenat (1757 - 1808) and the gardens of Cels and Empress Joséphine,eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Alberta; Arizona; Colorado; Georgia; Idaho; Illinois; Indiana; Kansas; Kentucky; Louisiana; Michigan; Minnesota; Montana; New Mexico; New York (INTRODUCED); North Dakota; Oklahoma; Saskatchewan,,Dalea purpurea,"Dalea purpurea is a species of flowering plant in the legume family known as purple prairie clover. Native to central North America, purple prairie clover is a relatively common member of the Great Plains and prairie ecosystems. It blooms in the summer with dense spikes of bright purple flowers that attract many species of insects.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalea_purpurea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Dalea+purpurea,"Notes. – In the Ventenat herbarium, two specimens have been found. One is clearly the one sent by Michaux from Illinois and the second is a sterile collection cultivated in Cels’s garden [G 00341561]. We choose to designate as the lectotype the Michaux s. n. collection as it is fertile and better represents the morphology of Dalea purpurea. Michaux collections determined as Petalostemon violaceus Michx. and kept in P and P-MICH are considered as isolectotypes as they do represent the same collection that Ventenat received from Illinois which would be described by him as Dalea purpurea. In P-MICH [P 00667210] only the collections on the far left and far right are type material.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 709
Scientific name: Dalea purpurea
Full species name: Dalea purpurea Vent.
Genus: Dalea
Family: Fabaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Dalea purpurea
Common names: purple prairie clover; purple prairie-clover; purple prairieclover; violet dalea; violet prairie clover; violet prairie-clover
GBIF description: Notes. – In the Ventenat herbarium, two specimens have been found. One is clearly the one sent by Michaux from Illinois and the second is a sterile collection cultivated in Cels’s garden [G 00341561]. We choose to designate as the lectotype the Michaux s. n. collection as it is fertile and better represents the morphology of Dalea purpurea. Michaux collections determined as Petalostemon violaceus Michx. and kept in P and P-MICH are considered as isolectotypes as they do represent the same collection that Ventenat received from Illinois which would be described by him as Dalea purpurea. In P-MICH [P 00667210] only the collections on the far left and far right are type material.
Wikipedia summary: Dalea purpurea is a species of flowering plant in the legume family known as purple prairie clover. Native to central North America, purple prairie clover is a relatively common member of the Great Plains and prairie ecosystems. It blooms in the summer with dense spikes of bright purple flowers that attract many species of insects.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Alberta; Arizona; Colorado; Georgia; Idaho; Illinois; Indiana; Kansas; Kentucky; Louisiana; Michigan; Minnesota; Montana; New Mexico; New York (INTRODUCED); North Dakota; Oklahoma; Saskatchewan
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/5353342 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalea_purpurea | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Dalea+purpurea",ok
710,Daucus pusillus Michx.,Daucus pusillus,Daucus,Apiaceae,pusillus,Michx.,,LC,3034741,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Daucus pusillus,https://www.gbif.org/species/3034741,american carrot; American wild carrot; Rattle-snake weed; Rattle-snake-weed; rattlesnake carrot; rattlesnake weed; rattlesnake-weed; Southwest wild carrot; southwestern wild carrot,herb,Database of Vascular Plants of Canada (VASCAN),,North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Alabama; Argentina Northeast; Argentina Northwest; Argentina South; Arizona; Arkansas; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; British Columbia; California; Chile Central; Chile South; Florida; Georgia; Germany (INTRODUCED); Hawaii (INTRODUCED); Idaho; Illinois,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica"",""Campo de Altitude"",""Campo Limpo"",""Vegetação Sobre Afloramentos Rochosos""]}; habitat: terrestrial",Daucus pusillus,"Daucus pusillus is a species of wild carrot known by the common names American wild carrot and rattle-snake-weed. Its Latin name means ""little carrot"", or ""tiny carrot"". It is similar in appearance to other species and subspecies of wild carrot, with umbels of white or pinkish flowers. The taproots are small, edible carrots. It should not be confused with Conium maculatum, which is highly poisonous.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daucus_pusillus,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Daucus+pusillus,herb,GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 710
Scientific name: Daucus pusillus
