751,Smilax herbacea L.,Smilax herbacea,Smilax,Smilacaceae,herbacea,L.,,Not assessed,5295311,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Smilax herbacea,https://www.gbif.org/species/5295311,Carrion-flower; carrionflower; herbaceous carrionflower; Herbaceous Greenbriar; Jacob's Lader; Jacob's-ladder; Smooth Carrionflower,"Lectotype (Pennell in Bull. Torrey Bot. Club 43: 413. 1916): Clayton 541, Herb. Linn. No. 1182.12 (LINN; iso- BM).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part S),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Georgia; Kentucky; Maine; Maryland; Massachusetts; New Brunswick; New Hampshire; New York; North Carolina; Ohio; Ontario; Pennsylvania; Québec; South Carolina; Tennessee; Vermont; Virginia; West Virginia,,Smilax herbacea,"Smilax herbacea is a perennial, herbaceous climbing vine in the family of Smilacaceae. It is native to eastern North America, including parts of eastern Canada and the eastern United States. It is commonly known by people as the smooth carrion flower, smooth herbaceous greenbrier, carrion vine, or as Jacob's-ladder. The species is known for being smooth in texture, and usually has thornless stems, it is a plant that can grow by climbing, and it has green colored flowers that have a foul, carrion-like odor which attracts flies and beetles for pollination. This plant grows in moist forests, savannas, meadows, and thickets, at moderate to high elevations. This allows it to serve as an understory vine. The plant blooms in May and June, and female individuals produce clusters of dark blue to nearly black berries later in the season. In addition to its ecological role, the species has a long history of use as both a food and medicinal plant.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smilax_herbacea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Smilax+herbacea,"Lectotype (Pennell in Bull. Torrey Bot. Club 43: 413. 1916): Clayton 541, Herb. Linn. No. 1182.12 (LINN; iso- BM).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 751
Scientific name: Smilax herbacea
Full species name: Smilax herbacea L.
Genus: Smilax
Family: Smilacaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Smilax herbacea
Common names: Carrion-flower; carrionflower; herbaceous carrionflower; Herbaceous Greenbriar; Jacob's Lader; Jacob's-ladder; Smooth Carrionflower
GBIF description: Lectotype (Pennell in Bull. Torrey Bot. Club 43: 413. 1916): Clayton 541, Herb. Linn. No. 1182.12 (LINN; iso- BM).
Wikipedia summary: Smilax herbacea is a perennial, herbaceous climbing vine in the family of Smilacaceae. It is native to eastern North America, including parts of eastern Canada and the eastern United States. It is commonly known by people as the smooth carrion flower, smooth herbaceous greenbrier, carrion vine, or as Jacob's-ladder. The species is known for being smooth in texture, and usually has thornless stems, it is a plant that can grow by climbing, and it has green colored flowers that have a foul, carrion-like odor which attracts flies and beetles for pollination. This plant grows in moist forests, savannas, meadows, and thickets, at moderate to high elevations. This allows it to serve as an understory vine. The plant blooms in May and June, and female individuals produce clusters of dark blue to nearly black berries later in the season. In addition to its ecological role, the species has a long history of use as both a food and medicinal plant.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Georgia; Kentucky; Maine; Maryland; Massachusetts; New Brunswick; New Hampshire; New York; North Carolina; Ohio; Ontario; Pennsylvania; Québec; South Carolina; Tennessee; Vermont; Virginia; West Virginia
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/5295311 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smilax_herbacea | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Smilax+herbacea",ok
752,Smilax tamnoides L.,Smilax tamnoides,Smilax,Smilacaceae,tamnoides,L.,,Not assessed,5295110,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Smilax tamnoides,https://www.gbif.org/species/5295110,bristly greenbriar; bristly greenbrier; Chinaroot; hellfetter; hogbrier,"Note: There has been much disagreement as to the identity of the type. Fernald identified it as S. tamnoides, but Clausen (in Rhodora 53: 109 - 111. 1951) concluded that it was a composite of several taxa, and that the name should therefore be discarded as ambiguous. Wilbur (in Sida 14: 38. 1990) supported this view, treating the woody species as S. hispida Muhl. ex. Torr. Subsequently, Wilbur (in Rhodora 105: 250 - 259. 2003) has provided an extensive review. He concludes that the bristly greenbriar is correctly known as S. hispida Raf. However, no formal proposal for the rejection of S. tamnoides seems to have been made.",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part S),eng,North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Arkansas; Connecticut; Delaware; District of Columbia; Florida; Georgia; Illinois; Indiana; Iowa; Kansas; Kentucky; Louisiana; Maryland; Massachusetts; Mexico Northeast; Michigan; Minnesota; Mississippi,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Liana/volúvel/trepadeira""],""habitat"":[""Desconhecido""]}",Smilax tamnoides,"Smilax tamnoides, common name bristly greenbrier, is a North American species of plants native to the United States and Canada. It is widespread from Ontario and New York State south to Texas and Florida.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smilax_tamnoides,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Smilax+tamnoides,"Note: There has been much disagreement as to the identity of the type. Fernald identified it as S. tamnoides, but Clausen (in Rhodora 53: 109 - 111. 1951) concluded that it was a composite of several taxa, and that the name should therefore be discarded as ambiguous. Wilbur (in Sida 14: 38. 1990) supported this view, treating the woody species as S. hispida Muhl. ex. Torr. Subsequently, Wilbur (in Rhodora 105: 250 - 259. 2003) has provided an extensive review. He concludes that the bristly greenbriar is correctly known as S. hispida Raf. However, no formal proposal for the rejection of S. tamnoides seems to have been made.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 752
Scientific name: Smilax tamnoides
Full species name: Smilax tamnoides L.
Genus: Smilax
Family: Smilacaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Smilax tamnoides
Common names: bristly greenbriar; bristly greenbrier; Chinaroot; hellfetter; hogbrier
GBIF description: Note: There has been much disagreement as to the identity of the type. Fernald identified it as S. tamnoides, but Clausen (in Rhodora 53: 109 - 111. 1951) concluded that it was a composite of several taxa, and that the name should therefore be discarded as ambiguous. Wilbur (in Sida 14: 38. 1990) supported this view, treating the woody species as S. hispida Muhl. ex. Torr. Subsequently, Wilbur (in Rhodora 105: 250 - 259. 2003) has provided an extensive review. He concludes that the bristly greenbriar is correctly known as S. hispida Raf. However, no formal proposal for the rejection of S. tamnoides seems to have been made.
Wikipedia summary: Smilax tamnoides, common name bristly greenbrier, is a North American species of plants native to the United States and Canada. It is widespread from Ontario and New York State south to Texas and Florida.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Arkansas; Connecticut; Delaware; District of Columbia; Florida; Georgia; Illinois; Indiana; Iowa; Kansas; Kentucky; Louisiana; Maryland; Massachusetts; Mexico Northeast; Michigan; Minnesota; Mississippi
