777,Lithops spp.,Lithops spp.,Lithops,Aizoaceae,,N.E.Br.,spp.,Not assessed,3231652,HIGHERRANK,96,ACCEPTED,Lithops,https://www.gbif.org/species/3231652,Living Stones; Stonefigs; Stoneplants,,,,Botswana; Cape Provinces; Free State; Namibia; Northern Provinces,,Leaf window,"A leaf window or epidermal window, also known as fenestration, is a specialized leaf structure consisting of a translucent area through which light can enter the interior surfaces of the leaf where photosynthesis can occur. The translucent structure may include epidermal tissue, and in some succulent plants it consists of several cell layers of parenchyma, which may also function as water-storage tissue. It can appear as a large continuous patch, a variegated or reticulated region, or as numerous small spots. It is found in some succulent plants native to arid climates, allowing much of the plant to remain beneath the soil surface where it is protected from desiccation by winds and heat while optimizing light absorption. Many species featuring leaf windows are native to Southern Africa.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaf_window,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lithops+spp.,"A leaf window or epidermal window, also known as fenestration, is a specialized leaf structure consisting of a translucent area through which light can enter the interior surfaces of the leaf where photosynthesis can occur. The translucent structure may include epidermal tissue, and in some succulent plants it consists of several cell layers of parenchyma, which may also function as water-storage tissue. It can appear as a large continuous patch, a variegated or reticulated region, or as numerous small spots. It is found in some succulent plants native to arid climates, allowing much of the plant to remain beneath the soil surface where it is protected from desiccation by winds and heat while optimizing light absorption. Many species featuring leaf windows are native to Southern Africa.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 777
Scientific name: Lithops spp.
Full species name: Lithops spp.
Genus: Lithops
Family: Aizoaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Lithops
Common names: Living Stones; Stonefigs; Stoneplants
Wikipedia summary: A leaf window or epidermal window, also known as fenestration, is a specialized leaf structure consisting of a translucent area through which light can enter the interior surfaces of the leaf where photosynthesis can occur. The translucent structure may include epidermal tissue, and in some succulent plants it consists of several cell layers of parenchyma, which may also function as water-storage tissue. It can appear as a large continuous patch, a variegated or reticulated region, or as numerous small spots. It is found in some succulent plants native to arid climates, allowing much of the plant to remain beneath the soil surface where it is protected from desiccation by winds and heat while optimizing light absorption. Many species featuring leaf windows are native to Southern Africa.
Distribution: Botswana; Cape Provinces; Free State; Namibia; Northern Provinces
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3231652 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaf_window | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lithops+spp.",ok
778,Cereus hildmannianus K.Schum.,Cereus hildmannianus,Cereus,Cactaceae,hildmannianus,K.Schum.,,LC,5384000,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Cereus hildmannianus,https://www.gbif.org/species/5384000,Andes organ pipe cactus; Hedge Cactus; queen-of-the-night,,,,Jardín Botánico de Bogotá; Caribbean (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast; Assam (INTRODUCED); Bolivia; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; Brazil West-Central; Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya (INTRODUCED); France (INTRODUCED); Hawaii (INTRODUCED); India (INTRODUCED); Italy (INTRODUCED); Nicobar Is. (INTRODUCED); Paraguay; Spain (INTRODUCED); Tunisia (INTRODUCED),"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Arbusto"",""Árvore"",""Suculenta""],""habitat"":[""Rupícola"",""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Floresta Estacional Decidual"",""Floresta Estacional Semidecidual"",""Vegetação Sobre Afloramentos Rochosos""]}; habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial",Cereus hildmannianus,"Cereus hildmannianus is a species of cactus from southern South America. Its distribution is uncertain but probably includes Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Argentina. This cactus thrives in diverse habitats such as forests, savannas, and grasslands, preferring well-draining soils and demonstrating adaptability to both drought and occasional flooding.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cereus_hildmannianus,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Cereus+hildmannianus,"Cereus hildmannianus is a species of cactus from southern South America. Its distribution is uncertain but probably includes Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Argentina. This cactus thrives in diverse habitats such as forests, savannas, and grasslands, preferring well-draining soils and demonstrating adaptability to both drought and occasional flooding.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 778
Scientific name: Cereus hildmannianus
Full species name: Cereus hildmannianus K.Schum.
Genus: Cereus
Family: Cactaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Cereus hildmannianus
Common names: Andes organ pipe cactus; Hedge Cactus; queen-of-the-night
Wikipedia summary: Cereus hildmannianus is a species of cactus from southern South America. Its distribution is uncertain but probably includes Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Argentina. This cactus thrives in diverse habitats such as forests, savannas, and grasslands, preferring well-draining soils and demonstrating adaptability to both drought and occasional flooding.
Distribution: Jardín Botánico de Bogotá; Caribbean (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Andaman Is. (INTRODUCED); Argentina Northeast; Assam (INTRODUCED); Bolivia; Brazil Southeast; Brazil South; Brazil West-Central; Canary Is. (INTRODUCED); East Himalaya (INTRODUCED); France (INTRODUCED); Hawaii (INTRODUCED); India (INTRODUCED); Italy (INTRODUCED); Nicobar Is. (INTRODUCED); Paraguay; Spain (INTRODUCED); Tunisia (INTRODUCED)
