806,Veronica × franciscana Eastw.,Veronica × franciscana,Veronica,Plantaginaceae,franciscana,Eastw.,,Not assessed,7445708,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Veronica franciscana,https://www.gbif.org/species/7445708,,,,,"England [I] (England [I], Wales [I], Isle of Man [I], Scotland [I], Outer Hebrides [I], Orkney Isl. [I], Shetland Isl. [I], Isles of Scilly [I]); Ireland [I] (Ireland [I], Northern Ireland [I]); Channel Isl. [I] (Alderney [I], Guernsey [I], Jersey [I], Sark [I]); New Zealand; USA [I] (California [I]); FK (PRESENT); IE (PRESENT)",habitat: terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial,Veronica sect. Hebe,"Veronica sect. Hebe is a group of plants within the genus Veronica, native to New Zealand, Rapa in French Polynesia, the Falkland Islands and South America. It was formerly treated as the separate genus Hebe. It includes about 90 species. Almost all species occur in New Zealand, apart from Veronica rapensis and Veronica salicifolia, found in South America. It is named after the Greek goddess of youth, Hebe. Informally, species in the section may be called shrubby veronicas or hebes.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronica_sect._Hebe,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Veronica+%C3%97+franciscana,"Veronica sect. Hebe is a group of plants within the genus Veronica, native to New Zealand, Rapa in French Polynesia, the Falkland Islands and South America. It was formerly treated as the separate genus Hebe. It includes about 90 species. Almost all species occur in New Zealand, apart from Veronica rapensis and Veronica salicifolia, found in South America. It is named after the Greek goddess of youth, Hebe. Informally, species in the section may be called shrubby veronicas or hebes.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 806
