817,Alocasia sanderiana W.Bull,Alocasia sanderiana,Alocasia,Araceae,sanderiana,W.Bull,,CR,5329946,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Alocasia sanderiana,https://www.gbif.org/species/5329946,Kris'-plant; Kris-plant; Sander's Alocasia,"Moderately robust herb to 60 cm tall; stem decumbent to creeping, ca. 15 cm long, ea. 2 cm thick; leaves solitary to few together, interspersed with cataphylls (precise arrangement unclear from herbarium material); cataphylls papery, narrowly lanceolate; petiole to 60 cm long, sheathing in lower fifth to quarter; blade sagittate, deep glossy green adaxially, purple abaxially (?always), peltate for 25-30% of the length of the posterior lobes, to ea. 40 cm long x 20 cm wide; margin deeply undulate to sub-pinnatifid; anterior lobe to 24 cm long; anterior costa with 3-4 often but not always opposite primary lateral veins on each side diverging at ca. 80-100°, these somewhat acropetally deflected towards the tip of each segment; primary veins and costae white to yellowish; secondary veins emerging from the primary at a wide angle, thence deflected marginally, not or hardly forming interprimary collective veins; inflorescence mostly paired; peduncle slender, ea. 14-18 cm long; spathe 6-10 cm long, lower part 1.5-2 cm long, ovoid; limb 4-8 cm long, more or less canoe-shaped; spadix somewhat shorter than to half the length of the spathe, stipitate for ea. 5 mm; female zone ea. 1 cm long; ovaries ea. 2 cm diam., subglobose; stigma sessile, rather sharply 3-4-lobed; sterile interstice corresponding to spathe constriction, ea. 5 mm long, tapering distally; male zone 1.2 cm long, ea. 4-5 mm thick (dry); synandria rhombo-hexagonal with the thecae ventrally but hardly laterally joined; synconnective centrally impressed, marginally slightly exceeding but not capping the thecae; appendix short, equalling the male zone, cylindric then abruptly tapering in distal 3-4 mm, slightly narrower than male zone (dry).",CATE Araceae,eng,Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Philippines; Tubuai Is. (INTRODUCED); Global (PRESENT); BR (MANAGED); TW (INTRODUCED),"habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}",Alocasia sanderiana,"Alocasia sanderiana, commonly known as the kris plant or Sander's alocasia, is a plant in the family Araceae. It is endemic to Northern Mindanao in the Philippines, but is commonly grown as an ornamental plant worldwide. It is classified as critically endangered in the wild by the International Union for Conservation of Nature.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alocasia_sanderiana,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Alocasia+sanderiana,"Moderately robust herb to 60 cm tall; stem decumbent to creeping, ca. 15 cm long, ea. 2 cm thick; leaves solitary to few together, interspersed with cataphylls (precise arrangement unclear from herbarium material); cataphylls papery, narrowly lanceolate; petiole to 60 cm long, sheathing in lower fifth to quarter; blade sagittate, deep glossy green adaxially, purple abaxially (?always), peltate for 25-30% of the length of the posterior lobes, to ea. 40 cm long x 20 cm wide; margin deeply undulate to sub-pinnatifid; anterior lobe to 24 cm long; anterior costa with 3-4 often but not always opposite primary lateral veins on each side diverging at ca. 80-100°, these somewhat acropetally deflected towards the tip of each segment; primary veins and costae white to yellowish; secondary veins emerging from the primary at a wide angle, thence deflected marginally, not or hardly forming interprimary collective veins; inflorescence mostly paired; peduncle slender, ea. 14-18 cm long; spathe 6-10 cm long, lower part 1.5-2 cm long, ovoid; limb 4-8 cm long, more or less canoe-shaped; spadix somewhat shorter than to half the length of the spathe, stipitate for ea. 5 mm; female zone ea. 1 cm long; ovaries ea. 2 cm diam., subglobose; stigma sessile, rather sharply 3-4-lobed; sterile interstice corresponding to spathe constriction, ea. 5 mm long, tapering distally; male zone 1.2 cm long, ea. 4-5 mm thick (dry); synandria rhombo-hexagonal with the thecae ventrally but hardly laterally joined; synconnective centrally impressed, marginally slightly exceeding but not capping the thecae; appendix short, equalling the male zone, cylindric then abruptly tapering in distal 3-4 mm, slightly narrower than male zone (dry).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 817
Scientific name: Alocasia sanderiana
Full species name: Alocasia sanderiana W.Bull
Genus: Alocasia
Family: Araceae
IUCN status: CR
Accepted scientific name: Alocasia sanderiana
Common names: Kris'-plant; Kris-plant; Sander's Alocasia
GBIF description: Moderately robust herb to 60 cm tall; stem decumbent to creeping, ca. 15 cm long, ea. 2 cm thick; leaves solitary to few together, interspersed with cataphylls (precise arrangement unclear from herbarium material); cataphylls papery, narrowly lanceolate; petiole to 60 cm long, sheathing in lower fifth to quarter; blade sagittate, deep glossy green adaxially, purple abaxially (?always), peltate for 25-30% of the length of the posterior lobes, to ea. 40 cm long x 20 cm wide; margin deeply undulate to sub-pinnatifid; anterior lobe to 24 cm long; anterior costa with 3-4 often but not always opposite primary lateral veins on each side diverging at ca. 80-100°, these somewhat acropetally deflected towards the tip of each segment; primary veins and costae white to yellowish; secondary veins emerging from the primary at a wide angle, thence deflected marginally, not or hardly forming interprimary collective veins; inflorescence mostly paired; peduncle slender, ea. 14-18 cm long; spathe 6-10 cm long, lower part 1.5-2 cm long, ovoid; limb 4-8 cm long, more or less canoe-shaped; spadix somewhat shorter than to half the length of the spathe, stipitate for ea. 5 mm; female zone ea. 1 cm long; ovaries ea. 2 cm diam., subglobose; stigma sessile, rather sharply 3-4-lobed; sterile interstice corresponding to spathe constriction, ea. 5 mm long, tapering distally; male zone 1.2 cm long, ea. 4-5 mm thick (dry); synandria rhombo-hexagonal with the thecae ventrally but hardly laterally joined; synconnective centrally impressed, marginally slightly exceeding but not capping the thecae; appendix short, equalling the male zone, cylindric then abruptly tapering in distal 3-4 mm, slightly narrower than male zone (dry).
Wikipedia summary: Alocasia sanderiana, commonly known as the kris plant or Sander's alocasia, is a plant in the family Araceae. It is endemic to Northern Mindanao in the Philippines, but is commonly grown as an ornamental plant worldwide. It is classified as critically endangered in the wild by the International Union for Conservation of Nature.
Distribution: Galápagos Islands (PRESENT); Southern Asia (PRESENT); Cook Is. (INTRODUCED); Philippines; Tubuai Is. (INTRODUCED); Global (PRESENT); BR (MANAGED); TW (INTRODUCED)
Profile: habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Terrícola""],""vegetationType"":[""Área Antrópica""]}
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/5329946 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alocasia_sanderiana | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Alocasia+sanderiana",ok
818,Daphne tangutica Maxim.,Daphne tangutica,Daphne,Thymelaeaceae,tangutica,Maxim.,,Not assessed,7311461,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Daphne tangutica,https://www.gbif.org/species/7311461,,,,,"China North-Central; China South-Central; Qinghai; Tibet; China (Shanxi, Shanxi, Gansu, Qinghai, Sichuan, Guizhou, Yunnan); Tibet; Nepal",,Daphne tangutica,"Daphne tangutica is a species of flowering plant in the family Thymelaeaceae, native to west and central China, including Tibet and Qinghai. It is an evergreen shrub growing to 1 m tall and wide, with leathery leaves and clusters of fragrant white and pink flowers in spring. The flowers are often followed by red berries. It grows in forests.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daphne_tangutica,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Daphne+tangutica,"Daphne tangutica is a species of flowering plant in the family Thymelaeaceae, native to west and central China, including Tibet and Qinghai. It is an evergreen shrub growing to 1 m tall and wide, with leathery leaves and clusters of fragrant white and pink flowers in spring. The flowers are often followed by red berries. It grows in forests.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 818
