Wikipedia summary: Daphne tangutica is a species of flowering plant in the family Thymelaeaceae, native to west and central China, including Tibet and Qinghai. It is an evergreen shrub growing to 1 m tall and wide, with leathery leaves and clusters of fragrant white and pink flowers in spring. The flowers are often followed by red berries. It grows in forests.
Distribution: China North-Central; China South-Central; Qinghai; Tibet; China (Shanxi, Shanxi, Gansu, Qinghai, Sichuan, Guizhou, Yunnan); Tibet; Nepal
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/7311461 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daphne_tangutica | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Daphne+tangutica",ok
819,Guaiacum sanctum L.,Guaiacum sanctum,Guaiacum,Zygophyllaceae,sanctum,L.,,NT,3189908,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Guaiacum sanctum,https://www.gbif.org/species/3189908,guaiacum; Holywood; Holywood Lignum Vitae; lignum-vitae; Roughbark Lignum-vitae; roughbark lignumvitae,"2. Guajacum foliolis multijugatis obtusis. Guajacum foliis pinnatis, foliolis obverse ovatis integerrimis. Roy. lugdb. 208. Guajacum flore caeruleo fimbriato, fructu tetragono. Plum. gen. 39. Guajacum propemodum sine matrice. Bauh. pin. 448. Jasminum vulgo americanum s. Euonymo affinis occidentalis, alatis rusci foliis, nucifera, cortice ad genicula fungoso. Pluk. alm. 139. t. 94. f. 4.","Species plantarum: exhibentes plantas rite cognitas, ad genera relatas, cum differentiis specificis, nominibus trivialibus, synonymis selectis, locis natalibus, secundum systema sexuale digestas",eng,Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Aruba; Bahamas; Belize; Costa Rica; Cuba; Dominican Republic; El Salvador; Florida; Guatemala; Haiti; Honduras; Mexico Gulf; Mexico Southeast; Mexico Southwest; Netherlands Antilles; Nicaragua; Panamá; Puerto Rico,habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; habitat: Terrestrial; lifeForm: Árbol,Guaiacum sanctum,"Guaiacum sanctum, commonly known as holywood, lignum vitae or holywood lignum-vitae, is a species of flowering plant in the creosote bush family, Zygophyllaceae. It is native to the Neotropical realm, from Mexico through Central America, Florida in the United States, the Caribbean, and northern South America. It has been introduced to other tropical areas of the world. It is currently threatened by habitat loss in its native region, and as such, is currently rated near threatened on the IUCN Red List. Guaiacum sanctum is the national tree of the Bahamas.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guaiacum_sanctum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Guaiacum+sanctum,"2. Guajacum foliolis multijugatis obtusis. Guajacum foliis pinnatis, foliolis obverse ovatis integerrimis. Roy. lugdb. 208. Guajacum flore caeruleo fimbriato, fructu tetragono. Plum. gen. 39. Guajacum propemodum sine matrice. Bauh. pin. 448. Jasminum vulgo americanum s. Euonymo affinis occidentalis, alatis rusci foliis, nucifera, cortice ad genicula fungoso. Pluk. alm. 139. t. 94. f. 4.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 819
