825,Nephrolepis falcata (Cav.) C.Chr.,Nephrolepis falcata,Nephrolepis,Nephrolepidaceae,falcata,(Cav.) C.Chr.,,Not assessed,2650928,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Nephrolepis falcata,https://www.gbif.org/species/2650928,Fishtail Swordfern,"Habit, rhizome morphology. Runners 1 - 1.5 mm thick, branching angle narrow. Scales on runners very sparse or sparse, appressed. Tubers absent. Fronds 65 - 200 cm long (or more), 7 - 10 cm wide, stipe 10 - 34 cm long. Lamina base strongly reduced, tapering over 20 - 35 cm, basal pinnae 0.7 - 1 cm long, 1.5 - 3.5 cm distant, middle pinnae distinctly to strongly falcate. Sterile pinnae 4 - 8 by 1 - 1.4 cm, herbaceous, thick, base strongly unequal, basiscopic base rounded, acroscopic base truncate, slightly to distinctly auricled, margin in basal part crenate, dentate or serrate, apex acute to (indistinctly) 1 cm caudate. Fertile pinnae 4.8 - 8 by 0.7 - 1.2 cm, otherwise similar to sterile ones. Indument. Basal scales peltate, appressed, 2 by 0.5 - 1 mm, central part blackish, shining, hyaline margin narrow, marginal glands absent, margin in basal part irregularly lacerate or ciliate, acumen ciliate. Rachis scales dense, with a well-developed protracted acumen, squarrose to recurved, dark, with entire acumen. Scales on lamina usually persistent, with a long, narrow, entire, acicular acumen. Hairs on lamina and costa absent. Sori submarginal, 19 - 29 pairs on fully fertile pinnae, round, not impressed. Indusium reniform, with narrow sinus, attached at sinus.",A conspectus of the native and naturalized species of Nephrolepis (Nephrolepidaceae) in the world,eng,"North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Philippines; Sri Lanka; Myanmar; Vietnam; Sumatra; Borneo (Sabah, Sarawak); Philippines; Hawaii [I] (Kauai [I], Oahu [I], Molokai [I], Lanai [I], Maui [I], Hawaii Isl. [I]); USA [I] (Florida [I]); Honduras [I]; Virgin Isl. [I] (Tortola [I]); SC (PRESENT); Hawaii (PRESENT); conterminous 48 United States (PRESENT)",habitat: terrestrial,List of pteridophytes of Sri Lanka,"Sri Lanka is a tropical island situated close to the southern tip of India. The invertebrate fauna is as large as it is common to other regions of the world. There are about 2 million species of arthropods found in the world, and more are still being discovered to this day. This makes it very complicated and difficult to summarize the exact number of species found within a certain region.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_pteridophytes_of_Sri_Lanka,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nephrolepis+falcata,"Habit, rhizome morphology. Runners 1 - 1.5 mm thick, branching angle narrow. Scales on runners very sparse or sparse, appressed. Tubers absent. Fronds 65 - 200 cm long (or more), 7 - 10 cm wide, stipe 10 - 34 cm long. Lamina base strongly reduced, tapering over 20 - 35 cm, basal pinnae 0.7 - 1 cm long, 1.5 - 3.5 cm distant, middle pinnae distinctly to strongly falcate. Sterile pinnae 4 - 8 by 1 - 1.4 cm, herbaceous, thick, base strongly unequal, basiscopic base rounded, acroscopic base truncate, slightly to distinctly auricled, margin in basal part crenate, dentate or serrate, apex acute to (indistinctly) 1 cm caudate. Fertile pinnae 4.8 - 8 by 0.7 - 1.2 cm, otherwise similar to sterile ones. Indument. Basal scales peltate, appressed, 2 by 0.5 - 1 mm, central part blackish, shining, hyaline margin narrow, marginal glands absent, margin in basal part irregularly lacerate or ciliate, acumen ciliate. Rachis scales dense, with a well-developed protracted acumen, squarrose to recurved, dark, with entire acumen. Scales on lamina usually persistent, with a long, narrow, entire, acicular acumen. Hairs on lamina and costa absent. Sori submarginal, 19 - 29 pairs on fully fertile pinnae, round, not impressed. Indusium reniform, with narrow sinus, attached at sinus.",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 825
Scientific name: Nephrolepis falcata
Full species name: Nephrolepis falcata (Cav.) C.Chr.
Genus: Nephrolepis
Family: Nephrolepidaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Nephrolepis falcata
Common names: Fishtail Swordfern
GBIF description: Habit, rhizome morphology. Runners 1 - 1.5 mm thick, branching angle narrow. Scales on runners very sparse or sparse, appressed. Tubers absent. Fronds 65 - 200 cm long (or more), 7 - 10 cm wide, stipe 10 - 34 cm long. Lamina base strongly reduced, tapering over 20 - 35 cm, basal pinnae 0.7 - 1 cm long, 1.5 - 3.5 cm distant, middle pinnae distinctly to strongly falcate. Sterile pinnae 4 - 8 by 1 - 1.4 cm, herbaceous, thick, base strongly unequal, basiscopic base rounded, acroscopic base truncate, slightly to distinctly auricled, margin in basal part crenate, dentate or serrate, apex acute to (indistinctly) 1 cm caudate. Fertile pinnae 4.8 - 8 by 0.7 - 1.2 cm, otherwise similar to sterile ones. Indument. Basal scales peltate, appressed, 2 by 0.5 - 1 mm, central part blackish, shining, hyaline margin narrow, marginal glands absent, margin in basal part irregularly lacerate or ciliate, acumen ciliate. Rachis scales dense, with a well-developed protracted acumen, squarrose to recurved, dark, with entire acumen. Scales on lamina usually persistent, with a long, narrow, entire, acicular acumen. Hairs on lamina and costa absent. Sori submarginal, 19 - 29 pairs on fully fertile pinnae, round, not impressed. Indusium reniform, with narrow sinus, attached at sinus.
Wikipedia summary: Sri Lanka is a tropical island situated close to the southern tip of India. The invertebrate fauna is as large as it is common to other regions of the world. There are about 2 million species of arthropods found in the world, and more are still being discovered to this day. This makes it very complicated and difficult to summarize the exact number of species found within a certain region.
Distribution: North America (PRESENT); Oceania (PRESENT); Philippines; Sri Lanka; Myanmar; Vietnam; Sumatra; Borneo (Sabah, Sarawak); Philippines; Hawaii [I] (Kauai [I], Oahu [I], Molokai [I], Lanai [I], Maui [I], Hawaii Isl. [I]); USA [I] (Florida [I]); Honduras [I]; Virgin Isl. [I] (Tortola [I]); SC (PRESENT); Hawaii (PRESENT); conterminous 48 United States (PRESENT)
Profile: habitat: terrestrial
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2650928 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_pteridophytes_of_Sri_Lanka | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nephrolepis+falcata",ok
