GBIF description: Distribution: Pakistan, Nepal, India, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, China, Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Malaysia, Philippines, Indonesia (Bingtao & Esser 2008). Specimens examined: Indonesia (Timor Barat): South Central Timor, [Supul, 9 ° 50 ’ 40 ” S, 124 ° 26 ’ 49 ” E], 20 February 1969, Kooy, C. W. 579 (L [L. 2193341]). Red List Assessment: Least Concern.
Wikipedia summary: Breynia vitis-idaea, the officinal breynia, is a perennial tree-like species of Phyllanthaceae, found from India east to Taiwan and Okinawa and south to Indonesia. It is a shrub or treelet with egg-shaped leaves that can reach up to 3 m tall. It has staminate flowers and spherical, red fruit.
Distribution: Global (PRESENT); China (Fujian, Guangdong, Guizhou, Yunnan); Ogasawara Isl. [I] (Chichijima [I]); Taiwan; Pakistan [I] (Sind [I], Lahore [I]); Nepal; India (throughout); Bangladesh; Andaman Isl. (North Andaman Isl., Middle Andaman Isl., South Andaman Isl., Little Andaman Isl.); Nicobar Isl. (Car Nicobar Isl., North Nicobar Isl., Central Nicobar Isl., Great Nicobar Isl., Little Nicobar Isl.); Myanmar; Thailand (widespread); Laos; Cambodia; Vietnam; peninsular Malaysia (north of Malaya); Singapore; Sumatra; Borneo; Palawan; Philippines (Batan, Luzon, Mindanao); Java; Lesser Sunda Isl. (Timor)
