844,Barringtonia acutangula (L.) Gaertn.,Barringtonia acutangula,Barringtonia,Lecythidaceae,acutangula,(L.) Gaertn.,,LC,3082835,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Barringtonia acutangula,https://www.gbif.org/species/3082835,freshwater mangrove; Hijal; itchytree; mango-pine,"Barringtonia acutangula (L.) Gaertn. Names. Myanmar: kyi, kyi-ni, ye-kyi. English: Indian oak. Range. India to northern Australia. Widely distributed in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used to treat dysentery and diarrhea. Fruit: Used for blood diseases. Seed: Used to treat opthalmia. Root: An aperient. Notes. In India a decoction of the bark is used as a mouthwash for toothache and gum pain; the stem is used for toothache; leaf juice is used for diarrhea; the fruit is used for nasal catarrh; the seed for liver problems; and an unspecified part, in a mixture with herbs, is used to treat cholera (Jain and DeFilipps 1991). Medicinal uses of the species in Indo-China and the Philippines are discussed in Perry (1980). References. Nordal (1963), Perry (1980).",The medicinal plants of Myanmar,eng,Afghanistan; Assam; Bangladesh; Borneo; Cambodia; India; Jawa; Laos; Lesser Sunda Is.; Malaya; Myanmar; New Guinea; Pakistan; Philippines; Queensland; Sri Lanka; Sulawesi; Sumatera; Thailand; Vietnam,,Barringtonia acutangula,"Barringtonia acutangula is a species of Barringtonia native to coastal wetlands in southern Asia and northern Australasia, from Afghanistan east to the Philippines, Queensland and the Northern Territory. Common names include freshwater mangrove, itchytree and mango-pine.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barringtonia_acutangula,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Barringtonia+acutangula,"Barringtonia acutangula (L.) Gaertn. Names. Myanmar: kyi, kyi-ni, ye-kyi. English: Indian oak. Range. India to northern Australia. Widely distributed in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used to treat dysentery and diarrhea. Fruit: Used for blood diseases. Seed: Used to treat opthalmia. Root: An aperient. Notes. In India a decoction of the bark is used as a mouthwash for toothache and gum pain; the stem is used for toothache; leaf juice is used for diarrhea; the fruit is used for nasal catarrh; the seed for liver problems; and an unspecified part, in a mixture with herbs, is used to treat cholera (Jain and DeFilipps 1991). Medicinal uses of the species in Indo-China and the Philippines are discussed in Perry (1980). References. Nordal (1963), Perry (1980).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 844
Scientific name: Barringtonia acutangula
Full species name: Barringtonia acutangula (L.) Gaertn.
Genus: Barringtonia
Family: Lecythidaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Barringtonia acutangula
Common names: freshwater mangrove; Hijal; itchytree; mango-pine
GBIF description: Barringtonia acutangula (L.) Gaertn. Names. Myanmar: kyi, kyi-ni, ye-kyi. English: Indian oak. Range. India to northern Australia. Widely distributed in Myanmar. Uses. Leaf: Used to treat dysentery and diarrhea. Fruit: Used for blood diseases. Seed: Used to treat opthalmia. Root: An aperient. Notes. In India a decoction of the bark is used as a mouthwash for toothache and gum pain; the stem is used for toothache; leaf juice is used for diarrhea; the fruit is used for nasal catarrh; the seed for liver problems; and an unspecified part, in a mixture with herbs, is used to treat cholera (Jain and DeFilipps 1991). Medicinal uses of the species in Indo-China and the Philippines are discussed in Perry (1980). References. Nordal (1963), Perry (1980).
Wikipedia summary: Barringtonia acutangula is a species of Barringtonia native to coastal wetlands in southern Asia and northern Australasia, from Afghanistan east to the Philippines, Queensland and the Northern Territory. Common names include freshwater mangrove, itchytree and mango-pine.
Distribution: Afghanistan; Assam; Bangladesh; Borneo; Cambodia; India; Jawa; Laos; Lesser Sunda Is.; Malaya; Myanmar; New Guinea; Pakistan; Philippines; Queensland; Sri Lanka; Sulawesi; Sumatera; Thailand; Vietnam
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3082835 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barringtonia_acutangula | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Barringtonia+acutangula",ok
