848,Hypericum hypericoides (L.) Crantz,Hypericum hypericoides,Hypericum,Hypericaceae,hypericoides,(L.) Crantz,,LC,3189520,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Hypericum hypericoides,https://www.gbif.org/species/3189520,St. Andrew's Cross; St. Andrew's-cross,"Note: Fernald (in Rhodora 38: 432. 1936) discussed various of the original elements, interpreting the name "" as to Plumiers plant "" but this falls short of formal typification. Adams (in Rhodora 59: 81. 1957) adopted a similar line but also designated Browne's specimen (944.4 LINN) as a neotype (unacceptable in the presence of original material). Robson's choice is followed here. See further comments by Reveal & al. (in Huntia 7: 226. 1987) and Robson (in Bull. Nat. Hist. Mus. London, Bot. 26: 129 - 130. 1996).",Chapter 7: Linnaean Plant Names and their Types (part A),eng,Caribbean (PRESENT); North America (PRESENT); Alabama; Arkansas; Azores (INTRODUCED); Bahamas; Bermuda; Cuba; Delaware; District of Columbia; Dominican Republic; Florida; Georgia; Guatemala; Haiti; Honduras; Illinois; Indiana; Kansas; Kentucky,habitat: Terrestrial,Hypericum hypericoides,"Hypericum hypericoides, commonly called St. Andrew's cross, is a species of flowering plant in the St. John's wort family, Hypericaceae. It is native to the Southeastern United States, Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean. Its preferred habitat is dry woods on acidic soil.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypericum_hypericoides,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Hypericum+hypericoides,"Note: Fernald (in Rhodora 38: 432. 1936) discussed various of the original elements, interpreting the name "" as to Plumiers plant "" but this falls short of formal typification. Adams (in Rhodora 59: 81. 1957) adopted a similar line but also designated Browne's specimen (944.4 LINN) as a neotype (unacceptable in the presence of original material). Robson's choice is followed here. See further comments by Reveal & al. (in Huntia 7: 226. 1987) and Robson (in Bull. Nat. Hist. Mus. London, 