870,Sedum niveum Davidson,Sedum niveum,Sedum,Crassulaceae,niveum,Davidson,,Not assessed,5362002,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Sedum niveum,https://www.gbif.org/species/5362002,Davidson's stonecrop; Pine City Sedum; snowy stonecrop,,,,North America (PRESENT); California; Mexico Northwest; USA (California); Mexico (Baja California Norte),,Sedum niveum,"Sedum niveum is a species of flowering plant in the family Crassulaceae known by the common name Davidson's stonecrop. It is native to southern California and northern Baja California, where it is known from several local mountain ranges. It grows in rocky, forested habitat. It is a succulent plant forming basal mats of spoon-shaped or oval leaves no more than a centimeter long. The small inflorescence grows up to 9 centimeters tall and bears several flowers with white petals tinged or veined with pink. The stamens have red or black anthers.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sedum_niveum,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Sedum+niveum,"Sedum niveum is a species of flowering plant in the family Crassulaceae known by the common name Davidson's stonecrop. It is native to southern California and northern Baja California, where it is known from several local mountain ranges. It grows in rocky, forested habitat. It is a succulent plant forming basal mats of spoon-shaped or oval leaves no more than a centimeter long. The small inflorescence grows up to 9 centimeters tall and bears several flowers with white petals tinged or veined with pink. The stamens have red or black anthers.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 870
