879,Xylococcus bicolor Nutt.,Xylococcus bicolor,Xylococcus,Ericaceae,bicolor,Nutt.,,Not assessed,2882684,EXACT,100,SYNONYM,Arctostaphylos bicolor,https://www.gbif.org/species/2882684,Mission manzanita,,,,"USA (California); Mexico (Baja California Norte, Baja California Sur)",,Xylococcus bicolor,"Xylococcus is a monotypic genus of flowering plants in the heather family which contains the single species Xylococcus bicolor, commonly known as the mission manzanita. It is a burl-forming, evergreen shrub with leathery leaves and smooth dark reddish bark. From December to February, white to pink urn-shaped flowers adorn the foliage, often attracting hummingbird pollinators. It is native to southern California and the Baja California Peninsula, south to the Sierra de la Giganta. There is growing concern over the future of this plant, referred to as the ""queen of the elfin forest"", as it may possibly lose up to 88% of its habitat and its wild seedlings are failing to survive more than a full year.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xylococcus_bicolor,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Xylococcus+bicolor,"Xylococcus is a monotypic genus of flowering plants in the heather family which contains the single species Xylococcus bicolor, commonly known as the mission manzanita. It is a burl-forming, evergreen shrub with leathery leaves and smooth dark reddish bark. From December to February, white to pink urn-shaped flowers adorn the foliage, often attracting hummingbird pollinators. It is native to southern California and the Baja California Peninsula, south to the Sierra de la Giganta. There is growing concern over the future of this plant, referred to as the ""queen of the elfin forest"", as it may possibly lose up to 88% of its habitat and its wild seedlings are failing to survive more than a full year.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 879
Scientific name: Xylococcus bicolor
Full species name: Xylococcus bicolor Nutt.
Genus: Xylococcus
Family: Ericaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Arctostaphylos bicolor
Common names: Mission manzanita
Wikipedia summary: Xylococcus is a monotypic genus of flowering plants in the heather family which contains the single species Xylococcus bicolor, commonly known as the mission manzanita. It is a burl-forming, evergreen shrub with leathery leaves and smooth dark reddish bark. From December to February, white to pink urn-shaped flowers adorn the foliage, often attracting hummingbird pollinators. It is native to southern California and the Baja California Peninsula, south to the Sierra de la Giganta. There is growing concern over the future of this plant, referred to as the ""queen of the elfin forest"", as it may possibly lose up to 88% of its habitat and its wild seedlings are failing to survive more than a full year.
Distribution: USA (California); Mexico (Baja California Norte, Baja California Sur)
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/2882684 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xylococcus_bicolor | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Xylococcus+bicolor",ok
