901,Lithops olivacea L.Bolus,Lithops olivacea,Lithops,Aizoaceae,olivacea,L.Bolus,,Not assessed,7329191,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Lithops olivacea,https://www.gbif.org/species/7329191,,,,,Cape Provinces; South Africa (N-Cape Prov.); ZA; NorthernCape; SouthAfrica; SouthernAfrica_FSA,,Lithops olivacea,"Lithops olivacea is a species of the genus Lithops under the family Aizoaceae. The name olivacea refers to the Latin word for olive (oliva) combined with the suffix -cea, meaning ""of the likeness"", producing the idea of ""olive likeness"". Lithops olivacea grow primarily in the Bushmanland of South Africa. They grow most abundantly in the regions of Aggeneys, Pofadder, and Namies. L. olivacea also received the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit for being ""excellent for ordinary use in appropriate conditions, available to buy, of good constitution, essentially stable in form & colour, [and] reasonably resistant to pests & diseases.""",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithops_olivacea,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Lithops+olivacea,"Lithops olivacea is a species of the genus Lithops under the family Aizoaceae. The name olivacea refers to the Latin word for olive (oliva) combined with the suffix -cea, meaning ""of the likeness"", producing the idea of ""olive likeness"". Lithops olivacea grow primarily in the Bushmanland of South Africa. They grow most abundantly in the regions of Aggeneys, Pofadder, and Namies. L. olivacea also received the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit for being ""excellent for ordinary use in appropriate conditions, available to buy, of good constitution, essentially stable in form & colour, [and] reasonably resistant to pests & diseases.""",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 901
Scientific name: Lithops olivacea
Full species name: Lithops olivacea L.Bolus
Genus: Lithops
Family: Aizoaceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Lithops olivacea
Wikipedia summary: Lithops olivacea is a species of the genus Lithops under the family Aizoaceae. The name olivacea refers to the Latin word for olive (oliva) combined with the suffix -cea, meaning ""of the likeness"", producing the idea of ""olive likeness"". Lithops olivacea grow primarily in the Bushmanland of South Africa. They grow most abundantly in the regions of Aggeneys, Pofadder, and Namies. L. olivacea also received the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit for being ""excellent for ordinary use in appropriate conditions, available to buy, of good constitution, essentially stable in form & colour, [and] reasonably resistant to pests & diseases.""
Distribution: Cape Provinces; South Africa (N-Cape Prov.); ZA; NorthernCape; SouthAfrica; SouthernAfrica_FSA
