934,Tagetes lunulata Ortega,Tagetes lunulata,Tagetes,Asteraceae,lunulata,Ortega,,Not assessed,3088477,EXACT,100,ACCEPTED,Tagetes lunulata,https://www.gbif.org/species/3088477,Himalayan marigold; Red-crescent marigold,,,,"India (INTRODUCED); Mexico Central; Mexico Gulf; Mexico Northeast; Mexico Northwest; Mexico Southwest; Mexico (PRESENT); India [c]; Mexico (Aguascalientes, Colima, Ciudad de Mexico, Durango, Guanajuato, Guerrero, Hidalgo, Jalisco, México State, Michoacán, Morelos, Nayarit, Oaxaca, Puebla, Queretaro, San Luis Potosi, Sinaloa, Tlaxcala, Veracruz, Zacatecas)",,Tagetes,"Tagetes is a genus of 50 species of annual or perennial, mostly herbaceous plants in the family Asteraceae. They are among several groups of plants known in English as marigolds. The genus Tagetes was formally named by Carl Linnaeus in 1753. Linnaeus cited Joseph Pitton de Tournefort (1700), Johann Jacob Dillenius (1732), Gaspard Bauhin (1623) and Fabio Colonna (1606) as authors who used the name 'Tagetes' before. In 1754 he published the formal description in his Genera Plantarum, referring to Tournefort, Sébastien Vaillant (1720) and Dillenius for the name 'Tagetes'.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tagetes,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Tagetes+lunulata,"Tagetes is a genus of 50 species of annual or perennial, mostly herbaceous plants in the family Asteraceae. They are among several groups of plants known in English as marigolds. The genus Tagetes was formally named by Carl Linnaeus in 1753. Linnaeus cited Joseph Pitton de Tournefort (1700), Johann Jacob Dillenius (1732), Gaspard Bauhin (1623) and Fabio Colonna (1606) as authors who used the name 'Tagetes' before. In 1754 he published the formal description in his Genera Plantarum, referring to Tournefort, Sébastien Vaillant (1720) and Dillenius for the name 'Tagetes'.",Wikipedia-en,"PlantNet species_id: 934
Scientific name: Tagetes lunulata
Full species name: Tagetes lunulata Ortega
Genus: Tagetes
Family: Asteraceae
IUCN status: Not assessed
Accepted scientific name: Tagetes lunulata
Common names: Himalayan marigold; Red-crescent marigold
Wikipedia summary: Tagetes is a genus of 50 species of annual or perennial, mostly herbaceous plants in the family Asteraceae. They are among several groups of plants known in English as marigolds. The genus Tagetes was formally named by Carl Linnaeus in 1753. Linnaeus cited Joseph Pitton de Tournefort (1700), Johann Jacob Dillenius (1732), Gaspard Bauhin (1623) and Fabio Colonna (1606) as authors who used the name 'Tagetes' before. In 1754 he published the formal description in his Genera Plantarum, referring to Tournefort, Sébastien Vaillant (1720) and Dillenius for the name 'Tagetes'.
Distribution: India (INTRODUCED); Mexico Central; Mexico Gulf; Mexico Northeast; Mexico Northwest; Mexico Southwest; Mexico (PRESENT); India [c]; Mexico (Aguascalientes, Colima, Ciudad de Mexico, Durango, Guanajuato, Guerrero, Hidalgo, Jalisco, México State, Michoacán, Morelos, Nayarit, Oaxaca, Puebla, Queretaro, San Luis Potosi, Sinaloa, Tlaxcala, Veracruz, Zacatecas)
Sources: https://www.gbif.org/species/3088477 | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tagetes | https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Tagetes+lunulata",ok
