965,Nymphaea rubra Roxb. ex Andrews,Nymphaea rubra,Nymphaea,Nymphaeaceae,rubra,Roxb. ex Andrews,,LC,7365664,EXACT,99,ACCEPTED,Nymphaea rubra,https://www.gbif.org/species/7365664,,"Nymphaea rubra Roxb. ex Andrews Names. Myanmar: kya-ni. English: Indian red water-lily. Range. Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Vietnam. Common in warmer parts of Myanmar. Conservation status. Least Concern [LC] (IUCN 2017). Uses. Flower: Used as a blood purifier and febrifuge. Notes. The medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The flower is decocted and used for heart palpitations; the rootstock is powdered and used for piles, diarrhea, and dyspepsia. Perry (1980) discusses the uses of Nymphaea species in Indo-China and the Philippines. Reference. Nordal (1963).",The medicinal plants of Myanmar,eng,Assam; Bangladesh; Cambodia; China Southeast (INTRODUCED); Cuba (INTRODUCED); Guyana (INTRODUCED); Hungary (INTRODUCED); India; Jawa; Laos; Malaya; Mexico Southeast (INTRODUCED); Myanmar; Philippines; Sri Lanka; Suriname (INTRODUCED); Thailand; Vietnam; Global (PRESENT); Hungary [I]; China (Yunnan); Pakistan (Sind); India (almost throughout India); Sri Lanka; Bangladesh; Myanmar; Thailand; Laos; Cambodia; Vietnam; peninsular Malaysia; Java,"lifeForm: {""lifeForm"":[""Erva""],""habitat"":[""Aquática""],""vegetationType"":[""Vegetação Aquática""]}; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater; habitat: Freshwater",Nymphaea rubra,"Nymphaea rubra is a species of waterlily native to the region spanning from Sri Lanka and northeastern India to western and central Malesia. Additionally, it has been introduced to regions such as Southeast China, Cuba, Guyana, Hungary, and Suriname.",https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nymphaea_rubra,https://powo.science.kew.org/results?q=Nymphaea+rubra,"Nymphaea rubra Roxb. ex Andrews Names. Myanmar: kya-ni. English: Indian red water-lily. Range. Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Vietnam. Common in warmer parts of Myanmar. Conservation status. Least Concern [LC] (IUCN 2017). Uses. Flower: Used as a blood purifier and febrifuge. Notes. The medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The flower is decocted and used for heart palpitations; the rootstock is powdered and used for piles, diarrhea, and dyspepsia. Perry (1980) discusses the uses of Nymphaea species in Indo-China and the Philippines. Reference. Nordal (1963).",GBIF,"PlantNet species_id: 965
Scientific name: Nymphaea rubra
Full species name: Nymphaea rubra Roxb. ex Andrews
Genus: Nymphaea
Family: Nymphaeaceae
IUCN status: LC
Accepted scientific name: Nymphaea rubra
GBIF description: Nymphaea rubra Roxb. ex Andrews Names. Myanmar: kya-ni. English: Indian red water-lily. Range. Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Vietnam. Common in warmer parts of Myanmar. Conservation status. Least Concern [LC] (IUCN 2017). Uses. Flower: Used as a blood purifier and febrifuge. Notes. The medicinal uses of this species in India are discussed in Jain and DeFilipps (1991) as follows: The flower is decocted and used for heart palpitations; the rootstock is powdered and used for piles, diarrhea, and dyspepsia. Perry (1980) discusses the uses of Nymphaea species in Indo-China and the Philippines. Reference. Nordal (1963).
Wikipedia summary: Nymphaea rubra is a species of waterlily native to the region spanning from Sri Lanka and northeastern India to western and central Malesia. Additionally, it has been introduced to regions such as Southeast China, Cuba, Guyana, Hungary, and Suriname.
Distribution: Assam; Bangladesh; Cambodia; China Southeast (INTRODUCED); Cuba (INTRODUCED); Guyana (INTRODUCED); Hungary (INTRODUCED); India; Jawa; Laos; Malaya; Mexico Southeast (INTRODUCED); Myanmar; Philippines; Sri Lanka; Suriname (INTRODUCED); Thailand; Vietnam; Global (PRESENT); Hungary [I]; China (Yunnan); Pakistan (Sind); India (almost throughout India); Sri Lanka; Bangladesh; Myanmar; Thailand; Laos; Cambodia; Vietnam; peninsular Malaysia; Java
